NOTOC__\n'''John A. Baker, Jr.''' (born December 19, 1988), better known by his stage name '''Spoken Reasons''', is an American actor, comedian, poet, and singer.\n\nBaker grew up in [[Bradenton, Florida]].<ref>[http://dalaughingbarrel.com/exclusive-comedian-to-watch-spoken-reasons-talks-new-deals-animosity-from-other-comedians-what-comedy-is-missing-and-more Exclusive - Comedian To Watch: Spoken Reasons Talks New Deals, Animosity From Other Comedians, What Comedy Is Missing, And More. | DaLaughingBarrel.Com - The Black Comedy Cent...<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> He began his career by creating a [[YouTube Channel]], which had, by August 2016, more than 1.9 million subscribers and over 280 million total views.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.youtube.com/user/SpokenReasons/about |title= Spoken Reasons: About |website= YouTube |publisher= Spoken Reasons|accessdate= 2016-08-20}}</ref>\n\nHe made his feature film debut in a supporting role in the [[20th Century Fox]] comedy, ''[[The Heat (film)|The Heat]]'', which opened on June 28, 2013.<ref>{{cite web |title= Paul Feig\u2019s \u2018The Heat\u2019 Adds Online Comic Spoken Reasons |author= Dominic Patten |url= https://tv.yahoo.com/news/paul-feig-heat-adds-online-comic-spoken-reasons-201650032.html |date= June 28, 2012 |accessdate= December 10, 2014}}</ref>\n\nBaker partnered with Russell Simmons' All Def Digital in 2013,<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.nbcbayarea.com/blogs/press-here/Producers-Looking-for-YouTube-Stars-for-New-Content-186209772.html |title= YOUTUBE Producers Want YouTube Stars for New Channels |last= Hernandez |first= Barbara |date= 9 January 2013 |website= NBC Bay Area |publisher= [[NBCUniversal]] Media |accessdate= December 10, 2014}}</ref> and worked with recording artist [[Russell Simmons]] and [[Priscilla Renea]].<ref>{{cite web |title= Spoken Reasons Invades Russell Simmons\u2019 Offices (VIDEO) |author= Lindsey India |url= http://globalgrind.com/entertainment/spoken-reasons-invades-russell-simmons-uncle-rush-offices-video |website= Global Grind |date= March 1, 2013 |accessdate= December 10, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last= Chmielewski |first= Dawn C. |date= January 8, 2013|title= CES 2013: Russell Simmons and Brian Robbins talk All Def Digital |url= http://articles.latimes.com/2013/jan/08/entertainment/la-et-ct-simmons-and-robbins-talk-add-20130108 |journal= [[Los Angeles Times]] |location= Los Angeles, CA |publisher= Tribune Publishing Company |accessdate= December 10, 2014 }}</ref> He appeared in the third season of [[Real Husbands of Hollywood]].{{citation needed|date=March 2016}}\n\n== Filmography/television ==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable jquery-tablesorter\"\n|+Actor\n!Year\n!Film<sup>[25]</sup>\n!Role<sup>[25]</sup>\n|-\n|2012\n|\"Relationship Games\" (Short Film)\n|Writer, Producer, Cinematography, Executive Producer, Mike\n|-\n|2013\n|\"Relationship Games\" 2 (Short Film)\n|Writer, Producer, Executive Producer, Mike\n|-\n|2013\n|\"Relationship Games\" 3 (Short Film)\n|Writer, Producer, Executive Producer, Mike \n|-\n|2013\n|''[[The Heat (film)|The Heat]]'' \n|Rojas\n|- \n|2013 -\n|''Relationship Games 4 (Short Film)''\n|Writer, Producer, Executive Producer, Mike\n|-\n|2013 -\n|'Adopted White Girl (Short Film)''\n|Writer, Director, Producer, Executive Producer, Uncle Earl, James\n|-\n|2014 \n|''Real Husbands of Hollywood''\n|Himself\n|- \n|2015 \n|''Sex & Friendship\" 1-2 (Short Film)\n|Writer, Director, Producer, Executive Producer, Kenny\n|-\n|2013 \u2013 15\n|''Dr. Reasons''\n|Dr. Reasons (All Def Digital Web series)  \n|-\n|2016 \n|\"Home From College\" (Short Film)\n|Writer, Director, Producer, Executive Producer, Cinematography, Justin\n|-\n|2018\n|\"Woke & Regular\" (Short Film)\n|Writer, Director, Producer, Executive Producer, Cinematography, Himself \n|-\n|2018 \n|\"Deal With The Devil\" - The Movie (Independent Feature)\n|Writer, Director, Producer, Executive Producer, Cinematography, Music, Himself\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{