{"title_page": "Anglophone Crisis", "text_new": "{{Infobox military conflict\n| conflict    = Anglophone Crisis\n| partof      = the [[Anglophone problem]]\n| image       = [[File:Map of the Federal Republic of Ambazonia (claimed).png|275px]]\n| image_size  = \n| caption     = {{legend0|#37c837|Undisputed Cameroonian territory}}<br/>{{legend0|#ff2a2a|Part of Cameroon claimed by Ambazonia}}\n| date        = September 9, 2017<ref name=\"Sept 13\"/> \u2013 present<br>({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=09|day1=09|year1=2017}})\n| place       = [[Northwest Region (Cameroon)|Northwest Region]] and [[Southwest Region (Cameroon)|Southwest Region]] ([[Southern Cameroons]]), [[Cameroon]]<br/><small>(With occasional spillover into [[Littoral Region (Cameroon)|Littoral Region]] and [[West Region (Cameroon)|West Region]])</small><ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroonanglophone-crisis-has-spilled-over-francophone-zones-sdf/ Cameroon:Anglophone crisis has spilled over Francophone zones-SDF] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181231205836/https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroonanglophone-crisis-has-spilled-over-francophone-zones-sdf/ |date=2018-12-31 }}, Journal du Cameroun, Dec 31, 2018. Accessed Dec 31, 2018.</ref>\n| territory   = \n| status      = [[List of ongoing armed conflicts|Ongoing]]\n| result      = \n| combatant1  = {{flag|Cameroon|size=22px}}\n| combatant2  = {{flag|Ambazonia|size=22px}}\n| commander1  = [[Paul Biya]]<br>[[Phil\u00e9mon Yang]]<br>[[Joseph Ngute]]<br>[[Ren\u00e9 Claude Meka]]<br/>[[Valere Nka]]\n| commander2  = [[Sisiku Julius Ayuk Tabe|Sisiku Ayuk Tabe]]<br>[[Samuel Ikome Sako]]<br>[[Ayaba Cho Lucas]]<br>[[Ebenezer Akwanga]]\n| units1      = [[Cameroon Armed Forces|FAC]]<br>Vigilante groups<ref name=\"xinhuavigilantes\">[http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2019-10/15/c_138473660.htm Cameroon sees more vigilante groups against insecurity in Anglophone regions], XinhuaNet, Oct 15, 2019. Accessed Oct 15, 2019.</ref>\n| units2      = [[Ambazonia Defence Forces|ADF]]<br>[[Southern Cameroons Defence Forces|SOCADEF]]<br>[[Ambazonia Self-Defence Council|ASC]]<br>[[List of Ambazonian militant groups|Other groups]]\n| strength1   = 12,500 troops, 9,000 militia <small>(total size of army)</small><ref name=\"autogenerated1\">International Institute for Strategic Studies. (2014). Chapter Ten: Country comparisons \u2013 commitments, force levels and economics. ''The Military Balance'', 114(1), 471\u2013492. doi:10.1080/04597222.2014.871887</ref>\n| strength2   = 2,000\u20134,000 fighters<br><small>(as of May 2019)</small><ref name=\"crisisgroupmay22019\"/>\n| casualties1 = 800-1,000 killed<br>{{small|(as of February 2020)}}<ref name=\"newhumanitarianfeb62020\">[https://www.thenewhumanitarian.org/news/2020/02/06/Cameroon-elections-anglophone-separatist-insurgency-Ambazonia Briefing: Cameroon's intensifying conflict and what it means for civilians], The New Humanitarian, Feb 6, 2020. Accessed Feb 8, 2020.</ref>\n| casualties2 = ~1,000 killed<br>{{small|(as of June 2019)}}<ref name=\"unfoldingcatastrophe\"/>\n| casualties3 = ~3,000 killed in total {{small|(as of September 2019)}}<ref name=\"3000killed\"/><br>679,000 internally displaced {{small|(as of January 2020)}}<ref name=\"reliefwebjan212020\">[https://reliefweb.int/sites/reliefweb.int/files/resources/20200121_acaps_short_note_escalation_of_the_anglophone_crisis_cameroon_0.pdf Escalation of the Anglophone crisis], ReliefWeb, Jan 21, 2020. Accessed Apr 12, 2020.</ref><br>51,000 refugees in Nigeria {{small|(as of January 2020)}}<ref name=\"reliefwebjan212020\">[https://reliefweb.int/sites/reliefweb.int/files/resources/20200121_acaps_short_note_escalation_of_the_anglophone_crisis_cameroon_0.pdf Escalation of the Anglophone crisis], ReliefWeb, Jan 21, 2020. Accessed Apr 12, 2020.</ref>\n| notes       = \n| campaignbox = {{Campaignbox Anglophone Crisis}}\n}}\n\nThe '''Anglophone Crisis''' ({{Lang-fr|Crise anglophone}}), also known as the '''Ambazonia War''',<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/ambazonia-war-drowns-sdf-28th-anniversary/ \u2018Ambazonia War\u2019 drowns SDF 28th Anniversary] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181025201919/https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/ambazonia-war-drowns-sdf-28th-anniversary/ |date=2018-10-25 }}, Journal du Cameroun, May 28, 2018. Accessed Oct 25, 2018.</ref> or the '''Cameroonian Civil War''',<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2018/10/06/world/africa/cameroon-election-biya-ambazonia.html Cameroon on Brink of Civil War as English Speakers Recount \u2018Unbearable\u2019 Horrors], The New York Times, Oct 6, 2018. Accessed Apr 27, 2019.</ref> is a conflict in the [[Southern Cameroons]] region of [[Cameroon]], part of the long-standing [[Anglophone problem]].<ref name=Africa>{{cite news|url=https://qz.com/1179202/cameroons-anglophone-crisis-is-threatening-to-spin-out-of-control/|title=Cameroon\u2019s Anglophone crisis is threatening to spin out of control|website=Quartz Africa|date=14 January 2018|accessdate=22 April 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180531194152/https://qz.com/1179202/cameroons-anglophone-crisis-is-threatening-to-spin-out-of-control/|archive-date=31 May 2018|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In September 2017, separatists in the [[English-speaking world|Anglophone]] territories of [[Northwest Region (Cameroon)|Northwest Region]] and [[Southwest Region (Cameroon)|Southwest Region]] (collectively known as Southern Cameroons) declared the independence of [[Ambazonia]] and began fighting against the [[Government of Cameroon]].<ref name=journal>{{cite news|url=https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/deadly-clashes-troops-adf-forces-leave-nguti-brink/|title=Deadly clashes between troops, ADF forces leave Nguti on the brink|website=Journal du Cameroun|date=13 March 2018|accessdate=22 April 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180421094808/https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/deadly-clashes-troops-adf-forces-leave-nguti-brink/|archive-date=21 April 2018|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}.</ref> Starting as a low-scale insurgency, the conflict spread to most parts of the Anglophone regions within a year.<ref name=\"acleddatapickingafight\"/> By the summer of 2019, the government controlled the major cities and parts of the countryside, while the separatists held parts of the countryside and regularly appeared in the major cities.<ref name=\"crisisgroupmay22019\"/>\n\nThe war has killed approximately 3,000 people<ref name=\"3000killed\"/> and forced more than half a million people to flee their homes.<ref name=\"crisisgroupmay22019\"/> Although 2019 has seen the first known instance of dialogue between Cameroon and the separatists,<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-ambazonia-leaders-agree-to-participate-in-swiss-led-dialogue/ Cameroon: Ambazonia leaders endorse Swiss-led dialogue to solve Anglophone crisis], Journal du Cameroun, Jun 28, 2019. Accessed Jun 28, 2019.</ref> as well as a [[Major National Dialogue|state-organized national dialogue]] and the granting of a special status to the Anglophone regions,<ref>[https://www.reuters.com/article/us-cameroon-separatists-lawmaking/cameroon-grants-special-status-to-anglophone-regions-idUSKBN1YO24S Cameroon grants special status to Anglophone regions], Reuters, Dec 20, 2019. Accessed Dec 22, 2019.</ref> the war continued to intensify in late 2019.<ref name=\"voasep242019\">[https://www.voanews.com/africa/cameroons-separatists-intensify-attacks-protest-dialogue Cameroon's Separatists Intensify Attacks to Protest Dialogue], Voice of America, Sep 24, 2019. Accessed Sep 26, 2019.</ref> The [[2020 Cameroonian parliamentary election]] brought further escalation, as the separatists became more assertive while Cameroon deployed additional forces. While the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] saw one armed group declare a unilateral ceasefire to combat the spread of [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]], other groups and the Cameroonian government ignored calls to follow suit and kept on fighting.<ref name=\"voaapr92020\"/>\n\n==Background==\n{{main|Ambazonia#History}}\n{{further|Bakassi conflict}}\n[[File:Monument in Limbe..JPG|thumb|left|Monument raised on the 150th anniversary of the establishment of Victoria at Ambas Bay, from which the name \"Ambazonia\" derives.]]\nThe name \"Ambazonia\" is taken from Ambas Bay and ''Ambozes'', the local name of the mouth of the [[Wouri River]].<ref name=\"Vine2004\">{{cite book|author=Victor T. Le Vine|title=Politics in Francophone Africa|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZVlzpwjhGqgC&pg=PA6|accessdate=9 May 2011|year=2004|publisher=Lynne Rienner Publishers|isbn=9781588262493|pages=6\u2013}}</ref> This is where the English language was permanently established for the first time in Southern Cameroons, when missionary [[Alfred Saker]] founded a settlement of freed slaves by [[Ambas Bay]] in 1858, which was later renamed Victoria (present-day [[Limbe, Cameroon|Limbe]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bakweri.org/2007/03/the_early_times.html|title=The Early Times in Victoria (Limbe)|publisher=|accessdate=26 October 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160307204612/http://www.bakweri.org/2007/03/the_early_times.html|archive-date=7 March 2016|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In 1884, the area became the British Ambas Bay Protectorate, with Victoria as its capital. Britain ceded the area to the [[German Empire|German]] territory of [[Kamerun]] in 1887. Germany had some trouble establishing control over the hinterlands of Victoria, and fought the [[Bafut Wars]] against local [[Fon (title)|fondoms]] until 1907.<ref>The Cameroon Tribune, No. 600, p. 2, December 26, 1996</ref>\n\nFollowing [[World War I]] and the [[Treaty of Versailles]], Kamerun was divided between a [[France|French]] and a British [[League of Nations Mandate]]. The French mandate was known as Cameroun, and comprised most of the former German territory. The British mandate was an elongated strip of land along the border of [[Colonial Nigeria]], consisting of Northern Cameroons and Southern Cameroons, including the historical Ambas Bay Protectorate. This territory was organized as [[British Cameroons]].<ref>Lee, Alexander, and Kenneth A. Schultz. ''Comparing British and French colonial legacies: A discontinuity analysis of Cameroon'', p. 10 APSA 2011 Annual Meeting Paper. 2011.</ref>\n\nThe British administered the territories through [[indirect rule]], allowing native authorities to administer the population according to their own traditions. In 1953, the Southern Cameroons delegation at a conference in London asked for a separate region. The British agreed, and Southern Cameroons became an autonomous region with its capital still at Buea. Elections were held in 1954 and the parliament met on 1 October 1954, with [[E. M. L. Endeley]] as Premier.<ref>DeLancey, Mark W., and Mark Dike DeLancey (2000): ''Historical Dictionary of the Republic of Cameroon'' (3rd ed.). Lanham, Maryland: The Scarecrow Press.</ref>\n\nThe United Nations organised a [[British Cameroons referendum, 1961|plebiscite in the region on 11 February 1961]] which put two alternatives to the people: union with Nigeria or union with Cameroon. The third option, independence, was opposed by the British representative to the UN Trusteeship Council, [[Andrew Cohen (statesman)|Sir Andrew Cohen]], and as a result was not listed. In the plebiscite, 60% of voters in the Northern Cameroons voted for union with Nigeria, while 70% of voters in the Southern Cameroons opted for union with Cameroon.<ref>Nohlen, D, Krennerich, M & Thibaut, B (1999) ''Elections in Africa: A data handbook'', p177 {{ISBN|0-19-829645-2}}</ref> The results owed partly to a fear of domination by much larger Nigeria.<ref>Amaazee, Victor Bong. ''The \u2018Igbo scare\u2019in the British Cameroons, c. 1945\u201361.'' The Journal of African History 31.2 (1990): 281\u2013293.</ref> Endeley was defeated in elections on 1 February 1959 by [[John Ngu Foncha]].<ref>{{cite book|author=Ndi, Anthony|title=Southern West Cameroon Revisited (1950\u20131972) Volume One: Unveiling Inescapable Traps|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hnIYAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA217|date=16 March 2014|publisher=Langaa RPCIG|isbn=978-9956-791-44-6|pages=217\u2013}}</ref>\n\nSouthern Cameroons became part of Cameroon on 1 October 1961 as \"West Cameroon\", with its own [[List of Prime Ministers of Cameroon|prime minister]]. However, the English-speaking peoples of the Southern Cameroons did not believe that they were fairly treated by the French-speaking government of the country. Then-president [[Ahmadou Ahidjo]] feared that Southern Cameroons would secede from the union, taking its natural resources with it. Following a French Cameroon [[Cameroonian constitutional referendum, 1972|unilateral referendum]] on 20 May 1972, a new constitution was adopted in Cameroon which replaced the [[Federal republic|federal]] state with a [[unitary state]], and also gave more power to the president.<ref>[http://africanelections.tripod.com/cm.html Elections in Cameroon] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110903053954/http://africanelections.tripod.com/cm.html |date=2011-09-03 }} African Elections Database</ref> Southern Cameroons lost its autonomous status and became the [[Northwest Region (Cameroon)|Northwest Region]] and the [[Southwest Region (Cameroon)|Southwest Region]] of the Republic of Cameroon. Pro-independence groups claimed that this violated the constitution, as the majority of deputies from West Cameroon had not consented to legitimize the constitutional changes.<ref>Roger, Jules, and Sombaye Eyango. ''Inside the Virtual Ambazonia: Separatism, Hate Speech, Disinformation and Diaspora in the Cameroonian Anglophone Crisis'', p. 28 (2018).</ref> They argued that Southern Cameroons had effectively been [[annexation|annexed]] by Cameroon.<ref>Anyangwe, Carlson. ''Betrayal of Too Trusting a People. The UN, the UK and the Trust Territory of the Southern Cameroons: The UN, the UK and the Trust Territory of the Southern Cameroons'', pp. 108\u2013111. African Books Collective, 2009.</ref> Shortly afterwards, French Cameroun's political leadership changed the constitution again, appointed French-speaking Paul Biya as Prime Minister and successor to Ahmadou Ahidjo ostensibly to deny the Speaker of the House of Assembly [[Salomon Tandeng Muna]] - an Anglophone the possibility of becoming president by succession.\n\nIn a memorandum dated 20 March 1985, Anglophone lawyer and President of the Cameroon Bar Association [[Fongum Gorji Dinka]] wrote that the Cameroonian government led by [[Paul Biya]] was unconstitutional and announced the former Southern Cameroons should become independent as the Republic of Ambazonia. Dinka was incarcerated the following January without trial.<ref>Nkwi; Nchoji, Paul (2015). The Anthropology of Africa: Challenges for the 21st Century (illustrated, reprint ed.), p. 478. Langaa RPCIG. {{ISBN|9789956792795}}.</ref> Three years later, he escaped to Nigeria.<ref>[https://www.ippmedia.com/en/features/cameroon%E2%80%99s-anglophone-war-part-1-rifle-only-way-out Cameroon's anglophone war, Part 1: A rifle as the only way out] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180709062633/https://www.ippmedia.com/en/features/cameroon%E2%80%99s-anglophone-war-part-1-rifle-only-way-out |date=2018-07-09 }}, IPP Media, Jul 9, 2018. Accessed Jul 9, 2018.</ref>\n\nIn 1993, representatives of Anglophone groups convened the first All Anglophone Conference (AAC1) in Buea. The conference issued the \"Buea Declaration\", which called for constitutional amendments to restore the 1961 federation. This was followed by the second All Anglophone Conference (AAC2) in [[Bamenda]] in 1994. This conference issued the \"Bamenda Declaration\", which stated that if the federal state was not restored within a reasonable time, Southern Cameroons would declare its independence. The AAC was renamed the Southern Cameroons Peoples Conference (SCPC), and later the Southern Cameroons Peoples Organisation (SCAPO), with the [[Southern Cameroons National Council]] (SCNC) as the executive governing body. Younger activists formed the Southern Cameroons Youth League (SCYL) in Buea on 28 May 1995. The SCNC sent a delegation, led by John Foncha, to the United Nations, which was received on 1 June 1995 and presented a petition against the 'annexation' of the Southern Cameroons by French Cameroon. This was followed by a signature referendum the same year, which the organisers claim produced a 99% vote in favour of independence with 315,000 people voting.<ref>[http://www.ambazania.org/referendum11.htm Southern Cameroons Peoples Organisation website] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927230920/http://www.ambazania.org/referendum11.htm |date=2007-09-27 }}</ref>\n\nSCNC activities were routinely disrupted by police.<ref name=Murison>{{cite book|title=Africa South of the Sahara 2004|year=2003|publisher=Europa Publications|pages=163\u2013164|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jj4J-AXGDaQC&pg=PA163|editor=Katharine Murison}}</ref> On March 23, 1997, about ten people were killed in a raid on a gendarme camp in [[Bamenda]]. The police arrested between 200 and 300 people, mostly SCNC supporters, but also members of the [[Social Democratic Front (Cameroon)|Social Democratic Front]], an opposition party with significant support in the Anglophone regions.<ref name=\"ecoi\">[https://www.ecoi.net/en/document/1056299.html March 1997 incidents in the north-west province CMR36066.E'], Immigration and Refugee Board of Canada, Jan 31, 2001. Accessed May 10, 2019.</ref> In the subsequent trials, [[Amnesty International]] and the SCNC found substantive evidence of admissions through torture and force.<ref name=Murison/> The raid and trial resulted in a shutdown of SCNC activities.<ref name=CQ>{{cite book|title=Political Handbook of the World 2016\u20132017|year=2017|publisher=CQ Press|pages=236\u2013246|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=UmNCDgAAQBAJ&pg=PA236|editor=Tom Lansdorf|chapter=Cameroon}}</ref> In response to this, in April 1998 a small faction elected Esoka Ndoki Mukete, a high-ranking member of the Social Democratic Front, as the new chair of the SCNC. In October 1999, when many of the accused were found guilty in the 1997 trial, the faction led by Mukete became more assertive. On 1 October 1999, militants took over Radio Buea to proclaim the independence of Southern Cameroons, but failed to do so before security forces intervened.<ref>Elong, Eric Ebolo. ''Sovereignty in the Making: The Case of Anglophone Cameroon. 2'', p. 24</ref> The leadership and many members of the SCNC were subsequently arrested.<ref name=CQ/> After clashes with the police, the SCNC was officially declared illegal by the Cameroonian authorities in 2001.<ref>[http://www.thenewhumanitarian.org/news/2007/02/19/secessionist-minority-anglophone-group-silenced Secessionist minority Anglophone group silenced], The New Humanitarian, Feb 19, 2007. Accessed Oct 27, 2019.</ref> In 2006, a faction of SCNC once again declared the independence of Ambazonia.<ref name=CQ>{{cite book|title=Political Handbook of the World 2016\u20132017|year=2017|publisher=CQ Press|pages=236\u2013246|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=UmNCDgAAQBAJ&pg=PA236|editor=Tom Lansdorf|chapter=Cameroon}}</ref>\n\nIn 2006, Nigeria ceded the [[Bakassi|Bakassi Peninsula]] to Cameroon, ending a decade-long territorial dispute. Local militias opposing the border change took up arms against the Cameroonian government, starting the [[Bakassi conflict]]. The conflict was a sea-based insurgency where the rebels used pirate tactics, attacking ships, abducting sailors and carrying out seaborne raids as far away as [[Limbe, Cameroon|Limbe]] and [[Douala]]. While some movements (such as [[Bakassi Movement for Self-Determination|BAMOSD]]) sought to make Bakassi an independent state, others came to tie their cause to that of Ambazonia. In November 2007, the \"Liberators of the Southern Cameroon People\", a previously unknown group, killed 21 Cameroonian soldiers. Most militias in Bakassi laid down their arms in September 2009.<ref name=\"bakassi\">[https://www.refworld.org/docid/4cf4dafc2.html Cameroon Rebels Threaten Security in Oil-Rich Gulf of Guinea] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190329001435/https://www.refworld.org/docid/4cf4dafc2.html |date=2019-03-29 }}, Ref World, Nov 24, 2010. Accessed Mar 28, 2019.</ref>\n\n== Prelude ==\n{{main|2016\u20132017 Cameroonian protests}}\nOn October 6, 2016, the [[Cameroon Anglophone Civil Society Consortium]], an organization consisting of lawyer and teacher trade unions in the Anglophone regions, initiated a strike.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-cameroon-protests/trial-over-cameroons-anglophone-protests-exposes-national-divide-idUSKBN15S1UH|title=Trial over Cameroon's Anglophone protests exposes national divide|last=|first=|date=13 February 2017|work=Reuters|access-date=2017-09-13|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170908155639/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-cameroon-protests/trial-over-cameroons-anglophone-protests-exposes-national-divide-idUSKBN15S1UH|archive-date=8 September 2017|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Led by Barrister [[Agbor Balla]], [[Fontem Neba]], and Tassang Wilfred, they were protesting against the appointment of [[French language|Francophone]] judges in the Anglophone regions.<ref>{{cite web|title=Rights groups call for probe into protesters' deaths in Cameroon|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2016/12/15/world/cameroon-protesters-deaths/index.html|website=CNN|access-date=2019-03-05|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170829213619/http://edition.cnn.com/2016/12/15/world/cameroon-protesters-deaths/index.html|archive-date=2017-08-29|url-status=dead|df=}}</ref> They saw this as threatening the [[common law]] system in the Anglophone regions,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://qz.com/845783/cameroon-protests-are-growing-over-the-anglophone-francophone-split/|title=Mass protests in Cameroon are exposing the fragility of its dual French-English system|publisher=|access-date=2019-03-05|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180625021637/https://qz.com/845783/cameroon-protests-are-growing-over-the-anglophone-francophone-split/|archive-date=2018-06-25|url-status=dead|df=}}</ref> as well as part of the general marginalization of Anglophones.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newsweek.com/cameroon-anglophone-problem-paul-biya-556151|title=What you need to know about Cameroon's Anglophone protests|date=13 February 2017|publisher=|access-date=5 March 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190402111124/https://www.newsweek.com/cameroon-anglophone-problem-paul-biya-556151|archive-date=2 April 2019|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The strikes were supported by peaceful protests in the cities of [[Bamenda]], [[Buea]] and [[Limbe, Cameroon|Limbe]]. The activists demanded protection of the law system of the Anglophone regions, and opposed the civil law system used by the Francophone magistrate replacing the common law system. They asked for several laws to be translated into English, and that the common law system should be taught at the [[University of Buea]] and the [[University of Bamenda]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://contranocendi.org/index.php/en/news/88-anglophone-cameroon-common-law-lawyers-protest|title=Anglophone Cameroon Common Law Lawyers Protest \u2013 Contra Nocendi International|last=|first=|date=|website=contranocendi.org|language=en-gb|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170903035849/http://contranocendi.org/index.php/en/news/88-anglophone-cameroon-common-law-lawyers-protest|archive-date=2017-09-03|url-status=dead|access-date=2017-09-13|df=}}</ref>\n\nThe Cameroonian government deployed security forces to crack down the protests. Protesters were attacked with tear gas, and protesters and lawyers were allegedly assaulted by soldiers.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.stopblablacam.com/culture-and-society/1511-199-two-anglophone-lawyers-beaten-up-in-buea|title=(True or False?) Two Anglophone lawyers beaten up in Buea \u2013 StopBlaBlaCam|last=|first=|date=|work=StopBlaBlaCam|access-date=2017-09-13|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170903032428/http://www.stopblablacam.com/culture-and-society/1511-199-two-anglophone-lawyers-beaten-up-in-buea|archive-date=2017-09-03|url-status=dead|language=en-gb|df=}}</ref> Throughout November 2016, thousands of teachers in the Anglophone regions joined the lawyers' strike. All schools in the Anglophone regions were shut down.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2016/12/cameroon-teachers-lawyers-strike-english-161205095929616.html|title=Cameroon teachers, lawyers strike in battle for English|website=www.aljazeera.com|access-date=2017-09-13|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170912143932/http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2016/12/cameroon-teachers-lawyers-strike-english-161205095929616.html|archive-date=2017-09-12|url-status=dead|df=}}</ref>\n\nTwo weeks into the protests, more than 100 protesters had been arrested, and six were reported dead. Unconfirmed videos released over social media showed various violent scenes, including the beating of protesters by policemen.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-38078238|title=Arrests in Cameroon language protests|date=2016-11-23|work=BBC News|access-date=2017-09-13|language=en-GB|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170911183649/http://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-38078238|archive-date=2017-09-11|url-status=dead|df=}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2017, the Cameroonian government set up a committee to initiate a dialogue with the lawyer activists. The lawyers refused to talk, demanding that all arrested activists be released before any dialogue. The lawyers submitted a draft for a federal state, and the government responded by banning their movements altogether. The protesters were now openly regarded as a security threat by the Cameroonian government, and more arrests followed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://thestandardtribune.com/2017/01/17/the-government-just-banned-scnc-and-consortium/|title=The Government Just Banned SCNC and Consortium \u2039 The Standard Tribune|website=thestandardtribune.com|language=en-US|access-date=2017-09-13|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170903034357/http://thestandardtribune.com/2017/01/17/the-government-just-banned-scnc-and-consortium/|archive-date=2017-09-03|url-status=dead|df=}}</ref> The government also implemented an Internet blockade in cities across the Anglophone regions.<ref name=\":11\">{{Cite web|url=http://pctechmag.com/2017/01/just-in-internet-blocked-in-bamenda-regions-of-cameroon/|title=JUST IN: Internet Blocked in Bamenda Regions of Cameroon|last=|first=|date=January 18, 2016|website=pctechmag.com|publisher=|access-date=January 18, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170120103538/http://pctechmag.com/2017/01/just-in-internet-blocked-in-bamenda-regions-of-cameroon/|archive-date=January 20, 2017|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nAt this point, the crisis began to attract international responses. More than 13,000 Anglophone Cameroonians living in Maryland protested against the Cameroonian government crackdown. On June 27, United States Congressman [[Anthony G. Brown]] filed a petition with the [[United States Secretary of State]], [[Rex Tillerson]], to call for the government of Cameroon to immediately show concern and solve the ongoing crises.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://journalducameroun.com/en/anglophone-protests-pressure-united-states-congress/|title=Anglophone protests: More pressure from United States\u2019 congress|last=|first=|date=2017-06-27|work=Journal du Cameroun|access-date=2017-09-13|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170905141504/http://journalducameroun.com/en/anglophone-protests-pressure-united-states-congress/|archive-date=2017-09-05|url-status=dead|language=en-US|df=}}</ref> The [[United States]] condemned the loss of life and brutality against Anglophone protesters.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://cameroon-concord.com/headlines/7378-cameroon-strike-the-united-stares-expresses-concern-over-the-loss-of-life-and-brutality-against-anglophone-protesters|title=Cameroon Strike: The United States expresses concern over the loss of life and brutality against anglophone protesters|work=Cameroon Concord|access-date=2017-09-13|language=en-gb|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170905143801/http://cameroon-concord.com/headlines/7378-cameroon-strike-the-united-stares-expresses-concern-over-the-loss-of-life-and-brutality-against-anglophone-protesters|archive-date=2017-09-05|url-status=dead|df=}}</ref>\n\nThe government crackdown on the protests contributed to mainstream separatist movements. In September 2017, Ambazonian separatists began to take up arms against the government.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dw.com/en/english-speakers-protest-in-cameroon-demand-equal-rights-amid-calls-for-secession/a-40649852|title=English speakers protest in Cameroon, demand equal rights amid calls for secession \u2013 News \u2013 DW \u2013 22.09.2017|first=Deutsche Welle|last=(www.dw.com)|website=DW.COM|access-date=2019-03-05|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180125091747/http://www.dw.com/en/english-speakers-protest-in-cameroon-demand-equal-rights-amid-calls-for-secession/a-40649852|archive-date=2018-01-25|url-status=dead|df=}}</ref>\n\n==Timeline==\n\n{{Main|Timeline of the Anglophone Crisis}}\n\n===2017===\n\n{{Main|Timeline of the Anglophone Crisis (2017)}}\n\nIn early September, 2017, the [[Ambazonia Governing Council]] (AGovC), a separatist movement established in 2013 through the merger of several groups,<ref name=\"crisisgroupmay22019\"/> formally deployed the [[Ambazonia Defence Forces]] (ADF) in Southern Cameroons. On September 9, the ADF carried out its first military action, attacking a military base in Besongabang, [[Manyu (department)|Manyu]]. Three Cameroonian soldiers were killed in the attack, while the ADF claimed their soldiers managed to return to base unreduced.<ref name=\"Sept 13\">[https://www.dailynewscameroon.com/breaking-news-explosions-in-bamenda-and-killings-in-besongabang-military-base-adf-claims-responsibility/ Explosions in Bamenda and Killings in Besongabang Military Base, ADF Claims Responsibility] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191223171302/https://www.dailynewscameroon.com/breaking-news-explosions-in-bamenda-and-killings-in-besongabang-military-base-adf-claims-responsibility/ |date=2019-12-23 }}, Daily News Cameroon, Sept 14, 2017. Accessed Apr 19, 2018.</ref> Throughout September, separatists carried out two bombings; one targeting security forces in [[Bamenda]],<ref>[https://qz.com/1084943/cameroons-anglophone-crisis-turns-violent-as-president-paul-biya-speak-at-unga-2017/ The crisis in Cameroon\u2019s English-speaking regions has turned violent with bombings] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180419183806/https://qz.com/1084943/cameroons-anglophone-crisis-turns-violent-as-president-paul-biya-speak-at-unga-2017/ |date=2018-04-19 }}, Quartz, Sept 22, 2017. Accessed Apr 19, 2018.</ref> and another targeting police officers. While the first bombing failed, the second injured three policemen.<ref>[https://www.reuters.com/article/us-cameroon-politics-blast/suspected-separatist-bomb-wounds-3-police-in-cameroons-anglophone-region-idUSKCN1BW2C9 Suspected separatist bomb wounds 3 police in Cameroon's Anglophone region] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180419183403/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-cameroon-politics-blast/suspected-separatist-bomb-wounds-3-police-in-cameroons-anglophone-region-idUSKCN1BW2C9 |date=2018-04-19 }}, Reuters, Sept 21, 2017. Accessed Apr 19, 2018.</ref> On September 22, Cameroonian soldiers opened fire on protesters, killing at least five and injuring many more.<ref name=\"22Sep\">{{cite news|url=https://qz.com/1086706/cameroon-is-on-edge-after-security-forces-opened-fire-on-anglophone-region-protesters/|title=Cameroon is on edge after security forces opened fire on Anglophone protesters|website=Quartz Africa|date=22 September 2017|accessdate=10 May 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180419183909/https://qz.com/1086706/cameroon-is-on-edge-after-security-forces-opened-fire-on-anglophone-region-protesters/|archive-date=19 April 2018|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Street of Buea (SW Region Cameroon) on a Ghost town day 2.jpg|thumb|right|Streets of Buea on a ghost town day, September 30.]]\n\nOn October 1, the [[Southern Cameroons Ambazonia Consortium United Front]] (SCACUF), an umbrella movement consisting of several independence movements, unilaterally declared the independence of Ambazonia. This declaration was followed by mass demonstrations across the Anglophone regions. The separatists strategically chose this date, as it is the anniversary for the unification of Cameroon and Southern Cameroons. SCACUF would later transform itself into the [[Interim Government of Ambazonia]] (IG). Several months into the war, the IG would reject the idea of an armed struggle, preferring instead a diplomatic campaign and [[civil disobedience]]. This stance would eventually change.<ref>[https://allafrica.com/stories/201712220550.html Cameroon: Anglophone Crisis - Dialogue Remains the Only Viable Solution], AllAfrica, Dec 7, 2017. Accessed Mar 9, 2019.</ref>\n\nThe Cameroonian Army moved into the regions in force to fight the separatists and quell the demonstrations. Throughout the day, at least eight demonstrators were killed in [[Buea]] and Bamenda.<ref name=\"2 Oct\">{{cite news|url=https://www.euractiv.com/section/languages-culture/news/several-killed-in-cameroon-as-anglophones-declare-independent-ambazonia/|title=Several killed in Cameroon as anglophones declare \u2018independent Ambazonia\u2019|website=Euractiv|date=2 October 2017|accessdate=10 May 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180420074508/https://www.euractiv.com/section/languages-culture/news/several-killed-in-cameroon-as-anglophones-declare-independent-ambazonia/|archive-date=20 April 2018|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The Cameroonian military also reinforced the Nigerian border, and on October 9, it claimed to have stopped \"hundreds of Nigerian fighters\" from crossing into Cameroon.<ref>[http://www.dw.com/en/cameroonian-troops-deploy-heavily-along-nigeria-border/a-40877538 Cameroonian troops deploy heavily along Nigeria border] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180420074620/http://www.dw.com/en/cameroonian-troops-deploy-heavily-along-nigeria-border/a-40877538 |date=2018-04-20 }}, DW, Oct 9, 2017. Accessed Apr 20, 2018.</ref>\n\nThroughout November, eight soldiers, at least 14 civilians and five fugitives were confirmed killed due to the conflict.<ref name=\"Nov 29\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nation.co.ke/news/africa/4-Cameroon-soldiers-killed/1066-4207694-10cknvr/index.html|title=Four Cameroon soldiers killed in restive Anglophone region|website=Daily Nation|date=29 November 2017|accessdate=5 May 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180421095229/https://www.nation.co.ke/news/africa/4-Cameroon-soldiers-killed/1066-4207694-10cknvr/index.html|archive-date=21 April 2018|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Separatists killed two [[Gendarmerie|gendarmes]] in Bamenda in the first week of the month.<ref>[https://www.reuters.com/article/us-cameroon-politics/cameroon-separatists-kill-at-least-two-gendarmes-as-anglophone-dispute-escalates-idUSKBN1D81PH Cameroon separatists kill at least two gendarmes as Anglophone dispute escalates] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180421030447/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-cameroon-politics/cameroon-separatists-kill-at-least-two-gendarmes-as-anglophone-dispute-escalates-idUSKBN1D81PH |date=2018-04-21 }}, Reuters, Nov 8, 2017. Accessed Apr 20, 2018.</ref> On the last two days of November, five soldiers and five policemen were killed in two separate separatist attacks near [[Mamfe]].<ref name=\"voanov302017\">[https://www.voanews.com/africa/five-police-five-soldiers-killed-cameroon-violence Five Police, Five Soldiers Killed in Cameroon Violence], Voice of America, Nov 30, 2017. Accessed Nov 17, 2019.</ref> On December 1, the Cameroonian government ordered the evacuation of 16 villages in Manyu ahead of a military offensive,<ref>[https://ewn.co.za/2017/12/07/cameroon-govt-forces-accused-of-murder-rape Cameroon govt forces accused of murder, rape] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180825180008/https://ewn.co.za/2017/12/07/cameroon-govt-forces-accused-of-murder-rape |date=2018-08-25 }}, Eyewitness News. Accessed Aug 25, 2018.</ref> and on December 4 it formally declared war on the separatists.<ref name=\"Dec 4\">[https://www.irinnews.org/analysis/2017/12/04/cameroon-government-declares-war-secessionist-rebels Cameroon government \u2018declares war\u2019 on secessionist rebels] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180421162931/https://www.irinnews.org/analysis/2017/12/04/cameroon-government-declares-war-secessionist-rebels |date=2018-04-21 }}, Irin, Dec 4, 2017. Accessed Apr 21, 2018.</ref> The Cameroonian Army moved into Manyu, retaking two villages on December 7<ref>[https://www.voanews.com/a/cameroon-military-moves-in-on-separatist-held-villages-/4153553.html Cameroon's Military Moves In on Separatist-held Villages] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180421094649/https://www.voanews.com/a/cameroon-military-moves-in-on-separatist-held-villages-/4153553.html |date=2018-04-21 }}, Voice of America, Dec 7, 2017. Accessed Apr 21, 2018.</ref> and securing Mamfe by December 15, partly with elite troops.<ref>[http://cameroonnewsagency.com/days-sporadic-gun-shots-mamfe-relative-calm-returns-massive-exodus/ After Days of Sporadic Gun Shots In Mamfe: Relative Calm Returns, Massive Exodus] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181125115427/http://cameroonnewsagency.com/days-sporadic-gun-shots-mamfe-relative-calm-returns-massive-exodus/ |date=2018-11-25 }}, Cameroon News Agency, December 15, 2017. Accessed Nov 24, 2018.</ref> During the offensive, the ADF carried out guerrilla attacks on the Cameroonian Army,<ref>[https://www.voanews.com/a/separatists-attack-cameroon-police/4156497.html Separatists Attack Cameroon Police] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180421162751/https://www.voanews.com/a/separatists-attack-cameroon-police/4156497.html |date=2018-04-21 }}, Voice of America, Dec 9, 2017. Accessed Apr 21, 2018.</ref> killing at least seven soldiers throughout December.<ref name=\"jan62018\">[http://cameroon-concord.com/boko-haram/anglophone-crisis-seven-military-personnel-murdered-in-december-icg-says Anglophone Crisis \u2013 Seven military personnel murdered in December \u2013 ICG says] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180704203403/http://cameroon-concord.com/boko-haram/anglophone-crisis-seven-military-personnel-murdered-in-december-icg-says |date=2018-07-04 }}, Cameroon Concord, Jan 6, 2018. Accessed Aug 25, 2018.</ref> On December 18, the Cameroonian Army began to destroy dozens of civilian homes in retaliation, and killed several civilians.<ref name=\"jan62018\">[http://cameroon-concord.com/boko-haram/anglophone-crisis-seven-military-personnel-murdered-in-december-icg-says Anglophone Crisis \u2013 Seven military personnel murdered in December \u2013 ICG says] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180704203403/http://cameroon-concord.com/boko-haram/anglophone-crisis-seven-military-personnel-murdered-in-december-icg-says |date=2018-07-04 }}, Cameroon Concord, Jan 6, 2018. Accessed Aug 25, 2018.</ref> The December offensive also saw occasional spillover across the Nigerian border.<ref name=\"Dec 20\">[https://www.reuters.com/article/us-cameroon-separatists-nigeria/exclusive-cameroonian-troops-entered-nigeria-without-seeking-authorization-sources-in-nigeria-say-idUSKBN1EE2II Cameroonian troops entered Nigeria without seeking authorization, sources in Nigeria say] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180421094816/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-cameroon-separatists-nigeria/exclusive-cameroonian-troops-entered-nigeria-without-seeking-authorization-sources-in-nigeria-say-idUSKBN1EE2II |date=2018-04-21 }}, Reuters, Dec 20, 2017. Accessed Apr 21, 2018.</ref>\n\nBy the end of 2017, several separatist militias had emerged, with the ADF standing out as the most prominent one.<ref name=\"forces\">[https://www.nation.co.ke/news/africa/The-Cameroon-English-speaking-separatists/1066-4312292-omwos6/index.html Who are Cameroon's English-speaking separatists?] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180423042915/https://www.nation.co.ke/news/africa/The-Cameroon-English-speaking-separatists/1066-4312292-omwos6/index.html |date=2018-04-23 }}, Daily Nation, Feb 20, 2018. Accessed Apr 22, 2018.</ref> During the guerrilla campaign in [[Manyu (department)|Manyu]] and [[Mezam]], it had clashed with the army 13 times.<ref name=\"BBCoct42018\"/> The separatists had also spread out, and by the end of the year, they were active in five [[Departments of Cameroon|departments]].<ref name=\"acleddatapickingafight\">[https://www.acleddata.com/2018/09/21/picking-a-fight-the-rise-of-armed-separatists-in-cameroon/ Picking a Fight: The Rise of Armed Separatists in Cameroon], ACLED. Accessed Nov 17, 2018.</ref>\n\n===2018===\n\n{{Main|Timeline of the Anglophone Crisis (2018)}}\n\nThe separatists suffered a major setback at the beginning of 2018. On January 5, members of the Ambazonia Interim Government were detained by Nigerian authorities,<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/jan/07/cameroon-separatist-leader-julius-ayuk-tabe-detained-in-nigeria Cameroon separatist leader detained in Nigeria as unrest grows] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180407165046/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/jan/07/cameroon-separatist-leader-julius-ayuk-tabe-detained-in-nigeria |date=2018-04-07 }}. The Guardian, Jan 7, 2018. Accessed Apr 19, 2018.</ref> which proceeded to hand them over to Cameroon. A total of 69 leaders and activists were [[Extradition|extradited]] to Cameroon and subsequently arrested, including [[President of Ambazonia|President]] [[Sisiku Julius Ayuk Tabe]]. Since most of the individuals had submitted asylum claims,<ref name=\"leadership UNPO\">{{cite news|url=http://unpo.org/article/20701|title=Ambazonia: Nigeria Hands over 47 Asylum-seekers to Cameroonian Authorities|website=UNPO|date=26 March 2018|accessdate=10 May 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180505144624/http://unpo.org/article/20701|archive-date=5 May 2018|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> the deportation immediately became controversial, as it possibly violated the Nigerian constitution.<ref name=\"journalducameroun.com\">[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-ambazonia-leaders-appear-before-judge-at-military-tribunal/ Cameroon: Ambazonia leaders appear before judge at military tribunal] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190415183927/https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-ambazonia-leaders-appear-before-judge-at-military-tribunal/ |date=2019-04-15 }}, Journal du Cameroun, Nov 28, 2018. Accessed Jan 13, 2019.</ref> They spent 10 months at a [[Gendarmerie|gendarme]] headquarters, before being transferred to a maximum security prison in [[Yaound\u00e9]].<ref name=\"journalducameroun.com\"/> [[Samuel Ikome Sako]] was announced as Acting President on February 4, replacing Tabe for the time being.<ref name=\"Sako\">[http://cameroonnewsagency.com/just-dr-samuel-ikome-sako-new-acting-interim-president-federal-republic-ambazonia/ Just In-Dr Samuel Ikome Sako Is New Acting Interim President of The \u2018Federal Republic of Ambazonia\u2019] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180419193452/http://cameroonnewsagency.com/just-dr-samuel-ikome-sako-new-acting-interim-president-federal-republic-ambazonia/ |date=2018-04-19 }}, Cameroon News Agency, Feb 4, 2018. Accessed Apr 19, 2018.</ref>\n\nJanuary saw an escalation in guerrilla attacks on symbolic targets,<ref>[http://cameroonnewsagency.com/tension-bangem-administrative-authorities-held-gunmen/ Tension In Bangem, Administrative Authorities Held By Gunmen] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181125073958/http://cameroonnewsagency.com/tension-bangem-administrative-authorities-held-gunmen/ |date=2018-11-25 }}, Cameroon News Agency, Jan 29, 2018. Accessed Nov 24, 2018.</ref> as well as repeated spillover into Nigeria.<ref>[https://www.reuters.com/article/us-cameroon-separatists-nigeria/gunmen-cross-from-nigeria-attack-cameroon-border-post-witnesses-idUSKBN1FE1LH Gunmen cross from Nigeria, attack Cameroon border post: witnesses] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180829072118/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-cameroon-separatists-nigeria/gunmen-cross-from-nigeria-attack-cameroon-border-post-witnesses-idUSKBN1FE1LH |date=2018-08-29 }}, Reuters, Jan 25, 2018. Accessed Aug 28, 2018.</ref> The separatists began to target traditional village chiefs, as well as local administrators whom they accused of siding with the security forces.<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/local-chief-murdered-mundemba-separatists/ Local chief murdered in Mundemba by separatists] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180717013218/https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/local-chief-murdered-mundemba-separatists/ |date=2018-07-17 }}, Journal du Cameroun, Feb 12, 2018. Accessed Jul 16, 2018.</ref> Attacks on gendarmes intensified,<ref name=\"thursfeb1\">[https://www.reuters.com/article/us-cameroon-separatists-france/france-condemns-killings-in-cameroon-urges-dialogue-idUSKBN1FM1VL France condemns killings in Cameroon, urges dialogue] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180709153706/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-cameroon-separatists-france/france-condemns-killings-in-cameroon-urges-dialogue-idUSKBN1FM1VL |date=2018-07-09 }}, Reuters, Feb 2, 2018. Accessed Jul 9, 2018.</ref> and gunmen also began to target schools to enforce a school boycott.<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/primary-chool-teacher-slaughtered-suspected-separatists-etam/ Head teacher slaughtered by suspected separatists in Etam] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180825180056/https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/primary-chool-teacher-slaughtered-suspected-separatists-etam/ |date=2018-08-25 }}, Journal du Cameroun, Feb 21, 2018. Accessed Aug 25, 2018.</ref> On February 24, separatists abducted the government's regional representative for social affairs in the [[Northwest Region (Cameroon)|Northwest Region]], apparently looking to exchange him for imprisoned separatist activists.<ref>[http://www.janes.com/article/78199/kidnapping-of-government-officials-highlights-risks-to-companies-in-cameroon-s-anglophone-regions-deemed-to-be-unfairly-exploiting-resources Kidnapping of government officials highlights risks to companies in Cameroon\u2019s Anglophone regions deemed to be unfairly exploiting resources] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180421094911/http://www.janes.com/article/78199/kidnapping-of-government-officials-highlights-risks-to-companies-in-cameroon-s-anglophone-regions-deemed-to-be-unfairly-exploiting-resources |date=2018-04-21 }}, Janes' 360, Feb 27, 2018. Accessed Apr 21, 2018.</ref>\n\nThe [[Battle of Batibo]] was fought on March 3,<ref>[http://www.cameroonpostline.com/3-villages-razed-in-batibo-4-deserted-after-bloody-attack-collateral-casualties-overwhelmed-local-administrators/ 3 Villages Razed In Batibo, 4 Deserted After Bloody Attack *Collateral Casualties Overwhelmed Local Administrators] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180901151211/http://www.cameroonpostline.com/3-villages-razed-in-batibo-4-deserted-after-bloody-attack-collateral-casualties-overwhelmed-local-administrators/ |date=2018-09-01 }}, Cameroon Postline, Mar 9, 2018. Accessed Sep 1, 2018.</ref> producing unprecedented casualties on both sides<ref name=\"mar202018\">[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/security-forces-rescue-three-hostages-ambazonia-fighters/ Security forces rescue three hostages from Ambazonia fighters] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180825180111/https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/security-forces-rescue-three-hostages-ambazonia-fighters/ |date=2018-08-25 }}, Journal du Cameroun, Mar 20, 2018. Accessed Aug 25, 2018.</ref> and forcing over 4,000 locals to flee.<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/4000-persons-batibo-displaced-deadly-clashes-gunmen-security-forces/ 4000 persons in Batibo displaced after deadly clashes between gunmen and security forces] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180825180050/https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/4000-persons-batibo-displaced-deadly-clashes-gunmen-security-forces/ |date=2018-08-25 }}, Journal du Cameroun, Mar 8, 2018. Accessed Aug 25, 2018.</ref> On March 20, Cameroonian soldiers freed two Cameroonian and one Tunisian hostage in [[Meme (department)|Meme Department]].<ref name=\"mar202018\"/> A similar operation freed seven Swiss, six Cameroonian and five Italian hostages on April 4, prompting the [[Ambazonia Defence Forces|ADF]] to declare that it did not take hostages nor target foreigners.<ref>[https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-43640886 Cameroon frees European hostages taken in Anglophone area] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180703054329/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-43640886 |date=2018-07-03 }}, BBC, Apr 4, 2018. Accessed Apr 28, 2018.</ref> On April 25, separatists forced the Cameroonian Army to retreat from the town of [[Belo, Cameroon|Belo]].<ref>[http://www.africanews.com/2018/04/27/cameroon-separatists-force-army-to-retreat-after-face-off-in-northwest/ Cameroon separatists force army to retreat after face off in Northwest] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180427100748/http://www.africanews.com/2018/04/27/cameroon-separatists-force-army-to-retreat-after-face-off-in-northwest// |date=2018-04-27 }}, Africa News, Apr 27, 2018. Accessed Apr 27, 2018.</ref>\n\nThroughout May, there were heavy clashes in [[Mbonge]]<ref name=\"2May\">{{cite news|url=http://cameroon-concord.com/boko-haram/anglophone-crisis-three-soldiers-killed-in-mbonge|title=Anglophone Crisis: Three soldiers killed in Mbonge|website=Cameroon Concord|date=3 May 2018|accessdate=10 May 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180507045116/http://www.cameroon-concord.com/boko-haram/anglophone-crisis-three-soldiers-killed-in-mbonge|archive-date=7 May 2018|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> and [[Muyuka]], resulting in heavy casualties.<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/travellers-stranded-deadly-clashes-muyuka/ Travellers stranded after deadly clashes in Muyuka] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180620124820/https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/travellers-stranded-deadly-clashes-muyuka/ |date=2018-06-20 }}, Journal du Cameroun, May 7, 2018. Accessed Jun 20, 2018.</ref> On May 20, in an effort to boycott celebrations of Cameroon's [[National Day (Cameroon)|National Day]], Ambazonian forces struck in several villages throughout Southern Cameroons, including [[Konye, Cameroon|Konye]], [[Batibo]] and Ekona,<ref name=\"May20\">[http://www.janes.com/article/80201/fighting-attacks-on-timber-and-fuel-trucks-in-anglophone-cameroon-likely-to-rise-shortly-before-october-elections Fighting, attacks on timber and fuel trucks in Anglophone Cameroon likely to rise shortly before October elections] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180523011733/http://www.janes.com/article/80201/fighting-attacks-on-timber-and-fuel-trucks-in-anglophone-cameroon-likely-to-rise-shortly-before-october-elections |date=2018-05-23 }}, Jane's 360, May 21, 2018. Accessed May 22, 2018.</ref> and abducted the mayor of the town of [[Bangem]].<ref>[http://allafrica.com/stories/201805210260.html Cameroon: Killings, Kidnappings Mars National Day Celebrations ] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180521103447/http://allafrica.com/stories/201805210260.html |date=2018-05-21 }}, allAfrica, May 21, 2018. Accessed May 21, 2018.</ref> On May 24, Cameroonian soldiers killed at least 30 people while storming a hotel in Pinyin.<ref>[https://www.voanews.com/a/dozens-of-cameroon-youth-killed-in-south/4411815.html Dozens of Cameroon Youth Killed in South] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180527194114/https://www.voanews.com/a/dozens-of-cameroon-youth-killed-in-south/4411815.html |date=2018-05-27 }}, Voanews, May 27, 2018. Accessed May 27, 2018.</ref> By the end of May, Cameroon had also retaken Belo, though fighting continued around the town, which was almost completely abandoned by its inhabitants.<ref name=thisisagenocide>[https://www.theguardian.com/global-development/2018/may/30/cameroon-killings-escalate-anglophone-crisis 'This is a genocide': villages burn as war rages in blood-soaked Cameroon] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180601174340/https://www.theguardian.com/global-development/2018/may/30/cameroon-killings-escalate-anglophone-crisis |date=2018-06-01 }}, The Guardian, May 20, 2018. Accessed Jun 1, 2018.</ref>\n\nIn mid-June, Ambazonian forces started a blockade of the [[Kumba]]-[[Buea]] highway at Ekona, a town located approximately 10 kilometers from Buea. A military assault on the separatists in Ekona failed to lift the blockade.<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/hold-kumba-buea-highway-leaves-passengers-stranded/ Hold up on Kumba-Buea highway leaves passengers stranded] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180624035717/https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/hold-kumba-buea-highway-leaves-passengers-stranded/ |date=2018-06-24 }}, Journal du Cameroun, Jun 18, 2018. Accessed Jun 23, 2018.</ref> While casualties related to the battle of Ekona remain unconfirmed, the Cameroonian government later declared that more than 40 soldiers and policemen died in the later half of June across Southern Cameroons.<ref name=100deadvoa>[https://www.voanews.com/a/cameroon-says-military-casualties-mounting/4456739.html Cameroon says Military Casualties Mounting] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180628015704/https://www.voanews.com/a/cameroon-says-military-casualties-mounting/4456739.html |date=2018-06-28 }}, Voice of America, Jun 27, 2018. Accessed Jun 27, 2018.</ref> By now, the war had fully extended to Buea, with separatists mounting road blocks and attacking government soldiers on June 29.<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/panic-grips-buea-soldiers-battle-separatists/ Panic grips Buea as soldiers battle separatists] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180629204552/https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/panic-grips-buea-soldiers-battle-separatists/ |date=2018-06-29 }}, Journal du Cameroun, Jun 29, 2018. Accessed Jun 29, 2018.</ref> Attacks in Buea intensified in July, with one invasion on July 1,<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/muea-lockdown-soldiers-battle-separatists/ Muea in lockdown as soldiers battle separatists] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180702122154/https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/muea-lockdown-soldiers-battle-separatists/ |date=2018-07-02 }}, Journal du Cameroun, Jul 1, 2018. Accessed Jul 2, 2018.</ref> another on July 9<ref>[https://www.enca.com/africa/gunfire-in-cameroons-english-restive-region Gunfire in Cameroon's English restive region] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180709201441/https://www.enca.com/africa/gunfire-in-cameroons-english-restive-region |date=2018-07-09 }}, Enca, Jul 9, 2018. Accessed Jul 9, 2018.</ref> and another on July 30.<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/four-civilians-killed-buea/ Four civilians killed in Buea] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180731105038/https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/four-civilians-killed-buea/ |date=2018-07-31 }}, Journal du Cameroun, Jul 31, 2018. Accessed Jul 31, 2018.</ref>\n\n[[File:Wreckage of vehicles at Mile 16, September 11, 2018.jpg|thumb|300px|right|Scorched vehicles left behind after clashes in Buea on September 11.]]\n\nOn August 16, separatists attacked a [[convoy]] transporting a member of parliament in [[Babungo (village)|Babungo]], [[Ngo-Ketunjia|Ngo-Ketunjia Department]], killing at least four soldiers. A civilian who got caught in the crossfire was also killed.<ref name=16.08.2018>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/four-soldiers-killed-baboungo/ Four soldiers killed in Baboungo] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180816114130/https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/four-soldiers-killed-baboungo/ |date=2018-08-16 }}, Journal du Cameroun, Aug 16, 2018. Accessed Aug 16, 2018.</ref> Eight days later, a successful guerrilla attack killed two gendarmes and wounded a brigade commander in Zhoa in [[Wum]], [[Northwest Region (Cameroon)|Northwest Region]].<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-army-kills-12-separatists-troubled-anglophone-region/ Cameroon army kills 12 separatists in troubled Anglophone region] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180827143959/https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-army-kills-12-separatists-troubled-anglophone-region/ |date=2018-08-27 }}, Journal du Cameroun, Aug 27, 2018. Accessed Aug 27, 2018.</ref> As a response, the Cameroonian Army burned down the village.<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/villagers-flee-zhoa-arson-attacks/ Villagers flee Zhoa after arson attacks] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180829215224/https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/villagers-flee-zhoa-arson-attacks/ |date=2018-08-29 }}, Journal du Cameroun, Aug 29, 2018. Accessed Aug 29, 2018.</ref>\n\nSeptember saw some setbacks for the separatists, as the government launched attacks into the rural areas they controlled.<ref name=\"crisisgroupmay22019\"/> There was heavy fighting in [[Muyuka]], where Cameroon launched an offensive.<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroonfour-separatists-killed-three-soldiers-muyuka-battle/ Cameroon:four separatists killed, three soldiers in Muyuka battle] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180904153957/https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroonfour-separatists-killed-three-soldiers-muyuka-battle/ |date=2018-09-04 }}, Journal du Cameroun, Sep 4, 2018. Accessed Sep 4, 2018.</ref> The Cameroonian Army enjoyed some success in weeding out separatist camps.  In a particularly lethal raid on September 4, Cameroonian soldiers killed 27 suspected separatists near Zhoa.<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-army-kills-27-fighters-wum/ Cameroon army kills 27 fighters in Wum] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180906225504/https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-army-kills-27-fighters-wum/ |date=2018-09-06 }}, Journal du Cameroun, Sep 6, 2018. Accessed Sep 7, 2018.</ref> Another raid on separatist camps near [[Chomba]] killed at least 15 separatists.<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-soldiers-kill-15-suspected-separatists-in-nw-region/ Cameroon soldiers kill 15 suspected separatists in NW region] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180912195645/https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-soldiers-kill-15-suspected-separatists-in-nw-region/ |date=2018-09-12 }}, Sep 12, 2018. Accessed Sep 12, 2018.</ref> The separatists also had their successes; On September 9, 50 or more separatists successfully carried out three coordinated attacks on multiple targets in Oku, burning down the police station, destroying the Assistant Division Officer's belongings, stealing a police van and abducting three police officers.<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroonthree-kidnapped-as-separatist-burn-police-station-in-oku/ Cameroon:Three kidnapped as separatist burn police station in Oku] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180912131143/https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroonthree-kidnapped-as-separatist-burn-police-station-in-oku/ |date=2018-09-12 }}, Sep 10, 2018. Accessed Sep 12, 2018.</ref> On September 11, separatists took control of two neighborhoods of Buea, blocking the main entrances to the city and killing a soldier from the [[Rapid Intervention Battalion, Cameroon|Rapid Intervention Battalion]] (BIR).<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-soldier-found-dead-in-buea/ Cameroon: soldier found dead in Buea], Journal du Cameroun, Sep 11, 2018. Accessed Jul 8, 2019.</ref> An attempt was also made to abduct the Fon of Buea.<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-kidnapped-buea-traditional-ruler-freed/ Cameroon: kidnapped Buea traditional ruler freed] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180916164330/https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-kidnapped-buea-traditional-ruler-freed/ |date=2018-09-16 }}, Sep 14, 2018. Accessed Sep 16, 2018.</ref> On September 27, separatists forced the police and gendarmes to retreat from [[Balikumbat]], [[Ngo-Ketunjia]].<ref>[http://cameroonnewsagency.com/ambazonia-fighters-hoist-flags-in-abandoned-do-police-buildings/ Ambazonia Fighters Hoist Flags In Abandoned DO, Police Buildings] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181125115455/http://cameroonnewsagency.com/ambazonia-fighters-hoist-flags-in-abandoned-do-police-buildings/ |date=2018-11-25 }}, Cameroon News Agency, Sep 28, 2018. Accessed Nov 24, 2018.</ref> Despite government offensives in September, the separatists remained in control of many rural and urban areas.<ref name=\"crisisgroupmay22019\"/>\n\nOn September 30, in anticipation of the first anniversary of Ambazonia's declaration of independence on October 1, the authorities imposed a 48-hour curfew throughout the Anglophone region. This was done to prevent a re-occurrence of the mass demonstrations that took place the year before. People were forbidden from moving across sub-division boundaries, and gatherings of four or more people in public were prohibited. Businesses were shut down and motor parks were closed as well. Meanwhile, in anticipation of the [[Cameroonian presidential election, 2018|Cameroonian presidential election]] on October 7, the separatists started enforcing a lock-down of their own, blocking major highways with trees or car wrecks. Throughout the day, security forces and separatists clashed in Buea, Bamenda and other cities.<ref>[https://qz.com/africa/1410357/cameroon-army-anglophone-separatists-have-ambazonia-region-on-lockdown/ Cameroon armed forces and separatists have the Anglophone region on lockdown ahead of elections] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181003141555/https://qz.com/africa/1410357/cameroon-army-anglophone-separatists-have-ambazonia-region-on-lockdown/ |date=2018-10-03 }}, Quartz Africa, Oct 2, 2018. Accessed Oct 3, 2018.</ref>\n\nBy October, the conflict had spread to most of Southern Cameroons. The ADF alone had clashed with the army 83 times,<ref name=\"BBCoct42018\"/> separatist militias were now active in 12 divisions, and attacks were now more lethal.<ref name=\"acleddatapickingafight\"/> According to an [[International Crisis Group]] analyst, by October the war had reached a stalemate, with the army being unable to defeat the separatists, while the separatists were not militarily strong enough to expel the army.<ref name=\"BBCoct42018\"/> Others described the separatists as severely outgunned and on the verge of defeat, mostly due to their lack of access to proper weapons.<ref name=\"viceoct2018\"/> On October 7, the day of the [[Cameroonian presidential election, 2018|Cameroonian presidential election]], there were clashes all over Southern Cameroons with both sides blaming the other; the Cameroonian government claimed that separatists moved to prevent what they considered a foreign election to take place in the Anglophone regions,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://calrev.org/2019/02/11/african-powder-keg-cameroonian-conflict-and-african-security/|title=AFRICAN POWDER KEG: CAMEROONIAN CONFLICT AND AFRICAN SECURITY|last=Genin|first=Aaron|date=2019-02-11|website=The California Review|language=en-US|access-date=2019-03-15}}</ref> while the separatists blamed the government for instigating the violence.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2016/12/15/world/cameroon-protesters-deaths/index.html|title=Rights groups call for probe into protesters' deaths in Cameroon|author=Radina Gigova|website=CNN|access-date=2019-03-17|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190227172641/https://www.cnn.com/2016/12/15/world/cameroon-protesters-deaths/index.html|archive-date=2019-02-27|url-status=dead|df=}}</ref> This resulted in a very low turnout, as \"more than 90 percent of residents\" fled violence in some localities; and in many cases no officials showed up to man the polling stations.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/10/06/world/africa/cameroon-election-biya-ambazonia.html|title=Cameroon on Brink of Civil War as English Speakers Recount \u2018Unbearable\u2019 Horrors|last=Searcey|first=Dionne|date=2018-10-06|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-03-17|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190324074220/https://www.nytimes.com/2018/10/06/world/africa/cameroon-election-biya-ambazonia.html|archive-date=2019-03-24|url-status=dead|df=}}</ref> In Bamenda, at least 20 separatist fighters moved around openly to prevent people from voting. Two separatists were killed by government troops while attacking a polling station.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/oct/07/gunfire-in-cameroons-anglophone-regions-deters-voters-on-polling-day Gunfire in Cameroon's anglophone regions deters voters on polling day] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181008162624/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/oct/07/gunfire-in-cameroons-anglophone-regions-deters-voters-on-polling-day |date=2018-10-08 }}, The Guardian, Oct 7, 2018. Accessed Oct 8, 2018.</ref> Following the election, two people from Kumba were murdered for having voted.<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroontwo-persons-killed-for-voting-in-kumba/ Cameroon:Two persons killed for voting in Kumba] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181012175439/https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroontwo-persons-killed-for-voting-in-kumba/ |date=2018-10-12 }}, Journal du Cameroun, Oct 12, 2018. Accessed Oct 12, 2018.</ref> On October 17, [[Social Democratic Front (Cameroon)|SDF]] President [[John Fru Ndi]]'s house in Bamenda was set on fire by armed men.<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroonfru-ndis-residence-goes-up-in-flames/ Cameroon:Fru Ndi\u2019s residence goes up in flames] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181020011458/https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroonfru-ndis-residence-goes-up-in-flames/ |date=2018-10-20 }}, Journal du Cameroun, Oct 18, 2018. Accessed Oct 19, 2018.</ref> On October 23, the Cameroonian Army launched simultaneous attacks on seven or more separatist camps in the Northwest Region, initiating battles that continued for more than 24 hours. At least 30 separatists were killed, as well as an unknown number of Cameroonian soldiers.<ref>[https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/africa/fighting-between-cameroon-military-separatists-kills-18/2018/10/25/a87fd7c2-d848-11e8-8384-bcc5492fef49_story.html Fighting between Cameroon military, separatists kills \u2018many\u2019] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181025144011/https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/africa/fighting-between-cameroon-military-separatists-kills-18/2018/10/25/a87fd7c2-d848-11e8-8384-bcc5492fef49_story.html |date=2018-10-25 }}, Washington Post, Oct 25, 2018. Accessed Oct 25, 2018.</ref>\n\nIn the beginning of November, 79 students and four staff members [[PSS Nkwen kidnapping|were kidnapped from a school in Nkwen]], near Bamenda.<ref>[http://www.wsfa.com/2018/11/05/armed-men-kidnap-students-cameroon-restive-northwest/ Separatists kidnap 78 pupils in Cameroon's restive northwest] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181105190926/http://www.wsfa.com/2018/11/05/armed-men-kidnap-students-cameroon-restive-northwest/ |date=2018-11-05 }}, WSFA 12 News, Nov 5, 2018. Accessed Nov 5, 2018.</ref> All 79 students were released without ransom three days later.<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-principal-of-pss-nkwen-three-others-released/ Cameroon: Principal of PSS Nkwen, three others released] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181112121607/https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-principal-of-pss-nkwen-three-others-released/ |date=2018-11-12 }}, Journal du Cameroun, Oct 12, 2018. Accessed Oct 12, 2018.</ref> The Ambazonia Self-Defence Council claimed that they not only had nothing to do with the kidnappings, but had also sent its own fighters to try to locate the children.<ref>[https://www.dw.com/en/kidnapped-children-in-cameroon-released-without-ransom/a-46199258 Kidnapped children in Cameroon released without ransom] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181108184003/https://www.dw.com/en/kidnapped-children-in-cameroon-released-without-ransom/a-46199258 |date=2018-11-08 }}, Deutsche Welle, Nov 7, 2018. Accessed Nov 8, 2018.</ref> November also saw several major confrontations. On November 11, according to the separatists, 13 Cameroonian soldiers and two separatists were killed when separatists carried out a successful ambush.<ref>[https://www.reuters.com/article/us-cameroon-separatists/at-least-15-killed-in-cameroon-in-clashes-between-army-separatists-idUSKCN1NI2VM At least 15 killed in Cameroon in clashes between army, separatists] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181114031829/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-cameroon-separatists/at-least-15-killed-in-cameroon-in-clashes-between-army-separatists-idUSKCN1NI2VM |date=2018-11-14 }}, Reuters, Nov 13, 2018. Accessed Nov 14, 2018.</ref> The next day, Cameroonian soldiers ambushed and killed at least 13 suspected separatists in [[Donga-Mantung]],<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-soldiers-kill-13-separatist-fighters-in-binka/ Cameroon soldiers kill 13 separatist fighters in Binka] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181113165855/https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-soldiers-kill-13-separatist-fighters-in-binka/ |date=2018-11-13 }}, Journal du Cameroun, Nov 13, 2018. Accessed Nov 13, 2018.</ref> and another 25  near [[Nkamb\u00e9]] the next day.<ref>[https://www.trtworld.com/africa/25-killed-in-clashes-in-english-speaking-cameroon-officials-21656 25 killed in clashes in English-speaking Cameroon \u2013 officials] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181114143737/https://www.trtworld.com/africa/25-killed-in-clashes-in-english-speaking-cameroon-officials-21656 |date=2018-11-14 }}, TRT World, Oct 14, 2018. Accessed Oct 14, 2018.</ref> On November 22, around 40 Ambazonian fighters and unarmed civilians were killed in [[Bali, Cameroon|Bali]] by government soldiers, who then set their corpses on fire. With no trace of bullet wounds on any of the bodies, unconfirmed reports alleged the use of chemicals by the soldiers.<ref>[http://cameroonnewsagency.com/soldiers-use-chemicals-to-kill-fighterscivilians-in-bali/ Soldiers Use \u2018Chemicals\u2019 to Kill Fighters,Civilians in Bali] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181228130941/http://cameroonnewsagency.com/soldiers-use-chemicals-to-kill-fighterscivilians-in-bali/ |date=2018-12-28 }}, Cameroon News Agency, Nov 25, 2018. Accessed Dec 28, 2018.</ref> On November 28, separatists blocked the Buea-Kumba Highway.<ref name=\"jdcdec3\">[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-traffic-paralysed-on-buea-kumba-road-after-heavy-gunshots/ Cameroon: Traffic paralysed on Buea-Kumba road after heavy gunshots] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181204151358/https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-traffic-paralysed-on-buea-kumba-road-after-heavy-gunshots/ |date=2018-12-04 }}, Journal du Cameroun, Dec 3, 2018. Accessed Dec 3, 2018.</ref> The month also saw the first major spillover into other parts of Cameroon; On November 29, at least 30 people were kidnapped by ten unidentified gunmen in [[Bangourain]], [[West Region (Cameroon)|West Region]], and transported with canoes across the [[Noun River (Cameroon)|Lake Bamendjing]] reservoir.<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/at-least-30-persons-kidnapped-in-cameroons-west-region/ At least 30 persons kidnapped in Cameroon\u2019s West region] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181129225551/https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/at-least-30-persons-kidnapped-in-cameroons-west-region/ |date=2018-11-29 }}, Journal du Cameroun, Nov 29, 2018. Accessed Nov 29, 2018.</ref> A month later, two suspected separatists were lynched by the villagers, and the Cameroonian Army launched an offensive nearby.<ref>[http://cameroonnewsagency.com/soldiers-vs-ambazonia-fighters-the-struggle-to-break-the-bangolan-wall/ Soldiers VS Ambazonia Fighters : The Struggle to Break The Bangolan Wall] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181228223332/http://cameroonnewsagency.com/soldiers-vs-ambazonia-fighters-the-struggle-to-break-the-bangolan-wall/ |date=2018-12-28 }}, Cameroon News Agency, Dec 28, 2018. Accessed Dec 28, 2018.</ref> Bangourain was attacked once more on December 22, prompting the separatists to accuse the government of carrying out a [[false flag]] operation to incite Cameroonian Francophones.<ref name=\"cnadec2618\">[http://cameroonnewsagency.com/the-bangourain-attack-a-long-walk-towards-peace-shaming-the-devil/ The Bangourain Attack: A Long Walk Towards Peace, Shaming The Devil] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181227043751/http://cameroonnewsagency.com/the-bangourain-attack-a-long-walk-towards-peace-shaming-the-devil/ |date=2018-12-27 }}, Cameroon News Agency, Dec 26, 2018. Accessed Dec 26, 2018.</ref> In Kembong, just south of [[Mamfe]], a military vehicle hit a road bomb; no soldiers died, but the vehicle was destroyed.<ref>[https://www.bbc.com/pidgin/tori-46367595 Anglophone crisis: Cameroon separatists 'bomb' military moto for Kembong] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181203013948/https://www.bbc.com/pidgin/tori-46367595 |date=2018-12-03 }}, BBC (Pidgin), Nov 30, 2018. Accessed Nov 30, 2018.</ref>\n\nDecember saw more burning of houses by government soldiers in Romajia,<ref name=\"cnadec72018\">[http://cameroonnewsagency.com/the-onslaught-in-kumbo-continues-analysis-of-radio-evangelum/ The Onslaught In Kumbo Continues-Analysis of Radio Evangelum] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181209165257/http://cameroonnewsagency.com/the-onslaught-in-kumbo-continues-analysis-of-radio-evangelum/ |date=2018-12-09 }}, Cameroon News Agency, Dec 7, 2018. Accessed Dec 7, 2018.</ref> Kikiakom and Ekona.<ref name=\"cnadec72018\"/> On December 15, at least five separatists were summarily executed, possibly by fellow separatists.<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-infighting-from-ambazonia-armed-groups-leaves-at-least-5-dead/ Cameroon: infighting from \u2018Ambazonia armed groups\u2019 leaves at least 5 dead] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181217062906/https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-infighting-from-ambazonia-armed-groups-leaves-at-least-5-dead/ |date=2018-12-17 }}, Journal du Cameroun, Dec 16, 2018. Accessed Dec 16, 2018.</ref> On December 21, ADF General [[Ivo Mbah]] was killed during a military raid in Kumba.<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-ambazonia-general-killed-in-kumba/ Cameroon: \u2018Ambazonia General\u2019 killed in Kumba] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181221230740/https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-ambazonia-general-killed-in-kumba/ |date=2018-12-21 }}, Journal du Cameroun, Dec 21, 2018. Accessed Dec 21, 2018.</ref>\n\nOn December 31, the presidents of Cameroon and Ambazonia addressed the ongoing conflict in their end of year speeches. President [[Paul Biya]] of Cameroon promised to \"neutralize\" all separatists who refused to disarm, while emphasizing that anyone who drops their guns can be reintegrated into society.<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/biya-says-soldiers-will-crush-ambazonia-fighters-who-fail-to-drop-their-guns/ Cameroon: Biya says soldiers will \u2018neutralize\u2019 Ambazonia fighters who fail to drop their guns] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190101014559/https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/biya-says-soldiers-will-crush-ambazonia-fighters-who-fail-to-drop-their-guns/ |date=2019-01-01 }}, Journal du Cameroun, Dec 31, 2018. Accessed Dec 31, 2018.</ref> President [[Samuel Ikome Sako]] of Ambazonia said that the separatists would switch from a defensive to an offensive strategy in the war, and announced that a Mobile Wing Police would be created to capture territory and defeat government militias. He also condemned anyone engaged in kidnappings of civilians, and promised to fight back against anyone involved in such practices.<ref>[http://cameroonnewsagency.com/no-retreat-no-surrender-from-defensive-to-offensive-strategy-the-way-forward-in-2019-dr-samuel-sako/ No Retreat, No Surrender, From Defensive To Offensive Strategy, The way Forward In 2019-Dr Samuel Sako] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190101051522/http://cameroonnewsagency.com/no-retreat-no-surrender-from-defensive-to-offensive-strategy-the-way-forward-in-2019-dr-samuel-sako/ |date=2019-01-01 }}, Cameroon News Agency, Dec 31, 2018. Accessed Dec 31, 2018.</ref> The same night, separatist fighters attacked the convoy of the Governor of the [[Northwest Region (Cameroon)|Northwest Region]], injuring at least one government soldier.<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-nw-governor-attacked-by-ambazonia-fighters-on-new-year/ Cameroon: NW Governor attacked by Ambazonia fighters on New Year] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190101192111/https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-nw-governor-attacked-by-ambazonia-fighters-on-new-year/ |date=2019-01-01 }}, Journal du Cameroun, Jan 1, 2019. Accessed Jan 1, 2019.</ref> The Cameroonian Army also announced the killing of [[Lekeaka Oliver]], Field Marshall of the [[Red Dragon (Ambazonian militia)|Red Dragon militia]], in [[Lebialem]]; the killing was denied by the Interim Government of Ambazonia,<ref name=\"Oliver\">[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-mystery-surrounds-reported-death-of-ambazonias-field-marshall/ Cameroon: Mystery surrounds \u2018reported death of Ambazonia\u2019s Field Marshall\u2019] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190102181616/https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-mystery-surrounds-reported-death-of-ambazonias-field-marshall/ |date=2019-01-02 }}, Journal du Cameroun, Jan 2, 2019. Accessed Jan 2, 2019.</ref> and was also denied by sources within the Cameroonian Army. Oliver resurfaced in a video a week later, proving that reports of his death were false.<ref name=\"jdcjan42019\">[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-three-soldiers-killed-in-mbelenka/ Cameroon: Three gendarmes killed in Mbelenka] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190104154040/https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-three-soldiers-killed-in-mbelenka/ |date=2019-01-04 }}, Journal du Cameroun, Jan 4, 2018. Accessed Jan 4, 2018.</ref>\n\n===2019===\n\n{{Main|Timeline of the Anglophone Crisis (2019)}}\n\n2019 started off with further escalation of the war. On January 6, Anglophone Cameroonians in the diaspora organized protests to mark the first anniversary of the arrest of the Ambazonian leadership. Throughout the day, armed clashes took place in [[Muyuka]], [[Bafut, Cameroon|Bafut]]. Mundum and [[Mamfe]].<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-protests-ghost-towns-marked-anniversary-celebrations-of-detained-ambazonia-leaders/ Cameroon: Protests, ghost towns mark anniversary celebrations of detained \u2018Ambazonia leaders\u2019] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190107170427/https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-protests-ghost-towns-marked-anniversary-celebrations-of-detained-ambazonia-leaders/ |date=2019-01-07 }}, Journal du Cameroun, Jan 7, 2019. Accessed Jan 7, 2019.</ref> In Mamfe, two Ambazonian generals were killed when their camps were raided by the BIR.<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-two-ambazonia-generals-killed-in-mamfe/ Cameroon: Two \u2018Ambazonia Generals\u2019 killed in Mamfe] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190107165605/https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-two-ambazonia-generals-killed-in-mamfe/ |date=2019-01-07 }}, Journal du Cameroun, Jan 7, 2019. Accessed Jan 7, 2019.</ref>  On January 24, General Andrew Ngoe of [[SOCADEF]] was killed in Matoh, [[Mbonge]].<ref name=\"AndrewNgoe\">[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-ambazonia-general-killed-in-matoh/ Cameroon: \u2018Ambazonia General\u2019 killed in Matoh] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190125020522/https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-ambazonia-general-killed-in-matoh/ |date=2019-01-25 }}, Journal du Cameroun, Jan 24, 2019. Accessed Jan 24, 2019.</ref>\n\nJanuary also saw the start of the trials of the Ambazonian leaders, including [[Sisiku Julius Ayuk Tabe]], who had spent a year in prison. The trial was complicated by all the Ambazonian leaders rejecting their Cameroonian nationality, which the court ultimately ignored. The leaders then refused to be tried by Francophone judges. On March 1, the trial took a diplomatic twist; a Nigerian court determined that the deportation of the Ambazonian leadership had been unconstitutional, and ordered their return to Nigeria. Nevertheless, the trial resumed.<ref name=\"mar12019abuja\">[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-nigerian-court-orders-return-of-ambazonia-leaders/ Cameroon: Nigerian Court orders return of Ambazonia leaders] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190301205941/https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-nigerian-court-orders-return-of-ambazonia-leaders/ |date=2019-03-01 }}, Journal du Cameroun, Mar 1, 2019. Accessed Mar 1, 2019.</ref>\n\nThe separatists got bolder with enforcing lockdowns. The same day as the start of the trial, the streets of Buea were almost completely deserted.<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-vionlence-gunshots-ghost-towns-engulf-parts-of-anglophone-towns/ Cameroon: vionlence, gunshots, ghost towns engulf parts of Anglophone towns], Journal du Cameroun, Jan 10, 2019. Accessed Jan 10, 2019.</ref> On February 4, in anticipation of [[Public holidays in Cameroon|Youth Day]] on February 11, separatists declared a 10-day lockdown, telling people all across the Anglophone regions to stay at home from February 5\u201314.<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-ambazonia-separatists-impose-ten-day-lockdown-on-anglophone-regions/ Cameroon: Ambazonia separatists impose \u2018ten-day lockdown\u2019 on Anglophone regions] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190205044109/https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-ambazonia-separatists-impose-ten-day-lockdown-on-anglophone-regions/ |date=2019-02-05 }}, Journal du Cameroun, Feb 4, 2019. Accessed Feb 4, 2019.</ref> The lockdown was a matter of controversy among the separatists, with a spokesperson of the [[Ambazonia Defence Forces]] arguing that it would be counterproductive.<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-ambazonia-activists-divided-over-ten-day-lockdown/ Cameroon: Ambazonia activists divided over \u2018ten-day lockdown\u2019] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190205030751/https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-ambazonia-activists-divided-over-ten-day-lockdown/ |date=2019-02-05 }}, Journal du Cameroun, Feb 4, 2019. Accessed Feb 4, 2019.</ref> The next day, large parts of Buea were closed down, while armed clashes took place in Muea and Muyuka. Most of Bamenda was also closed down, with smaller clashes taking place.<ref name=\"feb52019\">[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroongunshots-blackouts-open-day-one-of-ambazonia-lockdown/ Cameroon:Gunshots, blackout open day one of Ambazonia lockdown] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190206012239/https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroongunshots-blackouts-open-day-one-of-ambazonia-lockdown/ |date=2019-02-06 }}, Journal du Cameroun, Feb 5, 2019. Accessed Feb 5, 2019.</ref> In Muyuka, an Ambazonian Colonel was killed alongside two other separatist fighters.<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-ambazonia-colonel-killed-in-muyuka/ Cameroon: Ambazonia \u2018Colonel\u2019 killed in Muyuka] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190207020111/https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-ambazonia-colonel-killed-in-muyuka/ |date=2019-02-07 }}, Journal du Cameroun, Feb 6, 2019. Accessed Feb 6, 2019.</ref> In Mbengwi, two separatists died while attacking the Divisional Office there.<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-security-forces-kill-two-separatist-fighters-in-mbengwi/ Cameroon: Security forces kill two separatist fighters in Mbengwi] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190207015523/https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-security-forces-kill-two-separatist-fighters-in-mbengwi/ |date=2019-02-07 }}, Journal du Cameroun, Feb 6, 2019. Accessed Feb 6, 2019.</ref> As a result of the lockdown, Youth Day celebrations had negligible turnout in Southern Cameroons. In Bamenda, the Governor of Northwest Region, Adolph Lele l\u2019Afrique, was escorted by soldiers to attend a small celebration. The military escort came under fire while driving to the ceremony, possibly resulting in casualties. The celebrations were boycotted in most major cities in the Anglophone regions, including Buea, Kumbo, Belo, Ndop, Ndu, Wum, Muyuka, Mamfe, Tombem, Mundemba and Lebialem, while there was a comparatively significant turnout in Nkambe.<ref>[https://nationaltelegraph.net/cameroon-lockdown-gunshots-frustrate-youth-day-force-buea-university-to-postpone-exams/ Cameroon: Lockdown, Gunshots Frustrate Youth Day, Force Buea University To Postpone Exams] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190213124107/https://nationaltelegraph.net/cameroon-lockdown-gunshots-frustrate-youth-day-force-buea-university-to-postpone-exams/ |date=2019-02-13 }}, National Telegraph, Feb 11, 2019. Accessed Feb 12, 2019.</ref>\n\nEarly March saw two serious kidnapping incidents; one on the Kumba-Buea Highway, which was quickly foiled by the BIR,<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-soldiers-rescue-passengers-freed-along-buea-kumba-road/ Cameroon: Soldiers rescue passengers freed along Buea-Kumba road] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190321225853/https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-soldiers-rescue-passengers-freed-along-buea-kumba-road/ |date=2019-03-21 }}, Journal du Cameroun, Mar 20, 2019. Accessed Mar 20, 2019.</ref> and one at the University of Buea, where more than 15 students were kidnapped, beaten and released.<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-at-least-15-buea-university-students-kidnapped/ Cameroon: At least 15 Buea University students kidnapped], Journal du Cameroun, Mar 20, 2019. Accessed Jul 7, 2019.</ref> The separatists set up several road blocks, including an overnight mission where the [[Seven Karta]] militia blocked the Bafut-Bamenda Highway with concrete walls<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-ambazonia-fighters-erect-wall-in-bafut/ Cameroon: Ambazonia fighters erect wall in Bafut], Journal du Cameroun, Mar 23, 2019. Accessed Jul 7, 2019.</ref> On March 14, Cameroonian soldiers burned down several houses in Dunga Mantung and Menchum, and killed at least 12 people (several of whom were burned alive).<ref>[http://cameroonnewsagency.com/thursdays-incidents-in-wum-and-nkambe-central-casualties-you-should-know/ Thursday\u2019s Incidents In Wum And Nkambe Central; Casualties You Should Know], Cameroon News Agency, Mar 16, 2019. Accessed Mar 18, 2019.</ref> At the end of March, an ADF leader announced that they would take the war into the French-speaking parts of Cameroon. A week later, separatists \u2013 possibly the ADF \u2013 raided Penda Mboko, [[Littoral Region (Cameroon)|Littoral Region]], and injured three gendarmes.<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-three-gendarmes-injured-as-suspected-ambazonia-fighters-attack-littoral-region-again/ Cameroon:Three gendarmes injured as suspected Ambazonia fighters attack Littoral region again], Journal du Cameroun, Apr 2, 2019. Accessed Apr 2, 2019.</ref> This was done in defiance of the Interim Government.<ref>[https://www.bareta.news/interim-government-warns-cameroun-against-propagating-inter-citizen-war-between-both-cameroons/ Interim Government Warns Cameroun Against Propagating Inter-Citizen War Between Both Cameroons], Bareta News. Accessed Dec 25, 2018.</ref>\n\nOn March 31, various Ambazonian independence movements agreed to form the [[Southern Cameroons Liberation Council]] (SCLC), a united front consisting of both separatists and federalists.<ref>[http://cameroonnewsagency.com/federalists-meet-restorationists-which-group-will-perform-the-osmosis/ Federalists Meet Restorationists, Which Group Will Perform The Osmosis?], Cameroon News Agency, Mar 29, 2019. Accessed Apr 10, 2019.</ref> On April 4, separatists imposed a 10-day lockdown on Buea.<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-looming-ambazonia-lockdown-sparks-exodus-from-buea/ Cameroon: Looming Ambazonia lockdown sparks exodus from Buea], Journal du Cameroun, Apr 4, 2019. Accessed Apr 4, 2019.</ref> On April 9, the newly-established SCLC declared an early end to lockdown, citing how it mainly affected civilians. However, the [[Ambazonia Self-Defence Council]], the armed wing of the [[Interim Government of Ambazonia|Interim Government]], declared that the SCLC had no authority to call off the lockdown without consulting it first.<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-confusion-looms-as-ambazonia-faction-maintains-lockdown-in-fako/ Cameroon: Confusion looms as Ambazonia faction maintains Fako lockdown], Journal du Cameroun, Apr 10, 2019. Accessed Apr 10, 2019.</ref>\n\n[[File:Soldiers in Bamenda, May 24, 2019.png|thumb|right|Cameroonian soldiers in Bamenda in May, 2019.]]\n\nOn April 14, four Cameroonian soldiers and three separatist fighters were killed in [[Bali, Cameroon|Bali]].<ref>[http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2019-04/15/c_137978898.htm Three separatists, 4 soldiers killed in clashes in Cameroon's troubled Anglophone region], XinhuaNet, Apr 15, 2019. Accessed Apr 15, 2019.</ref> In Ekona, at least six people were killed in a government offensive.<ref>[http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2019-04/15/c_137977131.htm Six killed in anti-separatism military operation in Cameroon's restive Anglophone region], XinhuaNet, Apr 15, 2019. Accessed Apr 15, 2019.</ref> The next day, security forces carried out mass arrests in Buea as they searched for separatist bases.<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/camerooncivilians-arrested-as-security-forces-raid-buea-in-search-of-ambazonia-fighters/ Cameroon:Civilians arrested as security forces raid Buea in search of Ambazonia fighters], Journal du Cameroun, Apr 16, 2019. Accessed Apr 17, 2019.</ref> On April 24, gunmen burned down the house of the mayor of [[Fundong]].<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroonresidence-of-fundong-mayor-burnt-by-suspected-separatist-fighters/ Cameroon:Residence of Fundong Mayor burnt by suspected separatist fighters], Journal du Cameroun, Apr 25, 2019. Accessed Jul 8, 2019.</ref> On April 27, [[Social Democratic Front (Cameroon)|SDF]] leader [[John Fru Ndi]] [[Kidnapping of John Fru Ndi|was kidnapped]] in Kumbo by separatists, but was released the same day. Fru Ndi had travelled to Kumbo to attend the funeral of Joseph Banadzem, the Parliamentary group leader of the SDF. Local separatist fighters had consented to the funeral taking place, provided that no Francophone Cameroonians attended it.<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-sdf-chairman-ni-john-fru-ndi-kidnapped/ Cameroon: SDF Chairman Ni John Fru Ndi released after brief kidnap], Journal du Cameroun, Apr 27, 2019. Accessed Apr 27, 2019.</ref> On April 30, government soldiers killed one person and burned at least 10 houses in Kikaikelaiki, [[Bui (Cameroon department)|Bui]].<ref>[http://cameroonnewsagency.com/in-pictures-soldiers-burn-over-10-house-cardinal-tumis-village/ In Pictures: Soldiers Burn Over 10 House Cardinal Tumi\u2019s Village], Cameroon News Agency, Apr 30, 2019. Accessed May 1, 2019.</ref>\n\nMay saw the Anglophone Crisis get some international attention. On May 5, following appeals by the [[European Union Parliament]], it was announced that the Anglophone Crisis would be debated at the [[United Nations Security Council]].<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-un-security-council-to-discuss-anglophone-crisis/ Cameroon: UN Security Council to discuss Anglophone crisis], Journal du Cameroun, May 5, 2019. Accessed May 5, 2019.</ref> Days later, the Cameroonian government announced it was ready for an \"inclusive\" dialogue where anything except Ambazonian independence could be discussed.<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroonpaul-biya-ready-for-dialogue-to-end-anglophone-crisis-pm-says/ Cameroon:Paul Biya ready for dialogue to end Anglophone crisis, PM says], Journal du Cameroun, May 9, 2019. Accessed May 9, 2019.</ref> Meanwhile, a [[2019 Ambazonian leadership crisis|leadership crisis]] erupted within the [[Interim Government of Ambazonia]], forcing smaller separatist movements to pick their loyalties.<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-sepratist-hardliners-react-after-impechment-of-detained-ambazonia-leader/ Cameroon: Sepratist hardliners react after impechment of detained Ambazonia leader], Journal du Cameroun, Jun 12, 2019. Accessed Jun 12, 2019.</ref>\n\nIn June, the separatists announced that they had started producing their own weapons in the warzone. Shortly afterwards, a mine killed four policemen and wounded another six,<ref name=\"producingownweapons\"/> convincing many that the separatists were no longer outgunned, but indeed well-armed.<ref name=\"voajun192019\"/> The same month, it was revealed that the government of Cameroon and separatist movements would enter negotiations.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://cameroonnewsagency.com/armed-conflict-in-southern-cameroons-ambazonia-leaders-welcome-swiss-led-mediation-process/|title=Armed Conflict In Southern Cameroons: Ambazonia Leaders Welcome Swiss-Led Mediation Process \u2013 Cameroon News Agency|first=|date=|website=|language=en-US|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=dead|access-date=2019-07-04}}</ref> On June 27, John Fru Ndi was [[Kidnapping of John Fru Ndi#Second kidnapping|kidnapped for the second time]] in two months.<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-kidnapped-sdf-chairman-ni-john-fru-ndi-released/ Cameroon: Kidnapped SDF Chairman Ni John Fru Ndi released], Journal du Cameroun, Jun 29, 2019. Accessed Jun 29, 2019.</ref>\n\nHeavy fighting took place in July. On July 3, separatists ambushed a military boat carrying 13 Cameroonian soldiers on the Ekpambiri river, [[Manyu (department)|Manyu Division]]. Three soldiers managed to escape, two were rescued, one was found dead after five days, and seven remain unaccounted for. The Cameroonian Army declared that they knew which base the attackers had come from, and that an operation would be launched to destroy it.<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-corpse-of-soldier-discovered-in-manyu-river/ Cameroon: Corpse of soldier discovered in Manyu river], Journal du Cameroun, Jul 8, 2019. Accessed Jul 8, 2019.</ref> On July 8, at least two gendarmes were killed and several more were wounded in an ambush in [[Ndop]].<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-two-gendarmes-killed-in-restive-nw-region/ Cameroon: Two gendarmes killed in restive NW region], Journal du Cameroun, Jul 10, 2019. Accessed Jul 10, 2019.</ref> On July 11, at least seven separatist fighters were killed in Esu.<ref>[http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2019-07/12/c_138218983.htm 7 separatists killed in Cameroon's troubled Anglophone region], XinhuaNet, Jul 12, 2019. Accessed Jul 12, 2019.</ref> The next day, armed men kidnapped 30 bus passengers passing through [[Belo, Cameroon|Belo]], in an apparent case of infighting among local separatist militias.<ref>[http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2019-07/13/c_138224267.htm About 30 passengers kidnapped in Cameroon's restive Anglophone region], XinhuaNet, Jul 13, 2019. Accessed Jul 14, 2019.</ref> One Cameroonian soldier and three separatists were killed in Buea on July 14,<ref>[http://french.xinhuanet.com/2019-07/15/c_138229310.htm Cameroun/Crise anglophone : un soldat et trois s\u00e9paratistes arm\u00e9s tu\u00e9s dans le sud-ouest], XinhuaNet, Jul 15, 2019. Accessed Jul 15, 2019. (French)</ref> and at least one Cameroonian soldier and at least five separatists were killed in [[Mbiame]] three days later.<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-soldier-killed-in-restive-nw-region-2/ Cameroon: Soldier killed in restive NW region], Journal du Cameroun, Jul 17, 2019. Accessed Jul 17, 2019.</ref>\n\nTowards the end of July, [[July 2019 Cameroon prison riots|two major prison riots]] took place. On July 22, separatist inmates at [[Kondengui Central Prison]] took part in staging a protest against the prison conditions. The protest escalated into a riot, which was eventually quelled violently. A similar protest and crackdown took place at Buea Central Prison a few days later.<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/camerooncalm-returns-to-buea-prison-after-protest-by-prisoners/ Cameroon:Calm returns to Buea prison after protest by prisoners], Journal du Cameroun, Jul 24, 2019. Accessed Jul 24, 2019.</ref> More than 100 inmates were moved to undisclosed locations for detention,<ref name=\"jul292019\">[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-anglophone-detainees-missing-after-kondengui-protests/ Cameroon: Anglophone detainees missing after Kondengui protests], Journal du Cameroun, Jul 29, 2019. Accessed Jul 29, 2019.</ref> some of whom were subjected to torture,<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-tortured-mancho-bibixy-ambazonia-detainees-not-dead/ Cameroon: Tortured Mancho Bibixy, Ambazonia detainees not dead!], Journal du Cameroun, Jul 29, 2019. Accessed Jul 29, 2019.</ref> and there were speculations that some had been killed during the riots. The [[Interim Government of Ambazonia]] demanded that the Cameroonian government account for the missing inmates, threatening to impose a lockdown encompassing the entire Anglophone regions if it failed to do so.<ref name=\"jul262019\">[http://cameroonnewsagency.com/ambazonia-separatist-leaders-give-govt-ultimatum-to-present-detained-prisoners/ Ambazonia Separatist Leaders Give Gov\u2019t Ultimatum To Present Detained Prisoners], Cameroon News Agency, Jul 28, 2019. Accessed Jul 28, 2019.</ref> The lockdown started on July 29.<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-ambazonia-leaders-call-for-another-lockdown-in-anglophone-regions/ Cameroon: Ambazonia leaders call for another \u2018lockdown\u2019 in Anglophone regions], Journal du Cameroun, Jul 30, 2019. Accessed Jul 30, 2019.</ref> Midnight to July 31, the ten detained members of the Interim Government, including [[Sisiku Julius Ayuk Tabe]], went on a hunger strike over the missing convicts.<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-separatist-leader-launches-hunger-strike/ Cameroon separatist leader launches hunger strike], Journal du Cameroun, Aug 1, 2019. Accessed Aug 1, 2019.</ref>\n\nOn August 4, separatist fighters ambushed and killed a soldier and his civilian driver in Penda Mboko, [[Littoral Region (Cameroon)|Littoral Region]], the second attack there since March.<ref>[http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2019-08/05/c_138284639.htm One soldier killed in rare ambush in Cameroon], XinhuaNet, Aug 5, 2019. Accessed Aug 5, 2019.</ref> On August 14, in an effort to sabotage the new school year, separatist militias announced that region-wide lockdowns would be enforced on September 2\u20136 and 9\u201313, covering the first two weeks of the academic year.<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-ambazonia-fighters-declare-lockdown-to-frustrate-school-resumption-in-anglophone-regions/ Cameroon: Ambazonia fighters declare \u2018Lockdown\u2019 to frustrate school resumption in Anglophone regions], Journal du Cameroun, Aug 14, 2019. Accessed Aug 14, 2019.</ref> On August 15, at least seven soldiers from the BIR were injured when their vehicle skidded off the road in Kumba; while separatists claimed responsibility for the incident, the army claimed it was simply a road accident.<ref>[http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2019-08/16/c_138312378.htm Seven Cameroonian soldiers injured in accident in restive Anglophone region], XinhuaNet, Aug 16, 2019. Accessed Aug 16, 2019.</ref>\n\nOn August 20, the ten detained members of the [[Interim Government of Ambazonia]], including [[President of Ambazonia|President]] [[Sisiku Julius Ayuk Tabe|Ayuk Tabe]], were sentenced to [[life imprisonment]] by the Yaound\u00e9 Military Tribunal.<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-detained-ambazonia-leaders-handed-life-sentence/ Cameroon: Detained Ambazonia leaders handed life sentence], Journal du Cameroun, Aug 20, 2019. Accessed Aug 20, 2019.</ref> This was followed by a military escalation and a series of lockdowns, crushing hopes that the school year could start as normal in early September. Within a week, violence and uncertainty had triggered tens of thousands of people to flee from the Anglophone regions.<ref name=\"voaaug262019\">[https://www.voanews.com/africa/thousands-flee-violence-cameroons-english-speaking-regions Thousands Flee Violence in Cameroon\u2019s English-Speaking Regions], Voice of America, Aug 26, 2019. Accessed Aug 26, 2019.</ref> Due to the escalation, a government-led effort to reopen at least 4,500 schools by September 2 ultimately failed.<ref>[https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-49529774 Cameroon's conflict keeps schools shut], BBC, Sep 3, 2019. Accessed Sep 3, 2019.</ref>\n\nIn September, President Paul Biya announced the [[Major National Dialogue]], a political dialogue that would be held before the end of the month.<ref name=\"Cameroon 2019. p 12\">[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-paul-biya-convenes-national-dialogue-to-solve-anglophone-crisis/ Cameroon: Paul Biya convenes national dialogue to solve Anglophone crisis], Journal du Cameroun, Sep 10, 2019. Accessed Sep 12, 2019.</ref> While separatists were quick to reject the initiative, citing the recent life sentences handed to the separatist leaders,<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/biyas-dialogue-for-cameroon-crisis-runs-into-questions-rejection/ Biya\u2019s \u2018dialogue\u2019 for Cameroon crisis runs into questions, rejection], Journal du Cameroun, Sep 11, 2019. Accessed Sep 12, 2019.</ref> opposition parties in Cameroon showed interest in the initiative and started submitting proposals.<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-matomba-submits-pre-dialogue-proposals-to-pm-dion-ngute/ Cameroon: Matomba submits pre-dialogue proposals to PM Dion Ngute], Journal du Cameroun, Sep 20, 2019. Accessed Sep 23, 2019.</ref> Meanwhile, the war continued; on September 20, separatist fighters launched a failed attack on a hotel in Bamenda where several government officials were staying.<ref>[http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2019-09/21/c_138409937.htm Cameroon's security forces repel separatists' attack on gov't officials], XinhuaNet, Sep 21, 2019. Accessed Sep 21, 2019.</ref> While the Major National Dialogue was happening, a significant number of Anglophones celebrated Ambazonia's third independence day on October 1. Nine people were killed in clashes all across the Anglophone regions that day,<ref>[https://www.voanews.com/africa/cameroon-separatists-celebrate-independence-dialogue-held Cameroon Separatists Celebrate 'Independence' as Dialogue is Held], Voice of America, Oct 2, 2019. Accessed Oct 2, 2019.</ref> while \"Field Marshall\" Lekeaka Oliver of the [[Red Dragon (Ambazonian militia)|Red Dragon militia]] used the occasion to declare himself Paramout Ruler of [[Lebialem]].<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-lebialem-traditional-rulers-disown-ambazonia-warlord-field-marshal/ Cameroon: Lebialem traditional rulers disown Ambazonia warlord Field Marshal], Journal du Cameroun, Oct 15, 2019. Accessed Oct 15, 2019.</ref> October also saw the public surrender of Ambazonian general Ekeom Polycarp, who was subsequently assassinated by other separatists.<ref>[http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2019-10/17/c_138480115.htm Key separatist commander killed after dropping weapons in Cameroon's troubled Anglophone region], XinhuaNet, Oct 17, 2019. Accessed Oct 17, 2019.</ref> The separatists also started opening \"community schools\" across the Anglophone regions, providing an alternative to the government-run schools which they had boycotted for years.<ref name=\"community schools\">[https://www.voanews.com/africa/cameroon-separatists-open-community-schools Cameroon Separatists Open 'Community Schools'], Voice of America, Oct 18, 2019. Accessed Oct 18, 2019.</ref>\n\nOn December 1, separatist fighters carried out their first attack on an airplane, firing at a [[Camair-Co]] passenger plane while it was landing at [[Bamenda Airport]]. No one was wounded in the attack, although several bullets penetrated into the cabin. This incident was the first of its kind, and possibly indicated that the separatists would take on larger government targets.<ref>[https://www.theeastafrican.co.ke/news/africa/Passenger-plane-shot-at-west-Cameroon/4552902-5370230-do3bu5/index.html Passenger plane shot at as violence escalates in west Cameroon], The East African, Dec 2, 2019. Accessed Dec 5, 2019.</ref> The AGovC announced that the airline in question often transported soldiers, and that they thus considered their aircraft to be legitimate targets.<ref>[http://cameroonnewsagency.com/attack-on-camair-co-passenger-plane-shows-nothing-is-under-control/ Attack On Camair-Co Passenger Plane Shows Nothing Is Under Control], Cameroon News Agency, Dec 1, 2019. Accessed Dec 1, 2019.</ref> The separatists also started their campaign to sabotage the upcoming [[2020 Cameroonian parliamentary election]], and within a week they abducted some 40 politicians, including two mayors and at least 19 councilors.<ref>[https://www.voanews.com/africa/cameroon-separatists-kidnap-candidates-protest-election Cameroon Separatists Kidnap Candidates to Protest Election], Voice of America, Dec 16, 2019. Accessed Dec 18, 2019.</ref> A separatist attack on a civilian truck with a military escort left some three civilians dead on December 19.<ref>[http://cameroonnewsagency.com/2-die-and-15-injured-in-ekona-attack/ 2 Die And 15 Injured in Ekona Attack], Cameroon News Agency, Dec 19, 2019. Accessed Dec 19, 2019.</ref> Cameroon also launched a series of operations in Mezam, Boyo, Donga Mantung, Bui, Ngo Ketunjia and Boyo that would, over six days, force around 5,500 people to flee their homes.<ref>[https://reliefweb.int/report/cameroon/cameroon-massive-population-displacement-north-west-flash-update-20-december-2019 Cameroon: Massive population displacement, North West: Flash update (20 December 2019)], ReliefWeb, Dec 23, 2019. Accessed Dec 24, 2019.</ref> In their respective New Year speeches on December 31, President Paul Biya of Cameroon and Samuel Ikome Sako of Ambazonia both promised to intensify the war in 2020.<ref>References:\n*[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/paul-biyas-end-of-year-message-to-cameroonians-2/ Paul Biya\u2019s 2019 end of year message to Cameroonians], Journal du Cameroun, Dec 31, 2019. Accessed Jan 1, 2019.\n*[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroonambazonia-leader-delivers-end-of-year-message/ Cameroon:Ambazonia leader delivers end of year message], Journal du Cameroun, Dec 31, 2019. Accessed Jan 1, 2019.\n</ref>\n\n===2020===\n\n{{Main|Timeline of the Anglophone Crisis (2020)}}\n\nSeparatist forces started the new year by declaring a five-day lockdown for February, intended to prevent the upcoming parliamentary election from taking place in the Anglophone regions.<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-2020-twin-polls-separatists-announce-five-day-lockdown-in-anglophone-regions/ Cameroon/2020 twin polls: Separatists announce five-day lockdown in Anglophone regions], Journal du Cameroun, Jan 3, 2019. Accessed Jan 3, 2019.</ref> Clashes took place in Buea and Muyuka, where separatists burned down the office of the Divisional Officer.<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-ambazonia-boys-set-fire-on-muyukas-d-os-office/ Cameroon: Suspected Ambazonia boys set ablaze Muyuka\u2019s D.O\u2019s office], Journal du Cameroun, Jan 3, 2019. Accessed Jan 3, 2019.</ref> On January 6, after failing to listen to demands from fellow separatists not to terrorize civilians, separatist commander \"General Divine\" was assassinated by his own men.<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroonambazonia-general-killed-by-peers-in-sw-region/ Cameroon:\u2019Ambazonia General\u2019 killed by peers in SW Region], Journal du Cameroun, Jan 6, 2020. Accessed Jan 6, 2020.</ref> Following instances of popular uprisings against the separatists in Balikumbat and Babungo, the ADF ordered its fighters to take action against anyone caught terrorizing civilians.<ref name=\"voajan82020\">[https://www.voanews.com/africa/cameroon-anglophone-villagers-attack-separatist-camps-over-abuse Cameroon Anglophone Villagers Attack Separatist Camps Over Abuse], Voice of America, Jan 8, 2020. Accessed Jan 8, 2020.</ref> January also saw what was possibly the most serious instance of separatist infighting to date; the [[Southern Cameroons Restoration Forces]] (loyal to the Interim Government) abducted 40 fighters from the Ambazonia Defence Forces, six of whom were subsequently murdered.<ref name=\"voainfightingjan\">[https://www.voanews.com/africa/cameroons-anglophone-separatists-turn-infighting Cameroon\u2019s Anglophone Separatists Turn to Infighting], Voice of America, Jan 22, 2020. Accessed Jan 23, 2020.</ref> \"General Chacha\", the separatist commander responsible for the abduction, was captured and summarily executed by Cameroonian soldiers a week later.<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-dreaded-ambazonia-general-killed-in-bui/ Cameroon: Dreaded Ambazonia General killed in Bui], Journal du Cameroun, Jan 27, 2020. Accessed Jan 27, 2020.</ref>\n\nA [[2020 Cameroonian parliamentary election|parliamentary election]] was held in February, and was marked by unprecedented escalation on both sides. Hundreds of additional troops were deployed to combat separatist attempts to sabotage the election, while the separatists abducted 120 politicians within the two weeks preceding the election. Efforts by the Cameroonian government to prevent a repeat of the debacle surrounding the 2018 presidential election ultimately failed, as the turnout in the Anglophone regions was very low. The Ambazonians, who claimed that 98 percent of the population boycotted the election, hailed this as a great victory.<ref name=\"cnafeb92020\">[http://cameroonnewsagency.com/low-turnout-frustrates-election-in-north-west-south-west-regions/ Low Turnout Frustrates Election In North West, South West Regions], Feb 9, 2020. Accessed Feb 11, 2020.</ref> The results in 11 constituencies were later nullified due to separatist activities, triggering a partial re-election in March. The results were largely the same, with a marginal turnout and clashes taking place throughout the day.<ref>[https://www.theafricareport.com/25124/cameroon-anglophone-regions-hit-by-violence-during-partial-legislative-polls/ Cameroon\u2019s Anglophone regions hit by violence during partial legislative polls], The Africa Report, Mar 26, 2020. Accessed Mar 27, 2020.</ref> Less than a week after the February election, Cameroonian soldiers and armed Fulani carried out the [[Ngarbuh massacre]], killing at least 23 civilians in Ntumbo, Northwest Region and drawing international condemnation.<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-un-wants-punishment-for-perpetrators-of-ngarbuh-killings/ Cameroon: UN wants punishment for perpetrators of Ngarbuh killings], Journal du Cameroun, Feb 18, 2020. Accessed Feb 18, 2020.</ref>\n\nOn March 7, around 20 separatist fighters carried out attacks on a police station and gendarmerie in [[Galim]], [[West Region (Cameroon)|West Region]], killing two gendarmes, two police officers and four civilians. This was the third separatist attack in West Region.<ref name=\"trtmar92020\">[https://www.trtworld.com/africa/anglophone-separatists-kill-five-soldiers-four-civilians-in-west-cameroon-34394 Anglophone separatists kill five soldiers, four civilians in west Cameroon], TRT World, Mar 9, 2020. Accessed Mar 9, 2020.</ref> The next day, an [[improvised explosive device]] killed one soldier and injured four soldiers, two police officers and one civilian in Bamenda.<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-womens-day-explosion-leaves-soldier-dead-others-injured-in-bamenda/ Cameroon: Women\u2019s Day explosion leaves soldier dead, others injured in Bamenda], Journal du Cameroun, Mar 9, 2020. Accessed Mar 9, 2020.</ref> Cameroon subsequently carried out an offensive in [[Ngo-Ketunjia]], where it claimed to have destroyed 10 separatist camps and killed at least 20 fighters, including some of those who had participated in the Galim raid.<ref>[https://en.trend.az/world/other/3211672.html 20 separatists killed in military offensive in Cameroon's troubled Anglophone region], Trend News Agency, Mar 22, 2020. Accessed Mar 22, 2020.</ref>\n\nOn March 26, SOCADEF declared a two-week ceasefire to give people time to get tested for [[Coronavirus disease 2019|coronavirus]],<ref>[https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-52053738 Cameroon rebels declare coronavirus ceasefire], BBC, Mar 26, 2020. Accessed Mar 27, 2020.</ref> a move that was welcomed by the [[United Nations]].<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-un-reacts-to-ceasefire-declared-by-ambazonia-armed-group/ Cameroon: UN reacts to ceasefire declared by Ambazonia armed group], Journal du Cameroun, Mar 27, 2020. Accessed Mar 27, 2020.</ref> The Interim Government and the AGovC declared their willingness to have their armed groups follow suit, but conditioned it on international monitoring and Cameroonian troops being confined to their bases.<ref>[https://cameroonnewsagency.com/covid19-ig-agovc-will-declare-covid19-ceasefire-only-when-all-parties-agree-to-internationally-binding-terms/ COVID19: IG, AGovC Will Declare COVID19 Ceasefire Only When All Parties Agree To Internationally Binding Terms], Cameroon News Agency, Nov 27, 2020. Accessed Nov 27, 2020.</ref> The same day as SOCADEF's unilateral ceasefire went into effect and, coincidentally, the same day as the first COVID-19 case was confirmed in the Anglophone regions, President Sako declared the shutting of Ambazonia's borders and restriction of movement and public gatherings in order to limit the spreading of the virus, effective from April 1.<ref>[https://cameroonnewsagency.com/covid-19-ambazonia-interim-government-president-shuts-down-border/ COVID-19: Ambazonia \u2018Interim Government\u2019 President Shuts Down Border], Cameroon News Agency, Mar 29, 2020. Accessed Mar 30, 2020.</ref> However, the danger posed by COVID-19 did not bring about an immediate end of hostilities on the ground; just the day before Sako's declaration, separatists attacked an armored car, killing a soldier and 11 officials, including two deputy mayors.<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-at-least-12-ambushed-by-ambazonia-forces-in-oku/ Cameroon: Dozens ambushed by Ambazonia forces in Oku], Journal du Cameroun, Mar 30, 2020. Accessed Mar 30, 2020.</ref> On April 8, responding to claims by the Cameroonian government that the war was nearing an end, separatists attacked military bases and destroyed infrastructure in villages all across the Anglophone regions.<ref name=\"voaapr92020\">[https://www.voanews.com/africa/cameroons-separatists-relaunch-attacks-reject-state-reconstruction-plan Cameroon's Separatists Relaunch Attacks to Reject State Reconstruction Plan], Voice of America, Apr 9, 2020. Accessed Apr 9, 2020.</ref>\n\n==Strategy==\n\n===Military strategy===\n\nThe Cameroonian Army is fighting a [[counter-insurgency]] war, aiming to hit the separatists' support base. This includes burning houses where weapons are found and, according to locals but denied by the army, carrying out revenge attacks.<ref name=\"Dirty War\">[https://www.nation.co.ke/news/africa/-Dirty-war--ravages-Cameroon-s-anglophone-region/1066-4546558-fs0ta9z/index.html 'Dirty war' ravages Cameroon's Buea region] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180507050007/https://www.nation.co.ke/news/africa/-Dirty-war--ravages-Cameroon-s-anglophone-region/1066-4546558-fs0ta9z/index.html |date=2018-05-07 }}, Daily Nation, May 5, 2018. Accessed May 7, 2018.</ref> In August 2018, the Defence Minister of Cameroon announced that the army would be expanded with 2,600 new recruits, 2,000 of whom would go to the BIR.<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-recruit-2600-amidst-tension-anglophone-regions/ Cameroon to recruit 2600 soldiers amidst tension in Anglophone regions] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180829214638/https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-recruit-2600-amidst-tension-anglophone-regions/ |date=2018-08-29 }}, Aug 29, 2018. Accessed Aug 29, 2018.</ref> In addition to expanding the army, the government has supported local vigilante groups, which there were more than 30 of as of October 2019.<ref name=\"xinhuavigilantes\"/> The government has also set up rehab centers in Bamenda and Buea to reintegrate separatists who have surrendered into civil society.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.voanews.com/a/cameroon-yet-to-build-planned-rehab-centers-for-ex-boko-haram-fighters/4791847.html |title=Cameroon Yet to Build Planned Rehab Centers for ex-Boko Haram Fighters |author=Moki Edwin Kindzeka |work=Voice of America |date=18 February 2019 |accessdate=27 February 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190301013317/https://www.voanews.com/a/cameroon-yet-to-build-planned-rehab-centers-for-ex-boko-haram-fighters/4791847.html |archive-date=1 March 2019 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> With no military victory in sight, the Cameroonian Army has sought to at least contain the conflict to rural areas. As of late-2018, the Cameroonian Army aimed to control all urban areas as well as strategic points on the countryside, and did not seek to recapture the entire Anglophone regions.<ref name=\"crisisgroupmay22019\"/>\n\n[[File:Weapons seized from separatist fighters in Bamenda.jpg|thumb|right|Weapons of separatist fighters in Bamenda, seized by the Cameroonian military in February 2019]]\n\nThe Ambazonian separatists are fighting a [[Guerrilla warfare|guerrilla war]]. Numerically and materially disadvantaged, the separatists carry out [[Hit-and-run tactics|hit-and-run attacks]], [[ambush]]es and [[Raid (military)|raids]]. According to the ADF, as of June 2018 there were 1,500 soldiers in the ADF, spread across 20 camps throughout Southern Cameroons.<ref name=EmmanuelFreudenthal/> In May 2019, independent sources measured the total number of separatist fighters to be between 2,000 and 4,000, a figure that included numerous ex-soldiers and ex-policemen, a significant number of female combatants, and dozens of Nigerian mercenaries. The Nigerians among the rebels mostly consisted of criminals and ex-insurgents who had previously taken part in the [[conflict in the Niger Delta]].<ref name=\"crisisgroupmay22019\"/>\n\nAt the start of the war, the separatists struggled with gaining access to firearms, having to rely on [[Rifle|hunting rifles]] and in some cases single-shot pistols. As the war went on, they gradually gained limited access to some more sophisticated weapons, capturing some from the Cameroonian Army and buying some in Nigeria (where they enjoyed the support of officers in the Nigerian Army). They also benefitted from fundraising campaigns, launched by diaspora activists to purchase guns for the separatist militias. This began to yield visible results in the first half of 2019.<ref name=\"goinginternational\">[https://foreignpolicy.com/2019/05/13/cameroons-separatist-movement-is-going-international-ambazonia-military-forces-amf-anglophone-crisis/ Cameroon\u2019s Separatist Movement Is Going International], Foreign Policy, May 13, 2019. Accessed May 14, 2019.</ref> From being severely outgunned in the fall of 2018,<ref name=\"viceoct2018\">[https://news.vice.com/en_us/article/qvajj3/inside-cameroons-bloody-war-over-the-english-language Inside Cameroon's bloody war over the English language], VICE News, Oct 1, 2018. Accessed Jun 19, 2019.</ref> by the summer of 2019 the separatists had become well-armed.<ref name=\"voajun192019\">[https://www.voanews.com/africa/cameroon-war-victims-casualty-figures-high-because-fighters-are-well-armed Cameroon War Victims: Casualty Figures High Because Fighters Are Well Armed], Voice of America, Jun 19, 2019. Accessed Jun 19, 2019.</ref> They also declared that they had started producing their own weapons within Southern Cameroons, a declaration followed shortly by an explosion in Mamfe that killed four policemen.<ref name=\"producingownweapons\">[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroonexplosion-kills-four-policemen-restive-anglophone-region/ Cameroon:Explosion kills four policemen in restive Anglophone region], Journal du Cameroun, Jun 16, 2019. Accessed Jul 8, 2019.</ref>\n\nThe militias enjoy significant local support, with civilians giving them food, informing them on troop movements, or outright assisting them in carrying out attacks.<ref name=\"BBCoct42018\">[https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-45723211 Cameroon's Anglophone crisis: Red Dragons and Tigers \u2013 the rebels fighting for independence] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181004145026/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-45723211 |date=2018-10-04 }}, BBC, Oct 4, 2018. Accessed Oct 4, 2018.</ref> The Interim Government of Ambazonia has stressed that the war will take place solely within Southern Cameroons, and claims that attacks across the border have been [[false flag]] operations by the Cameroonian government.<ref>[https://www.bareta.news/interim-government-warns-cameroun-against-propagating-inter-citizen-war-between-both-cameroons/ Interim Government Warns Cameroun Against Propagating Inter-Citizen War Between Both Cameroons] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181226084435/https://www.bareta.news/interim-government-warns-cameroun-against-propagating-inter-citizen-war-between-both-cameroons/ |date=2018-12-26 }}, Bareta News. Accessed Dec 25, 2018.</ref> In March 2019, the ADF announced that it would take the war into the French-speaking parts of Cameroon, defying the Interim Government.<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-three-gendarmes-injured-as-suspected-ambazonia-fighters-attack-littoral-region-again/ Cameroon:Three gendarmes injured as suspected Ambazonia fighters attack Littoral region again] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190402151300/https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-three-gendarmes-injured-as-suspected-ambazonia-fighters-attack-littoral-region-again/ |date=2019-04-02 }}, Journal du Cameroun, Apr 2, 2019. Accessed Apr 2, 2019.</ref>\n\nUnlike most Cameroonian soldiers deployed in the region, the separatists are locals, and are thus more familiar with the terrain. Cameroonian General Melingui stated that the separatists have a leverage over the army when it comes to familiarity with the battleground; \"They know the terrain. These are youths from local villages. We try to seek them out but we can't find them. Our men aren't familiar with the forest.\" Cameroonian authorities have admitted that they have little control over the security situation outside the cities.<ref name=\"Dirty War\"/> Journalist Emmanuel Freudenthal, who spent a week with ADF rebels in 2018, stated that the separatists control much of the countryside because the infrastructure in Southern Cameroons is so poorly developed, making it hard for the Cameroonian government to access those areas.<ref name=EmmanuelFreudenthal>[http://en.rfi.fr/africa/20180614-cameroon-i-spent-week-embedded-anglophone-armed-separatists Cameroon: I spent a week embedded with Anglophone armed separatists] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180614222031/http://en.rfi.fr/africa/20180614-cameroon-i-spent-week-embedded-anglophone-armed-separatists |date=2018-06-14 }}, RFI, Jun 14, 2018. Accessed Jun 14, 2018.</ref>\n\nAGovC leader in exile [[Ayaba Cho Lucas]] summed up the ADF strategy in the following way: \"60% of the GDP of Cameroon is earned in Ambazonia. [...] We must try to raise the cost of the occupation to higher than the profits they get here.\"<ref name=thisisagenocide/>\n\nRetired American diplomat [[Herman Jay Cohen]] has argued that Cameroon's military approach to the conflict plays straight into the separatist strategy. Drawing parallels to the [[Eritrean War of Independence]], he has claimed that the growing bitterness resulting from prolonged warfare will only serve to close the window of opportunity where reconciliation and territorial integrity is still an option, thereby - ironically - increasing the likelihood of Ambazonian secession.<ref>[https://www.cfr.org/blog/lessons-past-cameroons-crisis Lessons From the Past on Cameroon\u2019s Crisis], Council on Foreign Relations, Jan 3, 2019. Accessed Jan 5, 2019.</ref>\n\n===Political, diplomatic and propaganda strategy===\n\nAccording to Millan Atam, chairperson of the Southern Cameroonians Congress of the People, the separatists are building up support for their cause through two distinct phases. The first phase was to build internal capability to resist the Cameroonian Army and raise faith in the cause. Once a significant portion of the population of Southern Cameroons clearly wanted separation, the separatists would approach the international community with their cause.<ref>[http://www.thedailyvox.co.za/black-on-black-colonialism-the-divide-between-francophone-cameroon-and-anglophone-ambazonia-nolwandle-zondi/ Black-On-Black Colonialism: The Divide Between Francophone Cameroon And Anglophone Ambazonia] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180608004454/http://www.thedailyvox.co.za/black-on-black-colonialism-the-divide-between-francophone-cameroon-and-anglophone-ambazonia-nolwandle-zondi |date=2018-06-08 }}, The Daily Vox, Jun 4, 2018. Accessed Jun 5, 2018.</ref>\n\nThe Cameroonian government has tried to limit the extent of which the conflict affects everyday life in Southern Cameroons, and portrays the war as a battle between chaos and stability in which the government represents the latter. To this end, local authorities have penalized businesses that respected \"ghost towns\" declared by the separatists.<ref>[http://www.africanews.com/2018/07/22/cameroon-warns-buea-businesses-don-t-obey-ghost-town-orders-from-separatists/ Cameroon mayor warns Buea businesses over ghost towns on Mondays] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180823141920/http://www.africanews.com/2018/07/22/cameroon-warns-buea-businesses-don-t-obey-ghost-town-orders-from-separatists/ |date=2018-08-23 }}, Africa News, Jul 22, 2018. Accessed Aug 23, 2018.</ref> The government has fired and replaced local administrators who fled from the region, despite their fears of kidnappings.<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/biya-appoints-new-batibo-do-sacks-runaway-administrators-in-anglophone-regions/ Biya appoints new Batibo DO, sacks runaway administrators in Anglophone regions] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180920234424/https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/biya-appoints-new-batibo-do-sacks-runaway-administrators-in-anglophone-regions/ |date=2018-09-20 }}, Journal du Cameroun, Sep 20, 2018. Accessed Sep 20, 2018.</ref> In September 2018, the army physically prevented people from fleeing their homes.<ref>[https://africa.cgtn.com/2018/09/16/cameroon-intercepts-families-from-fleeing-war-torn-anglophone-region/ Cameroon intercepts families from fleeing war-torn Anglophone region] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180916171051/https://africa.cgtn.com/2018/09/16/cameroon-intercepts-families-from-fleeing-war-torn-anglophone-region/ |date=2018-09-16 }}, CGTN Africa, Sep 16, 2018. Accessed Sep 16, 2018.</ref>\n\nIn August 2018, [[Ministry of Territorial Administration (Cameroon)|Minister of Territorial Administration]] Atanga Nji offered amnesty to separatists who surrender their weapons, saying they would \"be received as prodigal sons\". The minister also announced a plan to rebuild infrastructure that had been destroyed due to the conflict.<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/future-not-bushes-minister-atanga-nji/ Your future is not in the bushes- Minister Atanga Nji] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180823005857/https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/future-not-bushes-minister-atanga-nji/ |date=2018-08-23 }}, Journal du Cameroun, Aug 22, 2018. Accessed Aug 22, 2018.</ref>\n\nBoth sides have used [[WhatsApp]] to spread propaganda.<ref name=\"Dirty War\"/> Cameroonian authorities have arrested journalists on the accusation of propagating false information, the punishment for which is six months to two years in prison.<ref>[https://www.voanews.com/a/cameroon-journalist-jailed-in-anglophone-unrest/4650515.html Cameroon Journalist Jailed in Anglophone Unrest] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181109234807/https://www.voanews.com/a/cameroon-journalist-jailed-in-anglophone-unrest/4650515.html |date=2018-11-09 }}, Voice of America, Nov 8, 2018. Accessed Nov 9, 2018.</ref>\n\n== War crimes ==\n\n===By Cameroon===\n\nThere is photographic evidence that shows a consistent strategy of burning down villages. The army has claimed that the soldiers who were filmed were separatists wearing stolen Cameroonian Army uniforms, a claim that has been denied by local residents. Satellite images show extensive damage to villages. Journalists have been denied entry to the conflict zones, and soldiers have been forbidden from carrying mobile phones.<ref name=burning>[https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-44561929 Burning Cameroon: Images you're not meant to see] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180919204526/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-44561929 |date=2018-09-19 }}, BBC, Jun 25, 2018. Accessed Jun 25, 2018.</ref> In August 2018, the [[Centre for Human Rights and Democracy in Africa]] published a list of 106 villages that had been raided by government forces since October 2017. Citing eyewitness accounts, videos and photos as evidence, the Centre claimed that 71 of these villages had been completely destroyed and depopulated, while the remaining 34 had been partially deserted.<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/chrda-publishes-shocking-list-military-atrocities-cameroons-nw-sw-regions/ CHRDA publishes shocking list of military atrocities in Cameroon\u2019s NW, SW regions] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180822132046/https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/chrda-publishes-shocking-list-military-atrocities-cameroons-nw-sw-regions/ |date=2018-08-22 }}, Journal du Cameroun, Aug 22, 2018. Accessed Aug 22, 2018.</ref>\n\n===By Ambazonia===\n[[File:Government Bilingual High School in Fontem, South West Cameroon.jpg|thumb|right|A destroyed bilingual high school in [[Fontem]].]]\n\nAt the end of 2017, the separatists declared a school boycott, and have attacked and burnt down schools that refused to shut down. Between February 2017 and May 2018, at least 42 schools were targeted.<ref name=burning/> Some separatists consider schools to be legitimate targets because the French language is taught as a mandatory subject.<ref name=EmmanuelFreudenthal/> As of July 2019, close to 6,000 schools had shut down across the Anglophone regions, affecting more than 600,000 children.<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/6000-schools-shut-down-in-restive-anglophone-cameroon/ 6000 schools shut down in restive Anglophone Cameroon], Journal du Cameroun, Jul 30, 2019. Accessed Jul 30, 2019.</ref> In October 2019, separatists began opening their own schools.<ref name=\"community schools\"/>\n\nIn their effort to make the Anglophone regions ungovernable, separatist elements have maimed employees at state-owned corporations.<ref name=\"Cameroon 2019\">[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-armed-men-chop-off-fingers-of-cdc-workers/ Cameroon: Armed men chop off fingers of CDC workers], Journal du Cameroun, Jan 3, 2019. Accessed Jan 3, 2019.</ref> Kidnapping for ransom has also occurred frequently,<ref>[https://reliefweb.int/report/cameroon/schools-fail-open-cameroons-restive-english-speaking-regions Schools Fail to Open in Cameroon's Restive English-speaking Regions] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180904230919/https://reliefweb.int/report/cameroon/schools-fail-open-cameroons-restive-english-speaking-regions |date=2018-09-04 }}, Reliefweb, Sep 4, 2018. Accessed Sep 4, 2018.</ref> as well as blackmailing of civilians into transferring money to fund the struggle.<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-anglophones-forced-to-fund-secessionist-conflict/ Cameroon anglophones \u2018forced to fund\u2019 secessionist conflict], Journal du Cameroun, Jul 17, 2019. Accessed Jul 17, 2019.</ref> Owing to the obscure nature of many of the separatist militias (see [[List of Ambazonian militant groups|list]]), some attacks attributed to separatists may as well be the acts of local criminals. Notwithstanding, it is beyond doubt that separatist elements have carried out numerous such acts,<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-human-rights-watch-accuses-ambazonia-separatists-of-kidnappings/ Cameroon: Human Rights Watch accuses Ambazonia separatists of kidnappings], Journal du Cameroun, Jul 13, 2019. Accessed Jul 13, 2019.</ref> sometimes drawing condemnation from the Interim Government of Ambazonia.<ref name=\"Cameroon 2019\"/>\n\nThroughout 2017, there were no reports of ADF using violence against civilians. As of October 2018, five such incidents had been reported, though these attacks were for the most part not lethal; one civilian death was attributed to an ADF attack. Other separatist groups had attacked civilians 25 times within the same time frame, and were responsible for 13 civilian deaths.<ref name=\"acleddatapickingafight\"/> Separatists have also been accused of using schools and churches as military barracks;<ref>[https://www.christianpost.com/news/churches-turned-into-military-barracks-people-killed-cameroon-christians-cry-out.html Churches turned into military barracks, people killed: Cameroon Christians cry out] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181206162200/https://www.christianpost.com/news/churches-turned-into-military-barracks-people-killed-cameroon-christians-cry-out.html |date=2018-12-06 }}, The Christian Post, Dec 6, 2018. Accessed Dec 6, 2018.</ref> in July 2019, Cameroon accused the separatists of occupying more than 50 schools.<ref>[https://www.voanews.com/africa/cameroon-separatist-fighters-occupy-50-schools Cameroon: Separatist Fighters Occupy 50 Schools], Voice of America, Jul 22, 2019. Accessed Jul 23, 2019.</ref>\n\n==Casualties==\n\nBetween September 2017 and February 2018, Cameroon claimed to have lost 22 soldiers and policemen in the conflict.<ref>[https://ewn.co.za/2018/02/09/we-are-in-a-war-cameroon-unrest-confronted-by-army-offensive 'We are in a war': Cameroon unrest confronted by army offensive], Eyewitness News, Feb 8, 2018. Accessed Jul 23, 2019.</ref> By May, at least 44 soldiers and policemen had been killed.<ref name=\"unfoldingcatastrophe\"/> In June 2018, the official figure rose to 84 dead.<ref>[https://www.reuters.com/article/us-cameroon-separatists/separatists-have-killed-84-troops-since-sept-2017-cameroon-idUSKBN1JG360 Separatists have killed 84 troops since Sept. 2017: Cameroon], Reuters, Jun 20, 2018. Accessed Jul 23, 2019.</ref> Within two weeks in the later half of June, the official figure went up to more than 120 dead.<ref name=100deadvoa/> By October 2018, the military and police had lost at least 175 servicemen. Separatist losses were estimated to be in the hundreds.<ref name=\"reliefweboct10\">[https://reliefweb.int/report/afghanistan/atrocity-alert-no-126-10-october-2018-afghanistan-cameroon-and-democratic Atrocity Alert No. 126 (10 October 2018): Afghanistan, Cameroon and Democratic Republic of the Congo], Relief Web, Oct 10, 2018. Accessed Nov 7, 2018.</ref>\n\nThe war intensified in early 2019. By June, Cameroonian military and police casualties were estimated to be around 500 dead. The separatists had lost around 1,000 fighters.<ref name=\"unfoldingcatastrophe\">[https://www.raoulwallenbergcentre.org/newsfeed/2019/6/4/release-of-landmark-report-on-unfolding-catastrophe-in-cameroon Cameroon-unfolding catastrophe\u2019 evidence of human rights violations and crimes against humanity], Centre for Human Rights and Democracy in Africa (CHRDA), Jun 3, 2019.</ref> While civilian casualties are hard to determine, in May 2019 they were estimated by independent sources to be around 650 killed.<ref name=\"crisisgroupmay22019\">[https://www.crisisgroup.org/africa/central-africa/cameroon/272-crise-anglophone-au-cameroun-comment-arriver-aux-pourparlers Cameroon\u2019s Anglophone Crisis: How to Get to Talks?], Crisis Group, May 2, 2019. Accessed May 2, 2019.</ref> In January the same year, the [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Kumbo|Diocese of Kumbo]] had been able to document 385 civilian deaths in Kumbo alone within the past seven months.<ref>[http://cameroonnewsagency.com/kumbo-diocese-documents-385-deaths-in-7-months/ Kumbo Diocese Documents 385 Deaths In 7 Months], Cameroon News Agency, Mar 29, 2019. Accessed Oct 29, 2019.</ref> In September 2019, independent sources stated that the conflict had claimed the lives of around 3,000 people, counting both combatants and civilians.<ref name=\"3000killed\">[https://www.crisisgroup.org/africa/central-africa/cameroon/cameroons-anglophone-dialogue-work-progress Cameroon\u2019s Anglophone Dialogue: A Work in Progress], CrisisGroup, Sep 26, 2019. Accessed Oct 28, 2019.</ref> By February 2020, between 800 and 1,000 Cameroonian soldiers had been killed.<ref name=\"newhumanitarianfeb62020\"/>\n\nAnglophone groups have disputed these figures. While federalist movements claimed that the conflict had taken 3,000\u20135,000 lives as of the summer of 2019, separatists claimed that between 5,000 and 10,000 people had been killed.<ref name=\"unfoldingcatastrophe\"/>\n\n==Humanitarian consequences==\nBy January 2018, 15,000 people had fled from Southern Cameroons to Nigeria.<ref name=Africa/> This number increased to at least 40,000 people by February.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.africanews.com/2018/02/14/cameroon-separatists-claim-to-have-abducted-missing-soldier/|title=Cameroon separatists claim to have abducted missing soldier|website=Africa News|date=14 February 2018|accessdate=23 April 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180421162750/http://www.africanews.com/2018/02/14/cameroon-separatists-claim-to-have-abducted-missing-soldier/|archive-date=21 April 2018|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> By August 2018, more than 180,000 people had been displaced due to the war.<ref name=atrisk230818>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroons-anglophone-population-risk/ Cameroon\u2019s Anglophone population at risk] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180823122945/https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroons-anglophone-population-risk/ |date=2018-08-23 }}, Journal du Cameroun, Aug 23, 2018. Accessed Aug 23, 2018.</ref> As of May 2019, 530,000 people had been internally displaced, and 35,000 had fled to Nigeria.<ref name=\"crisisgroupmay22019\"/> In June 2019, [[UNICEF]] said that 1.3 million people in the Anglophone regions needed humanitarian aid.<ref>[https://www.unicef.org/press-releases/geneva-palais-briefing-note-situation-children-north-west-and-south-west-regions Geneva Palais briefing note on the situation for children in the North-West and South-West regions of Cameroon], UNICEF, Jun 21, 2019. Accessed Jul 8, 2019.</ref>\n\n== Other consequences ==\nThe conflict has severely harmed the local economy. In June 2018, Cameroon Development Corporation, a state-owned company with 22,000 employees, declared the conflict could lead to the loss of 5,000 jobs on the short term.<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-anglophone-crisis-could-cost-5000-jobs/ Cameroon: Anglophone crisis could cost 5,000 jobs] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180619012714/https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-anglophone-crisis-could-cost-5000-jobs/ |date=2018-06-19 }}, Journal du Cameroon, Jun 18, 2018. Accessed Jun 18, 2018.</ref> In July 2018, Cameroonian NGO ''Human Is Right'' reported that the war had caused a 70 percent increase in unemployment in the agricultural sector. The palm oil and cocoa sectors in Southwest Region had taken a severe blow, with state-owned company Pamol abandoning plantations in some areas. The private company Telcar Cocoa reported that the cocoa production had fallen 80 percent. The NGO suggested that companies make deals with the separatists in order to safeguard their facilities.<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroons-palm-oil-cocoa-sectors-worst-hit-crisis/ Cameroon\u2019s palm oil, cocoa sectors worst hit by crisis] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180719123106/https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroons-palm-oil-cocoa-sectors-worst-hit-crisis/ |date=2018-07-19 }}, Journal du Cameroun, Jul 19, 2018. Accessed Jul 18, 2018.</ref> The separatists aim to prevent the Cameroonian state from getting any income from the Anglophone regions, in order to make cost of controlling the region surpass the benefits.<ref name=thisisagenocide/>\n\nThe conflict has triggered an exodus of the Nigerian business community from Southern Cameroons, as well as Nigerian traders who used to run key markets.<ref>[https://qz.com/1322709/cameroons-anglophone-crisis-sees-nigerian-business-community-flee-as-ambazonia-forces-strike/ Cameroon\u2019s Nigerian business community is fleeing as the Anglophone crisis deepens] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180709153727/https://qz.com/1322709/cameroons-anglophone-crisis-sees-nigerian-business-community-flee-as-ambazonia-forces-strike/ |date=2018-07-09 }}, Quartz, Jul 7, 2018. Accessed Jul 9, 2018.</ref>\n\nThousands of displaced people have fled to protected natural areas, endangering the wildlife there.<ref>[http://africanarguments.org/2018/07/12/cameroon-crisis-threatens-wildlife-people-flee-protected-areas/ Cameroon crisis threatens wildlife as thousands flee to protected areas], African Arguments, Jul 12, 2018. Accessed Jul 12, 2018.</ref>\n\n==Reactions==\n[[File:Southern Cameroonians We Did.JPG|thumb|right|Southern Cameroonian expats marching in support of the Ambazonian cause]]\n\n===Within Cameroon===\n\nThe Anglophone Crisis has become a divisive question in Cameroonian politics. The [[Cameroon People's Democratic Movement]] (CPDM), the ruling party, regards the separatists as terrorists and supports a military solution to the conflict.<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-defence-minister-says-terrorirsts-will-not-be-freed/ Cameroon\u2019s Defence minister says \u201cterrorists\u201d will not be freed] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190327195906/https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-defence-minister-says-terrorirsts-will-not-be-freed/ |date=2019-03-27 }}, Journal du Cameroun, Dec 14, 2018. Accessed Mar 27, 2019.</ref> The CPDM supported both the carrying out and conclusion of the [[Major National Dialogue]], which was organized by the Cameroonian government.<ref name=\"Cameroon 2019. p 12\"/>\n\nMeanwhile, the opposition has been vocal in its criticism of the government's handling of the conflict. In January 2019, the [[Social Democratic Front (Cameroon)|Social Democratic Front]] announced it would oppose any future elections in the country while the war is still ongoing. The party supports a negotiated solution to the conflict, and has demanded a ceasefire, the opening of a dialogue, amnesty for everyone jailed because of the crisis, the establishment of a [[truth and reconciliation commission]], and decentralization of the country.<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/no-elections-in-cameroon-if-anglophone-crisis-persists-sdf-warns-biya/ No elections in Cameroon if Anglophone crisis persists, SDF warns Biya] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190128191136/https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/no-elections-in-cameroon-if-anglophone-crisis-persists-sdf-warns-biya/ |date=2019-01-28 }}, Journal du Cameroun, Jan 22, 2019. Accessed Jan 28, 2019.</ref> In March 2019, the SDF accused members of the Cameroonian government of supporting certain armed elements in the Anglophone regions.<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-sdf-suspects-biya-regime-of-sponsoring-ambazonia-fighters/ Cameroon: SDF suspects Biya regime of sponsoring Ambazonia fighters] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190327194549/https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-sdf-suspects-biya-regime-of-sponsoring-ambazonia-fighters/ |date=2019-03-27 }}, Journal du Cameroun, Mar 27, 2019. Accessed Mar 27, 2019.</ref> In May 2019, the SDF announced it would boycott [[National Day (Cameroon)|National Day]] celebrations in sympathy with people in Southern Cameroons living in a state of civil war.<ref name=\"nationalday2019\">[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-sdf-to-boycott-may-20-celebrations/ Cameroon: SDF to boycott May 20 celebrations], Journal du Cameroun, May 8, 2019. Accessed May 8, 2019.</ref>\n\nSmaller opposition parties, such as the [[Cameroon Renaissance Movement]] (MRC), also blame the government for failing to solve the Anglophone Crisis.<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-maurice-kamto-announces-nationwide-protests-on-january-26/ Cameroon: Maurice Kamto announces nationwide protests on January 26] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190128191123/https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-maurice-kamto-announces-nationwide-protests-on-january-26/ |date=2019-01-28 }}, Journal du Cameroun, Jan 16, 2019. Accessed Jan 28, 2019.</ref> On January 26, 2019, supporters of the MRC invaded the Cameroonian embassy in Paris, citing \u2013 among other reasons \u2013 the Anglophone Crisis.<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/protesters-invade-cameroon-embassies-abroad/ Protesters invade Cameroon embassies abroad] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190128135442/https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/protesters-invade-cameroon-embassies-abroad/ |date=2019-01-28 }}, Journal du Cameroun, Jan 27, 2019. Accessed Jan 28, 2019.</ref> In May 2019, the MRC joined the SDF in boycotting National Day celebrations.<ref name=\"nationalday2019\"/> The Cameroon People's Party has taken a nuanced approach, condemning both the government and the separatists. Party leader [[Kah Walla]] has said that the crisis can be solved by turning Cameroon into a federation.<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-kah-walla-rubbishes-separatist-threats-insists-only-federation-can-solve-anglophone-crisis/ Cameroon: Kah Walla rubbishes separatist threats, insists Federation can solve Anglophone crisis] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190422024152/https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-kah-walla-rubbishes-separatist-threats-insists-only-federation-can-solve-anglophone-crisis/ |date=2019-04-22 }}, Journal du Cameroun, Apr 22, 2019. Accessed Apr 22, 2019.</ref>\n\n===Countries and international organizations===\n{{Main|International reactions to the Anglophone Crisis}}\n\nThe Anglophone Crisis has become a diplomatic challenge to Cameroon, and has damaged the country's relations with some of its allies. While member states of the [[African Union]]<ref name=\"AU\">[https://taarifa.rw/2018/07/12/african-union-intervenes-in-cameroon-crisis/ African Union Intervenes In Cameroon Crisis], Taarifa, Jul 12, 2018. Accessed Jul 12, 2018.</ref> and [[France]]<ref name=\"Arria\">[http://webtv.un.org/live-now/watch/arria-formula-meeting-of-the-un-security-council/6036271424001/?term= Arria-Formula Meeting of the UN Security Council], United Nations, May 13, 2019. Accessed Jul 8, 2019.</ref> have taken either a neutral stance or sided with the Cameroonian government, several European countries and the [[United States]] have criticized Cameroon.<ref name=\"FalloutsUN\">[https://www.hrw.org/news/2019/06/28/africa-should-not-fail-cameroon Africa Should Not Fail Cameroon], Human Rights Watch, Jun 28, 2019. Accessed Jul 8, 2019.</ref> The United States have been particularly vocal in its criticism; In July 2019, following a fact-finding mission by some of its members to the country, the [[United States House of Representatives|House of Representatives]] called for a reintroduction of a federal system in Cameroon.<ref>References:\n*[https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/116/hres358/text H.Res. 358: Calling on the Government of Cameroon and armed groups to respect the human rights of all Cameroonian citizens, to end all violence, and to pursue a broad-based dialogue without preconditions to resolve the conflict in the Northwest and Southwest regions.], [[GovTrack]], Jul 23, 2019. Accessed Jul 25, 2019.\n*{{cite web| url = https://reliefweb.int/report/cameroon/cameroon-north-west-and-south-west-crisis-situation-report-no-9-31-july-2019| title = Cameroon: North-West and South-West Crisis Situation Report No. 9 - As of 31 July 2019| date = September 3, 2019| website = [[ReliefWeb]]| access-date = September 26, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2019, Switzerland announced that both the Cameroonian government and the separatists had asked it to act as a mediator, and that negotiations would take place. This would be the first known case of talks between the two warring sides, and has been met with international endorsement.<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-ambazonia-leaders-agree-to-participate-in-swiss-led-dialogue/ Cameroon: Ambazonia leaders endorse Swiss-led dialogue to solve Anglophone crisis], ''Journal du Cameroun'', Jun 28, 2019. Accessed Jun 28, 2019.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Ongoing military conflicts}}\n{{Post-Cold War African conflicts}}\n\n[[Category:2010s conflicts]]\n[[Category:2020s conflicts]]\n[[Category:Conflicts in 2016]]\n[[Category:Conflicts in 2017]]\n[[Category:Conflicts in 2018]]\n[[Category:Conflicts in 2019]]\n[[Category:Conflicts in 2020]]\n[[Category:2010s in Cameroon]]\n[[Category:Wars of independence]]\n[[Category:Wars involving Cameroon]]\n[[Category:History of Cameroon]]\n[[Category:History of Ambazonia]]\n[[Category:Anglophone Crisis| ]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox military conflict\n| conflict    = Anglophone Crisis\n| partof      = the [[Anglophone problem]]\n| image       = [[File:Map of the Federal Republic of Ambazonia (claimed).png|275px]]\n| image_size  = \n| caption     = {{legend0|#37c837|Undisputed Cameroonian territory}}<br/>{{legend0|#ff2a2a|Part of Cameroon claimed by Ambazonia}}\n| date        = September 9, 2017<ref name=\"Sept 13\"/> \u2013 present<br>({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=09|day1=09|year1=2017}})\n| place       = [[Northwest Region (Cameroon)|Northwest Region]] and [[Southwest Region (Cameroon)|Southwest Region]] ([[Southern Cameroons]]), [[Cameroon]]<br/><small>(With occasional spillover into [[Littoral Region (Cameroon)|Littoral Region]] and [[West Region (Cameroon)|West Region]])</small><ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroonanglophone-crisis-has-spilled-over-francophone-zones-sdf/ Cameroon:Anglophone crisis has spilled over Francophone zones-SDF] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181231205836/https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroonanglophone-crisis-has-spilled-over-francophone-zones-sdf/ |date=2018-12-31 }}, Journal du Cameroun, Dec 31, 2018. Accessed Dec 31, 2018.</ref>\n| territory   = \n| status      = [[List of ongoing armed conflicts|Ongoing]]\n| result      = \n| combatant1  = {{flag|Cameroon|size=22px}}\n| combatant2  = {{flag|Ambazonia|size=22px}}\n| commander1  = [[Paul Biya]]<br>[[Phil\u00e9mon Yang]]<br>[[Joseph Ngute]]<br>[[Ren\u00e9 Claude Meka]]<br/>[[Valere Nka]]\n| commander2  = [[Sisiku Julius Ayuk Tabe|Sisiku Ayuk Tabe]]<br>[[Samuel Ikome Sako]]<br>[[Ayaba Cho Lucas]]<br>[[Ebenezer Akwanga]]\n| units1      = [[Cameroon Armed Forces|FAC]]<br>Vigilante groups<ref name=\"xinhuavigilantes\">[http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2019-10/15/c_138473660.htm Cameroon sees more vigilante groups against insecurity in Anglophone regions], XinhuaNet, Oct 15, 2019. Accessed Oct 15, 2019.</ref>\n| units2      = [[Ambazonia Defence Forces|ADF]]<br>[[Southern Cameroons Defence Forces|SOCADEF]]<br>[[Ambazonia Self-Defence Council|ASC]]<br>[[List of Ambazonian militant groups|Other groups]]\n| strength1   = 12,500 troops, 9,000 militia <small>(total size of army)</small><ref name=\"autogenerated1\">International Institute for Strategic Studies. (2014). Chapter Ten: Country comparisons \u2013 commitments, force levels and economics. ''The Military Balance'', 114(1), 471\u2013492. doi:10.1080/04597222.2014.871887</ref>\n| strength2   = 2,000\u20134,000 fighters<br><small>(as of May 2019)</small><ref name=\"crisisgroupmay22019\"/>\n| casualties1 = 800-1,000 killed<br>{{small|(as of February 2020)}}<ref name=\"newhumanitarianfeb62020\">[https://www.thenewhumanitarian.org/news/2020/02/06/Cameroon-elections-anglophone-separatist-insurgency-Ambazonia Briefing: Cameroon's intensifying conflict and what it means for civilians], The New Humanitarian, Feb 6, 2020. Accessed Feb 8, 2020.</ref>\n| casualties2 = ~1,000 killed<br>{{small|(as of June 2019)}}<ref name=\"unfoldingcatastrophe\"/>\n| casualties3 = ~3,000 killed in total {{small|(as of September 2019)}}<ref name=\"3000killed\"/><br>679,000 internally displaced {{small|(as of January 2020)}}<ref name=\"reliefwebjan212020\">[https://reliefweb.int/sites/reliefweb.int/files/resources/20200121_acaps_short_note_escalation_of_the_anglophone_crisis_cameroon_0.pdf Escalation of the Anglophone crisis], ReliefWeb, Jan 21, 2020. Accessed Apr 12, 2020.</ref><br>51,000 refugees in Nigeria {{small|(as of January 2020)}}<ref name=\"reliefwebjan212020\">[https://reliefweb.int/sites/reliefweb.int/files/resources/20200121_acaps_short_note_escalation_of_the_anglophone_crisis_cameroon_0.pdf Escalation of the Anglophone crisis], ReliefWeb, Jan 21, 2020. Accessed Apr 12, 2020.</ref>\n| notes       = \n| campaignbox = {{Campaignbox Anglophone Crisis}}\n}}\n\nThe '''Anglophone Crisis''' ({{Lang-fr|Crise anglophone}}), also known as the '''Ambazonia War''',<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/ambazonia-war-drowns-sdf-28th-anniversary/ \u2018Ambazonia War\u2019 drowns SDF 28th Anniversary] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181025201919/https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/ambazonia-war-drowns-sdf-28th-anniversary/ |date=2018-10-25 }}, Journal du Cameroun, May 28, 2018. Accessed Oct 25, 2018.</ref> or the '''Cameroonian Civil War''',<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2018/10/06/world/africa/cameroon-election-biya-ambazonia.html Cameroon on Brink of Civil War as English Speakers Recount \u2018Unbearable\u2019 Horrors], The New York Times, Oct 6, 2018. Accessed Apr 27, 2019.</ref> is a conflict in the [[Southern Cameroons]] region of [[Cameroon]], part of the long-standing [[Anglophone problem]].<ref name=Africa>{{cite news|url=https://qz.com/1179202/cameroons-anglophone-crisis-is-threatening-to-spin-out-of-control/|title=Cameroon\u2019s Anglophone crisis is threatening to spin out of control|website=Quartz Africa|date=14 January 2018|accessdate=22 April 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180531194152/https://qz.com/1179202/cameroons-anglophone-crisis-is-threatening-to-spin-out-of-control/|archive-date=31 May 2018|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In September 2017, separatists in the [[English-speaking world|Anglophone]] territories of [[Northwest Region (Cameroon)|Northwest Region]] and [[Southwest Region (Cameroon)|Southwest Region]] (collectively known as Southern Cameroons) declared the independence of [[Ambazonia]] and began fighting against the [[Government of Cameroon]].<ref name=journal>{{cite news|url=https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/deadly-clashes-troops-adf-forces-leave-nguti-brink/|title=Deadly clashes between troops, ADF forces leave Nguti on the brink|website=Journal du Cameroun|date=13 March 2018|accessdate=22 April 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180421094808/https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/deadly-clashes-troops-adf-forces-leave-nguti-brink/|archive-date=21 April 2018|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}.</ref> Starting as a low-scale insurgency, the conflict spread to most parts of the Anglophone regions within a year.<ref name=\"acleddatapickingafight\"/> By the summer of 2019, the government controlled the major cities and parts of the countryside, while the separatists held parts of the countryside and regularly appeared in the major cities.<ref name=\"crisisgroupmay22019\"/>\n\nThe war has killed approximately 3,000 people<ref name=\"3000killed\"/> and forced more than half a million people to flee their homes.<ref name=\"crisisgroupmay22019\"/> Although 2019 has seen the first known instance of dialogue between Cameroon and the separatists,<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-ambazonia-leaders-agree-to-participate-in-swiss-led-dialogue/ Cameroon: Ambazonia leaders endorse Swiss-led dialogue to solve Anglophone crisis], Journal du Cameroun, Jun 28, 2019. Accessed Jun 28, 2019.</ref> as well as a [[Major National Dialogue|state-organized national dialogue]] and the granting of a special status to the Anglophone regions,<ref>[https://www.reuters.com/article/us-cameroon-separatists-lawmaking/cameroon-grants-special-status-to-anglophone-regions-idUSKBN1YO24S Cameroon grants special status to Anglophone regions], Reuters, Dec 20, 2019. Accessed Dec 22, 2019.</ref> the war continued to escalate in late 2019.<ref name=\"voasep242019\">[https://www.voanews.com/africa/cameroons-separatists-intensify-attacks-protest-dialogue Cameroon's Separatists Intensify Attacks to Protest Dialogue], Voice of America, Sep 24, 2019. Accessed Sep 26, 2019.</ref> The [[2020 Cameroonian parliamentary election]] brought further escalation, as the separatists became more assertive while Cameroon deployed additional forces. While the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] saw one armed group declare a unilateral ceasefire to combat the spread of [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]], other groups and the Cameroonian government ignored calls to follow suit and kept on fighting.<ref name=\"voaapr92020\"/>\n\n==Background==\n{{main|Ambazonia#History}}\n{{further|Bakassi conflict}}\n[[File:Monument in Limbe..JPG|thumb|left|Monument raised on the 150th anniversary of the establishment of Victoria at Ambas Bay, from which the name \"Ambazonia\" derives.]]\nThe name \"Ambazonia\" is taken from Ambas Bay and ''Ambozes'', the local name of the mouth of the [[Wouri River]].<ref name=\"Vine2004\">{{cite book|author=Victor T. Le Vine|title=Politics in Francophone Africa|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZVlzpwjhGqgC&pg=PA6|accessdate=9 May 2011|year=2004|publisher=Lynne Rienner Publishers|isbn=9781588262493|pages=6\u2013}}</ref> This is where the English language was permanently established for the first time in Southern Cameroons, when missionary [[Alfred Saker]] founded a settlement of freed slaves by [[Ambas Bay]] in 1858, which was later renamed Victoria (present-day [[Limbe, Cameroon|Limbe]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bakweri.org/2007/03/the_early_times.html|title=The Early Times in Victoria (Limbe)|publisher=|accessdate=26 October 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160307204612/http://www.bakweri.org/2007/03/the_early_times.html|archive-date=7 March 2016|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In 1884, the area became the British Ambas Bay Protectorate, with Victoria as its capital. Britain ceded the area to the [[German Empire|German]] territory of [[Kamerun]] in 1887. Germany had some trouble establishing control over the hinterlands of Victoria, and fought the [[Bafut Wars]] against local [[Fon (title)|fondoms]] until 1907.<ref>The Cameroon Tribune, No. 600, p. 2, December 26, 1996</ref>\n\nFollowing [[World War I]] and the [[Treaty of Versailles]], Kamerun was divided between a [[France|French]] and a British [[League of Nations Mandate]]. The French mandate was known as Cameroun, and comprised most of the former German territory. The British mandate was an elongated strip of land along the border of [[Colonial Nigeria]], consisting of Northern Cameroons and Southern Cameroons, including the historical Ambas Bay Protectorate. This territory was organized as [[British Cameroons]].<ref>Lee, Alexander, and Kenneth A. Schultz. ''Comparing British and French colonial legacies: A discontinuity analysis of Cameroon'', p. 10 APSA 2011 Annual Meeting Paper. 2011.</ref>\n\nThe British administered the territories through [[indirect rule]], allowing native authorities to administer the population according to their own traditions. In 1953, the Southern Cameroons delegation at a conference in London asked for a separate region. The British agreed, and Southern Cameroons became an autonomous region with its capital still at Buea. Elections were held in 1954 and the parliament met on 1 October 1954, with [[E. M. L. Endeley]] as Premier.<ref>DeLancey, Mark W., and Mark Dike DeLancey (2000): ''Historical Dictionary of the Republic of Cameroon'' (3rd ed.). Lanham, Maryland: The Scarecrow Press.</ref>\n\nThe United Nations organised a [[British Cameroons referendum, 1961|plebiscite in the region on 11 February 1961]] which put two alternatives to the people: union with Nigeria or union with Cameroon. The third option, independence, was opposed by the British representative to the UN Trusteeship Council, [[Andrew Cohen (statesman)|Sir Andrew Cohen]], and as a result was not listed. In the plebiscite, 60% of voters in the Northern Cameroons voted for union with Nigeria, while 70% of voters in the Southern Cameroons opted for union with Cameroon.<ref>Nohlen, D, Krennerich, M & Thibaut, B (1999) ''Elections in Africa: A data handbook'', p177 {{ISBN|0-19-829645-2}}</ref> The results owed partly to a fear of domination by much larger Nigeria.<ref>Amaazee, Victor Bong. ''The \u2018Igbo scare\u2019in the British Cameroons, c. 1945\u201361.'' The Journal of African History 31.2 (1990): 281\u2013293.</ref> Endeley was defeated in elections on 1 February 1959 by [[John Ngu Foncha]].<ref>{{cite book|author=Ndi, Anthony|title=Southern West Cameroon Revisited (1950\u20131972) Volume One: Unveiling Inescapable Traps|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hnIYAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA217|date=16 March 2014|publisher=Langaa RPCIG|isbn=978-9956-791-44-6|pages=217\u2013}}</ref>\n\nSouthern Cameroons became part of Cameroon on 1 October 1961 as \"West Cameroon\", with its own [[List of Prime Ministers of Cameroon|prime minister]]. However, the English-speaking peoples of the Southern Cameroons did not believe that they were fairly treated by the French-speaking government of the country. Then-president [[Ahmadou Ahidjo]] feared that Southern Cameroons would secede from the union, taking its natural resources with it. Following a French Cameroon [[Cameroonian constitutional referendum, 1972|unilateral referendum]] on 20 May 1972, a new constitution was adopted in Cameroon which replaced the [[Federal republic|federal]] state with a [[unitary state]], and also gave more power to the president.<ref>[http://africanelections.tripod.com/cm.html Elections in Cameroon] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110903053954/http://africanelections.tripod.com/cm.html |date=2011-09-03 }} African Elections Database</ref> Southern Cameroons lost its autonomous status and became the [[Northwest Region (Cameroon)|Northwest Region]] and the [[Southwest Region (Cameroon)|Southwest Region]] of the Republic of Cameroon. Pro-independence groups claimed that this violated the constitution, as the majority of deputies from West Cameroon had not consented to legitimize the constitutional changes.<ref>Roger, Jules, and Sombaye Eyango. ''Inside the Virtual Ambazonia: Separatism, Hate Speech, Disinformation and Diaspora in the Cameroonian Anglophone Crisis'', p. 28 (2018).</ref> They argued that Southern Cameroons had effectively been [[annexation|annexed]] by Cameroon.<ref>Anyangwe, Carlson. ''Betrayal of Too Trusting a People. The UN, the UK and the Trust Territory of the Southern Cameroons: The UN, the UK and the Trust Territory of the Southern Cameroons'', pp. 108\u2013111. African Books Collective, 2009.</ref> Shortly afterwards, French Cameroun's political leadership changed the constitution again, appointed French-speaking Paul Biya as Prime Minister and successor to Ahmadou Ahidjo ostensibly to deny the Speaker of the House of Assembly [[Salomon Tandeng Muna]] - an Anglophone the possibility of becoming president by succession.\n\nIn a memorandum dated 20 March 1985, Anglophone lawyer and President of the Cameroon Bar Association [[Fongum Gorji Dinka]] wrote that the Cameroonian government led by [[Paul Biya]] was unconstitutional and announced the former Southern Cameroons should become independent as the Republic of Ambazonia. Dinka was incarcerated the following January without trial.<ref>Nkwi; Nchoji, Paul (2015). The Anthropology of Africa: Challenges for the 21st Century (illustrated, reprint ed.), p. 478. Langaa RPCIG. {{ISBN|9789956792795}}.</ref> Three years later, he escaped to Nigeria.<ref>[https://www.ippmedia.com/en/features/cameroon%E2%80%99s-anglophone-war-part-1-rifle-only-way-out Cameroon's anglophone war, Part 1: A rifle as the only way out] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180709062633/https://www.ippmedia.com/en/features/cameroon%E2%80%99s-anglophone-war-part-1-rifle-only-way-out |date=2018-07-09 }}, IPP Media, Jul 9, 2018. Accessed Jul 9, 2018.</ref>\n\nIn 1993, representatives of Anglophone groups convened the first All Anglophone Conference (AAC1) in Buea. The conference issued the \"Buea Declaration\", which called for constitutional amendments to restore the 1961 federation. This was followed by the second All Anglophone Conference (AAC2) in [[Bamenda]] in 1994. This conference issued the \"Bamenda Declaration\", which stated that if the federal state was not restored within a reasonable time, Southern Cameroons would declare its independence. The AAC was renamed the Southern Cameroons Peoples Conference (SCPC), and later the Southern Cameroons Peoples Organisation (SCAPO), with the [[Southern Cameroons National Council]] (SCNC) as the executive governing body. Younger activists formed the Southern Cameroons Youth League (SCYL) in Buea on 28 May 1995. The SCNC sent a delegation, led by John Foncha, to the United Nations, which was received on 1 June 1995 and presented a petition against the 'annexation' of the Southern Cameroons by French Cameroon. This was followed by a signature referendum the same year, which the organisers claim produced a 99% vote in favour of independence with 315,000 people voting.<ref>[http://www.ambazania.org/referendum11.htm Southern Cameroons Peoples Organisation website] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927230920/http://www.ambazania.org/referendum11.htm |date=2007-09-27 }}</ref>\n\nSCNC activities were routinely disrupted by police.<ref name=Murison>{{cite book|title=Africa South of the Sahara 2004|year=2003|publisher=Europa Publications|pages=163\u2013164|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jj4J-AXGDaQC&pg=PA163|editor=Katharine Murison}}</ref> On March 23, 1997, about ten people were killed in a raid on a gendarme camp in [[Bamenda]]. The police arrested between 200 and 300 people, mostly SCNC supporters, but also members of the [[Social Democratic Front (Cameroon)|Social Democratic Front]], an opposition party with significant support in the Anglophone regions.<ref name=\"ecoi\">[https://www.ecoi.net/en/document/1056299.html March 1997 incidents in the north-west province CMR36066.E'], Immigration and Refugee Board of Canada, Jan 31, 2001. Accessed May 10, 2019.</ref> In the subsequent trials, [[Amnesty International]] and the SCNC found substantive evidence of admissions through torture and force.<ref name=Murison/> The raid and trial resulted in a shutdown of SCNC activities.<ref name=CQ>{{cite book|title=Political Handbook of the World 2016\u20132017|year=2017|publisher=CQ Press|pages=236\u2013246|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=UmNCDgAAQBAJ&pg=PA236|editor=Tom Lansdorf|chapter=Cameroon}}</ref> In response to this, in April 1998 a small faction elected Esoka Ndoki Mukete, a high-ranking member of the Social Democratic Front, as the new chair of the SCNC. In October 1999, when many of the accused were found guilty in the 1997 trial, the faction led by Mukete became more assertive. On 1 October 1999, militants took over Radio Buea to proclaim the independence of Southern Cameroons, but failed to do so before security forces intervened.<ref>Elong, Eric Ebolo. ''Sovereignty in the Making: The Case of Anglophone Cameroon. 2'', p. 24</ref> The leadership and many members of the SCNC were subsequently arrested.<ref name=CQ/> After clashes with the police, the SCNC was officially declared illegal by the Cameroonian authorities in 2001.<ref>[http://www.thenewhumanitarian.org/news/2007/02/19/secessionist-minority-anglophone-group-silenced Secessionist minority Anglophone group silenced], The New Humanitarian, Feb 19, 2007. Accessed Oct 27, 2019.</ref> In 2006, a faction of SCNC once again declared the independence of Ambazonia.<ref name=CQ>{{cite book|title=Political Handbook of the World 2016\u20132017|year=2017|publisher=CQ Press|pages=236\u2013246|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=UmNCDgAAQBAJ&pg=PA236|editor=Tom Lansdorf|chapter=Cameroon}}</ref>\n\nIn 2006, Nigeria ceded the [[Bakassi|Bakassi Peninsula]] to Cameroon, ending a decade-long territorial dispute. Local militias opposing the border change took up arms against the Cameroonian government, starting the [[Bakassi conflict]]. The conflict was a sea-based insurgency where the rebels used pirate tactics, attacking ships, abducting sailors and carrying out seaborne raids as far away as [[Limbe, Cameroon|Limbe]] and [[Douala]]. While some movements (such as [[Bakassi Movement for Self-Determination|BAMOSD]]) sought to make Bakassi an independent state, others came to tie their cause to that of Ambazonia. In November 2007, the \"Liberators of the Southern Cameroon People\", a previously unknown group, killed 21 Cameroonian soldiers. Most militias in Bakassi laid down their arms in September 2009.<ref name=\"bakassi\">[https://www.refworld.org/docid/4cf4dafc2.html Cameroon Rebels Threaten Security in Oil-Rich Gulf of Guinea] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190329001435/https://www.refworld.org/docid/4cf4dafc2.html |date=2019-03-29 }}, Ref World, Nov 24, 2010. Accessed Mar 28, 2019.</ref>\n\n== Prelude ==\n{{main|2016\u20132017 Cameroonian protests}}\nOn October 6, 2016, the [[Cameroon Anglophone Civil Society Consortium]], an organization consisting of lawyer and teacher trade unions in the Anglophone regions, initiated a strike.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-cameroon-protests/trial-over-cameroons-anglophone-protests-exposes-national-divide-idUSKBN15S1UH|title=Trial over Cameroon's Anglophone protests exposes national divide|last=|first=|date=13 February 2017|work=Reuters|access-date=2017-09-13|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170908155639/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-cameroon-protests/trial-over-cameroons-anglophone-protests-exposes-national-divide-idUSKBN15S1UH|archive-date=8 September 2017|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Led by Barrister [[Agbor Balla]], [[Fontem Neba]], and Tassang Wilfred, they were protesting against the appointment of [[French language|Francophone]] judges in the Anglophone regions.<ref>{{cite web|title=Rights groups call for probe into protesters' deaths in Cameroon|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2016/12/15/world/cameroon-protesters-deaths/index.html|website=CNN|access-date=2019-03-05|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170829213619/http://edition.cnn.com/2016/12/15/world/cameroon-protesters-deaths/index.html|archive-date=2017-08-29|url-status=dead|df=}}</ref> They saw this as threatening the [[common law]] system in the Anglophone regions,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://qz.com/845783/cameroon-protests-are-growing-over-the-anglophone-francophone-split/|title=Mass protests in Cameroon are exposing the fragility of its dual French-English system|publisher=|access-date=2019-03-05|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180625021637/https://qz.com/845783/cameroon-protests-are-growing-over-the-anglophone-francophone-split/|archive-date=2018-06-25|url-status=dead|df=}}</ref> as well as part of the general marginalization of Anglophones.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newsweek.com/cameroon-anglophone-problem-paul-biya-556151|title=What you need to know about Cameroon's Anglophone protests|date=13 February 2017|publisher=|access-date=5 March 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190402111124/https://www.newsweek.com/cameroon-anglophone-problem-paul-biya-556151|archive-date=2 April 2019|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The strikes were supported by peaceful protests in the cities of [[Bamenda]], [[Buea]] and [[Limbe, Cameroon|Limbe]]. The activists demanded protection of the law system of the Anglophone regions, and opposed the civil law system used by the Francophone magistrate replacing the common law system. They asked for several laws to be translated into English, and that the common law system should be taught at the [[University of Buea]] and the [[University of Bamenda]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://contranocendi.org/index.php/en/news/88-anglophone-cameroon-common-law-lawyers-protest|title=Anglophone Cameroon Common Law Lawyers Protest \u2013 Contra Nocendi International|last=|first=|date=|website=contranocendi.org|language=en-gb|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170903035849/http://contranocendi.org/index.php/en/news/88-anglophone-cameroon-common-law-lawyers-protest|archive-date=2017-09-03|url-status=dead|access-date=2017-09-13|df=}}</ref>\n\nThe Cameroonian government deployed security forces to crack down the protests. Protesters were attacked with tear gas, and protesters and lawyers were allegedly assaulted by soldiers.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.stopblablacam.com/culture-and-society/1511-199-two-anglophone-lawyers-beaten-up-in-buea|title=(True or False?) Two Anglophone lawyers beaten up in Buea \u2013 StopBlaBlaCam|last=|first=|date=|work=StopBlaBlaCam|access-date=2017-09-13|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170903032428/http://www.stopblablacam.com/culture-and-society/1511-199-two-anglophone-lawyers-beaten-up-in-buea|archive-date=2017-09-03|url-status=dead|language=en-gb|df=}}</ref> Throughout November 2016, thousands of teachers in the Anglophone regions joined the lawyers' strike. All schools in the Anglophone regions were shut down.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2016/12/cameroon-teachers-lawyers-strike-english-161205095929616.html|title=Cameroon teachers, lawyers strike in battle for English|website=www.aljazeera.com|access-date=2017-09-13|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170912143932/http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2016/12/cameroon-teachers-lawyers-strike-english-161205095929616.html|archive-date=2017-09-12|url-status=dead|df=}}</ref>\n\nTwo weeks into the protests, more than 100 protesters had been arrested, and six were reported dead. Unconfirmed videos released over social media showed various violent scenes, including the beating of protesters by policemen.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-38078238|title=Arrests in Cameroon language protests|date=2016-11-23|work=BBC News|access-date=2017-09-13|language=en-GB|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170911183649/http://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-38078238|archive-date=2017-09-11|url-status=dead|df=}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2017, the Cameroonian government set up a committee to initiate a dialogue with the lawyer activists. The lawyers refused to talk, demanding that all arrested activists be released before any dialogue. The lawyers submitted a draft for a federal state, and the government responded by banning their movements altogether. The protesters were now openly regarded as a security threat by the Cameroonian government, and more arrests followed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://thestandardtribune.com/2017/01/17/the-government-just-banned-scnc-and-consortium/|title=The Government Just Banned SCNC and Consortium \u2039 The Standard Tribune|website=thestandardtribune.com|language=en-US|access-date=2017-09-13|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170903034357/http://thestandardtribune.com/2017/01/17/the-government-just-banned-scnc-and-consortium/|archive-date=2017-09-03|url-status=dead|df=}}</ref> The government also implemented an Internet blockade in cities across the Anglophone regions.<ref name=\":11\">{{Cite web|url=http://pctechmag.com/2017/01/just-in-internet-blocked-in-bamenda-regions-of-cameroon/|title=JUST IN: Internet Blocked in Bamenda Regions of Cameroon|last=|first=|date=January 18, 2016|website=pctechmag.com|publisher=|access-date=January 18, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170120103538/http://pctechmag.com/2017/01/just-in-internet-blocked-in-bamenda-regions-of-cameroon/|archive-date=January 20, 2017|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nAt this point, the crisis began to attract international responses. More than 13,000 Anglophone Cameroonians living in Maryland protested against the Cameroonian government crackdown. On June 27, United States Congressman [[Anthony G. Brown]] filed a petition with the [[United States Secretary of State]], [[Rex Tillerson]], to call for the government of Cameroon to immediately show concern and solve the ongoing crises.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://journalducameroun.com/en/anglophone-protests-pressure-united-states-congress/|title=Anglophone protests: More pressure from United States\u2019 congress|last=|first=|date=2017-06-27|work=Journal du Cameroun|access-date=2017-09-13|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170905141504/http://journalducameroun.com/en/anglophone-protests-pressure-united-states-congress/|archive-date=2017-09-05|url-status=dead|language=en-US|df=}}</ref> The [[United States]] condemned the loss of life and brutality against Anglophone protesters.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://cameroon-concord.com/headlines/7378-cameroon-strike-the-united-stares-expresses-concern-over-the-loss-of-life-and-brutality-against-anglophone-protesters|title=Cameroon Strike: The United States expresses concern over the loss of life and brutality against anglophone protesters|work=Cameroon Concord|access-date=2017-09-13|language=en-gb|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170905143801/http://cameroon-concord.com/headlines/7378-cameroon-strike-the-united-stares-expresses-concern-over-the-loss-of-life-and-brutality-against-anglophone-protesters|archive-date=2017-09-05|url-status=dead|df=}}</ref>\n\nThe government crackdown on the protests contributed to mainstream separatist movements. In September 2017, Ambazonian separatists began to take up arms against the government.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dw.com/en/english-speakers-protest-in-cameroon-demand-equal-rights-amid-calls-for-secession/a-40649852|title=English speakers protest in Cameroon, demand equal rights amid calls for secession \u2013 News \u2013 DW \u2013 22.09.2017|first=Deutsche Welle|last=(www.dw.com)|website=DW.COM|access-date=2019-03-05|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180125091747/http://www.dw.com/en/english-speakers-protest-in-cameroon-demand-equal-rights-amid-calls-for-secession/a-40649852|archive-date=2018-01-25|url-status=dead|df=}}</ref>\n\n==Timeline==\n\n{{Main|Timeline of the Anglophone Crisis}}\n\n===2017===\n\n{{Main|Timeline of the Anglophone Crisis (2017)}}\n\nIn early September, 2017, the [[Ambazonia Governing Council]] (AGovC), a separatist movement established in 2013 through the merger of several groups,<ref name=\"crisisgroupmay22019\"/> formally deployed the [[Ambazonia Defence Forces]] (ADF) in Southern Cameroons. On September 9, the ADF carried out its first military action, attacking a military base in Besongabang, [[Manyu (department)|Manyu]]. Three Cameroonian soldiers were killed in the attack, while the ADF claimed their soldiers managed to return to base unreduced.<ref name=\"Sept 13\">[https://www.dailynewscameroon.com/breaking-news-explosions-in-bamenda-and-killings-in-besongabang-military-base-adf-claims-responsibility/ Explosions in Bamenda and Killings in Besongabang Military Base, ADF Claims Responsibility] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191223171302/https://www.dailynewscameroon.com/breaking-news-explosions-in-bamenda-and-killings-in-besongabang-military-base-adf-claims-responsibility/ |date=2019-12-23 }}, Daily News Cameroon, Sept 14, 2017. Accessed Apr 19, 2018.</ref> Throughout September, separatists carried out two bombings; one targeting security forces in [[Bamenda]],<ref>[https://qz.com/1084943/cameroons-anglophone-crisis-turns-violent-as-president-paul-biya-speak-at-unga-2017/ The crisis in Cameroon\u2019s English-speaking regions has turned violent with bombings] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180419183806/https://qz.com/1084943/cameroons-anglophone-crisis-turns-violent-as-president-paul-biya-speak-at-unga-2017/ |date=2018-04-19 }}, Quartz, Sept 22, 2017. Accessed Apr 19, 2018.</ref> and another targeting police officers. While the first bombing failed, the second injured three policemen.<ref>[https://www.reuters.com/article/us-cameroon-politics-blast/suspected-separatist-bomb-wounds-3-police-in-cameroons-anglophone-region-idUSKCN1BW2C9 Suspected separatist bomb wounds 3 police in Cameroon's Anglophone region] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180419183403/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-cameroon-politics-blast/suspected-separatist-bomb-wounds-3-police-in-cameroons-anglophone-region-idUSKCN1BW2C9 |date=2018-04-19 }}, Reuters, Sept 21, 2017. Accessed Apr 19, 2018.</ref> On September 22, Cameroonian soldiers opened fire on protesters, killing at least five and injuring many more.<ref name=\"22Sep\">{{cite news|url=https://qz.com/1086706/cameroon-is-on-edge-after-security-forces-opened-fire-on-anglophone-region-protesters/|title=Cameroon is on edge after security forces opened fire on Anglophone protesters|website=Quartz Africa|date=22 September 2017|accessdate=10 May 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180419183909/https://qz.com/1086706/cameroon-is-on-edge-after-security-forces-opened-fire-on-anglophone-region-protesters/|archive-date=19 April 2018|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Street of Buea (SW Region Cameroon) on a Ghost town day 2.jpg|thumb|right|Streets of Buea on a ghost town day, September 30.]]\n\nOn October 1, the [[Southern Cameroons Ambazonia Consortium United Front]] (SCACUF), an umbrella movement consisting of several independence movements, unilaterally declared the independence of Ambazonia. This declaration was followed by mass demonstrations across the Anglophone regions. The separatists strategically chose this date, as it is the anniversary for the unification of Cameroon and Southern Cameroons. SCACUF would later transform itself into the [[Interim Government of Ambazonia]] (IG). Several months into the war, the IG would reject the idea of an armed struggle, preferring instead a diplomatic campaign and [[civil disobedience]]. This stance would eventually change.<ref>[https://allafrica.com/stories/201712220550.html Cameroon: Anglophone Crisis - Dialogue Remains the Only Viable Solution], AllAfrica, Dec 7, 2017. Accessed Mar 9, 2019.</ref>\n\nThe Cameroonian Army moved into the regions in force to fight the separatists and quell the demonstrations. Throughout the day, at least eight demonstrators were killed in [[Buea]] and Bamenda.<ref name=\"2 Oct\">{{cite news|url=https://www.euractiv.com/section/languages-culture/news/several-killed-in-cameroon-as-anglophones-declare-independent-ambazonia/|title=Several killed in Cameroon as anglophones declare \u2018independent Ambazonia\u2019|website=Euractiv|date=2 October 2017|accessdate=10 May 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180420074508/https://www.euractiv.com/section/languages-culture/news/several-killed-in-cameroon-as-anglophones-declare-independent-ambazonia/|archive-date=20 April 2018|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The Cameroonian military also reinforced the Nigerian border, and on October 9, it claimed to have stopped \"hundreds of Nigerian fighters\" from crossing into Cameroon.<ref>[http://www.dw.com/en/cameroonian-troops-deploy-heavily-along-nigeria-border/a-40877538 Cameroonian troops deploy heavily along Nigeria border] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180420074620/http://www.dw.com/en/cameroonian-troops-deploy-heavily-along-nigeria-border/a-40877538 |date=2018-04-20 }}, DW, Oct 9, 2017. Accessed Apr 20, 2018.</ref>\n\nThroughout November, eight soldiers, at least 14 civilians and five fugitives were confirmed killed due to the conflict.<ref name=\"Nov 29\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nation.co.ke/news/africa/4-Cameroon-soldiers-killed/1066-4207694-10cknvr/index.html|title=Four Cameroon soldiers killed in restive Anglophone region|website=Daily Nation|date=29 November 2017|accessdate=5 May 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180421095229/https://www.nation.co.ke/news/africa/4-Cameroon-soldiers-killed/1066-4207694-10cknvr/index.html|archive-date=21 April 2018|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Separatists killed two [[Gendarmerie|gendarmes]] in Bamenda in the first week of the month.<ref>[https://www.reuters.com/article/us-cameroon-politics/cameroon-separatists-kill-at-least-two-gendarmes-as-anglophone-dispute-escalates-idUSKBN1D81PH Cameroon separatists kill at least two gendarmes as Anglophone dispute escalates] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180421030447/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-cameroon-politics/cameroon-separatists-kill-at-least-two-gendarmes-as-anglophone-dispute-escalates-idUSKBN1D81PH |date=2018-04-21 }}, Reuters, Nov 8, 2017. Accessed Apr 20, 2018.</ref> On the last two days of November, five soldiers and five policemen were killed in two separate separatist attacks near [[Mamfe]].<ref name=\"voanov302017\">[https://www.voanews.com/africa/five-police-five-soldiers-killed-cameroon-violence Five Police, Five Soldiers Killed in Cameroon Violence], Voice of America, Nov 30, 2017. Accessed Nov 17, 2019.</ref> On December 1, the Cameroonian government ordered the evacuation of 16 villages in Manyu ahead of a military offensive,<ref>[https://ewn.co.za/2017/12/07/cameroon-govt-forces-accused-of-murder-rape Cameroon govt forces accused of murder, rape] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180825180008/https://ewn.co.za/2017/12/07/cameroon-govt-forces-accused-of-murder-rape |date=2018-08-25 }}, Eyewitness News. Accessed Aug 25, 2018.</ref> and on December 4 it formally declared war on the separatists.<ref name=\"Dec 4\">[https://www.irinnews.org/analysis/2017/12/04/cameroon-government-declares-war-secessionist-rebels Cameroon government \u2018declares war\u2019 on secessionist rebels] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180421162931/https://www.irinnews.org/analysis/2017/12/04/cameroon-government-declares-war-secessionist-rebels |date=2018-04-21 }}, Irin, Dec 4, 2017. Accessed Apr 21, 2018.</ref> The Cameroonian Army moved into Manyu, retaking two villages on December 7<ref>[https://www.voanews.com/a/cameroon-military-moves-in-on-separatist-held-villages-/4153553.html Cameroon's Military Moves In on Separatist-held Villages] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180421094649/https://www.voanews.com/a/cameroon-military-moves-in-on-separatist-held-villages-/4153553.html |date=2018-04-21 }}, Voice of America, Dec 7, 2017. Accessed Apr 21, 2018.</ref> and securing Mamfe by December 15, partly with elite troops.<ref>[http://cameroonnewsagency.com/days-sporadic-gun-shots-mamfe-relative-calm-returns-massive-exodus/ After Days of Sporadic Gun Shots In Mamfe: Relative Calm Returns, Massive Exodus] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181125115427/http://cameroonnewsagency.com/days-sporadic-gun-shots-mamfe-relative-calm-returns-massive-exodus/ |date=2018-11-25 }}, Cameroon News Agency, December 15, 2017. Accessed Nov 24, 2018.</ref> During the offensive, the ADF carried out guerrilla attacks on the Cameroonian Army,<ref>[https://www.voanews.com/a/separatists-attack-cameroon-police/4156497.html Separatists Attack Cameroon Police] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180421162751/https://www.voanews.com/a/separatists-attack-cameroon-police/4156497.html |date=2018-04-21 }}, Voice of America, Dec 9, 2017. Accessed Apr 21, 2018.</ref> killing at least seven soldiers throughout December.<ref name=\"jan62018\">[http://cameroon-concord.com/boko-haram/anglophone-crisis-seven-military-personnel-murdered-in-december-icg-says Anglophone Crisis \u2013 Seven military personnel murdered in December \u2013 ICG says] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180704203403/http://cameroon-concord.com/boko-haram/anglophone-crisis-seven-military-personnel-murdered-in-december-icg-says |date=2018-07-04 }}, Cameroon Concord, Jan 6, 2018. Accessed Aug 25, 2018.</ref> On December 18, the Cameroonian Army began to destroy dozens of civilian homes in retaliation, and killed several civilians.<ref name=\"jan62018\">[http://cameroon-concord.com/boko-haram/anglophone-crisis-seven-military-personnel-murdered-in-december-icg-says Anglophone Crisis \u2013 Seven military personnel murdered in December \u2013 ICG says] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180704203403/http://cameroon-concord.com/boko-haram/anglophone-crisis-seven-military-personnel-murdered-in-december-icg-says |date=2018-07-04 }}, Cameroon Concord, Jan 6, 2018. Accessed Aug 25, 2018.</ref> The December offensive also saw occasional spillover across the Nigerian border.<ref name=\"Dec 20\">[https://www.reuters.com/article/us-cameroon-separatists-nigeria/exclusive-cameroonian-troops-entered-nigeria-without-seeking-authorization-sources-in-nigeria-say-idUSKBN1EE2II Cameroonian troops entered Nigeria without seeking authorization, sources in Nigeria say] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180421094816/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-cameroon-separatists-nigeria/exclusive-cameroonian-troops-entered-nigeria-without-seeking-authorization-sources-in-nigeria-say-idUSKBN1EE2II |date=2018-04-21 }}, Reuters, Dec 20, 2017. Accessed Apr 21, 2018.</ref>\n\nBy the end of 2017, several separatist militias had emerged, with the ADF standing out as the most prominent one.<ref name=\"forces\">[https://www.nation.co.ke/news/africa/The-Cameroon-English-speaking-separatists/1066-4312292-omwos6/index.html Who are Cameroon's English-speaking separatists?] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180423042915/https://www.nation.co.ke/news/africa/The-Cameroon-English-speaking-separatists/1066-4312292-omwos6/index.html |date=2018-04-23 }}, Daily Nation, Feb 20, 2018. Accessed Apr 22, 2018.</ref> During the guerrilla campaign in [[Manyu (department)|Manyu]] and [[Mezam]], it had clashed with the army 13 times.<ref name=\"BBCoct42018\"/> The separatists had also spread out, and by the end of the year, they were active in five [[Departments of Cameroon|departments]].<ref name=\"acleddatapickingafight\">[https://www.acleddata.com/2018/09/21/picking-a-fight-the-rise-of-armed-separatists-in-cameroon/ Picking a Fight: The Rise of Armed Separatists in Cameroon], ACLED. Accessed Nov 17, 2018.</ref>\n\n===2018===\n\n{{Main|Timeline of the Anglophone Crisis (2018)}}\n\nThe separatists suffered a major setback at the beginning of 2018. On January 5, members of the Ambazonia Interim Government were detained by Nigerian authorities,<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/jan/07/cameroon-separatist-leader-julius-ayuk-tabe-detained-in-nigeria Cameroon separatist leader detained in Nigeria as unrest grows] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180407165046/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/jan/07/cameroon-separatist-leader-julius-ayuk-tabe-detained-in-nigeria |date=2018-04-07 }}. The Guardian, Jan 7, 2018. Accessed Apr 19, 2018.</ref> which proceeded to hand them over to Cameroon. A total of 69 leaders and activists were [[Extradition|extradited]] to Cameroon and subsequently arrested, including [[President of Ambazonia|President]] [[Sisiku Julius Ayuk Tabe]]. Since most of the individuals had submitted asylum claims,<ref name=\"leadership UNPO\">{{cite news|url=http://unpo.org/article/20701|title=Ambazonia: Nigeria Hands over 47 Asylum-seekers to Cameroonian Authorities|website=UNPO|date=26 March 2018|accessdate=10 May 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180505144624/http://unpo.org/article/20701|archive-date=5 May 2018|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> the deportation immediately became controversial, as it possibly violated the Nigerian constitution.<ref name=\"journalducameroun.com\">[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-ambazonia-leaders-appear-before-judge-at-military-tribunal/ Cameroon: Ambazonia leaders appear before judge at military tribunal] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190415183927/https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-ambazonia-leaders-appear-before-judge-at-military-tribunal/ |date=2019-04-15 }}, Journal du Cameroun, Nov 28, 2018. Accessed Jan 13, 2019.</ref> They spent 10 months at a [[Gendarmerie|gendarme]] headquarters, before being transferred to a maximum security prison in [[Yaound\u00e9]].<ref name=\"journalducameroun.com\"/> [[Samuel Ikome Sako]] was announced as Acting President on February 4, replacing Tabe for the time being.<ref name=\"Sako\">[http://cameroonnewsagency.com/just-dr-samuel-ikome-sako-new-acting-interim-president-federal-republic-ambazonia/ Just In-Dr Samuel Ikome Sako Is New Acting Interim President of The \u2018Federal Republic of Ambazonia\u2019] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180419193452/http://cameroonnewsagency.com/just-dr-samuel-ikome-sako-new-acting-interim-president-federal-republic-ambazonia/ |date=2018-04-19 }}, Cameroon News Agency, Feb 4, 2018. Accessed Apr 19, 2018.</ref>\n\nJanuary saw an escalation in guerrilla attacks on symbolic targets,<ref>[http://cameroonnewsagency.com/tension-bangem-administrative-authorities-held-gunmen/ Tension In Bangem, Administrative Authorities Held By Gunmen] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181125073958/http://cameroonnewsagency.com/tension-bangem-administrative-authorities-held-gunmen/ |date=2018-11-25 }}, Cameroon News Agency, Jan 29, 2018. Accessed Nov 24, 2018.</ref> as well as repeated spillover into Nigeria.<ref>[https://www.reuters.com/article/us-cameroon-separatists-nigeria/gunmen-cross-from-nigeria-attack-cameroon-border-post-witnesses-idUSKBN1FE1LH Gunmen cross from Nigeria, attack Cameroon border post: witnesses] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180829072118/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-cameroon-separatists-nigeria/gunmen-cross-from-nigeria-attack-cameroon-border-post-witnesses-idUSKBN1FE1LH |date=2018-08-29 }}, Reuters, Jan 25, 2018. Accessed Aug 28, 2018.</ref> The separatists began to target traditional village chiefs, as well as local administrators whom they accused of siding with the security forces.<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/local-chief-murdered-mundemba-separatists/ Local chief murdered in Mundemba by separatists] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180717013218/https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/local-chief-murdered-mundemba-separatists/ |date=2018-07-17 }}, Journal du Cameroun, Feb 12, 2018. Accessed Jul 16, 2018.</ref> Attacks on gendarmes intensified,<ref name=\"thursfeb1\">[https://www.reuters.com/article/us-cameroon-separatists-france/france-condemns-killings-in-cameroon-urges-dialogue-idUSKBN1FM1VL France condemns killings in Cameroon, urges dialogue] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180709153706/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-cameroon-separatists-france/france-condemns-killings-in-cameroon-urges-dialogue-idUSKBN1FM1VL |date=2018-07-09 }}, Reuters, Feb 2, 2018. Accessed Jul 9, 2018.</ref> and gunmen also began to target schools to enforce a school boycott.<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/primary-chool-teacher-slaughtered-suspected-separatists-etam/ Head teacher slaughtered by suspected separatists in Etam] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180825180056/https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/primary-chool-teacher-slaughtered-suspected-separatists-etam/ |date=2018-08-25 }}, Journal du Cameroun, Feb 21, 2018. Accessed Aug 25, 2018.</ref> On February 24, separatists abducted the government's regional representative for social affairs in the [[Northwest Region (Cameroon)|Northwest Region]], apparently looking to exchange him for imprisoned separatist activists.<ref>[http://www.janes.com/article/78199/kidnapping-of-government-officials-highlights-risks-to-companies-in-cameroon-s-anglophone-regions-deemed-to-be-unfairly-exploiting-resources Kidnapping of government officials highlights risks to companies in Cameroon\u2019s Anglophone regions deemed to be unfairly exploiting resources] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180421094911/http://www.janes.com/article/78199/kidnapping-of-government-officials-highlights-risks-to-companies-in-cameroon-s-anglophone-regions-deemed-to-be-unfairly-exploiting-resources |date=2018-04-21 }}, Janes' 360, Feb 27, 2018. Accessed Apr 21, 2018.</ref>\n\nThe [[Battle of Batibo]] was fought on March 3,<ref>[http://www.cameroonpostline.com/3-villages-razed-in-batibo-4-deserted-after-bloody-attack-collateral-casualties-overwhelmed-local-administrators/ 3 Villages Razed In Batibo, 4 Deserted After Bloody Attack *Collateral Casualties Overwhelmed Local Administrators] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180901151211/http://www.cameroonpostline.com/3-villages-razed-in-batibo-4-deserted-after-bloody-attack-collateral-casualties-overwhelmed-local-administrators/ |date=2018-09-01 }}, Cameroon Postline, Mar 9, 2018. Accessed Sep 1, 2018.</ref> producing unprecedented casualties on both sides<ref name=\"mar202018\">[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/security-forces-rescue-three-hostages-ambazonia-fighters/ Security forces rescue three hostages from Ambazonia fighters] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180825180111/https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/security-forces-rescue-three-hostages-ambazonia-fighters/ |date=2018-08-25 }}, Journal du Cameroun, Mar 20, 2018. Accessed Aug 25, 2018.</ref> and forcing over 4,000 locals to flee.<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/4000-persons-batibo-displaced-deadly-clashes-gunmen-security-forces/ 4000 persons in Batibo displaced after deadly clashes between gunmen and security forces] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180825180050/https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/4000-persons-batibo-displaced-deadly-clashes-gunmen-security-forces/ |date=2018-08-25 }}, Journal du Cameroun, Mar 8, 2018. Accessed Aug 25, 2018.</ref> On March 20, Cameroonian soldiers freed two Cameroonian and one Tunisian hostage in [[Meme (department)|Meme Department]].<ref name=\"mar202018\"/> A similar operation freed seven Swiss, six Cameroonian and five Italian hostages on April 4, prompting the [[Ambazonia Defence Forces|ADF]] to declare that it did not take hostages nor target foreigners.<ref>[https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-43640886 Cameroon frees European hostages taken in Anglophone area] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180703054329/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-43640886 |date=2018-07-03 }}, BBC, Apr 4, 2018. Accessed Apr 28, 2018.</ref> On April 25, separatists forced the Cameroonian Army to retreat from the town of [[Belo, Cameroon|Belo]].<ref>[http://www.africanews.com/2018/04/27/cameroon-separatists-force-army-to-retreat-after-face-off-in-northwest/ Cameroon separatists force army to retreat after face off in Northwest] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180427100748/http://www.africanews.com/2018/04/27/cameroon-separatists-force-army-to-retreat-after-face-off-in-northwest// |date=2018-04-27 }}, Africa News, Apr 27, 2018. Accessed Apr 27, 2018.</ref>\n\nThroughout May, there were heavy clashes in [[Mbonge]]<ref name=\"2May\">{{cite news|url=http://cameroon-concord.com/boko-haram/anglophone-crisis-three-soldiers-killed-in-mbonge|title=Anglophone Crisis: Three soldiers killed in Mbonge|website=Cameroon Concord|date=3 May 2018|accessdate=10 May 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180507045116/http://www.cameroon-concord.com/boko-haram/anglophone-crisis-three-soldiers-killed-in-mbonge|archive-date=7 May 2018|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> and [[Muyuka]], resulting in heavy casualties.<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/travellers-stranded-deadly-clashes-muyuka/ Travellers stranded after deadly clashes in Muyuka] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180620124820/https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/travellers-stranded-deadly-clashes-muyuka/ |date=2018-06-20 }}, Journal du Cameroun, May 7, 2018. Accessed Jun 20, 2018.</ref> On May 20, in an effort to boycott celebrations of Cameroon's [[National Day (Cameroon)|National Day]], Ambazonian forces struck in several villages throughout Southern Cameroons, including [[Konye, Cameroon|Konye]], [[Batibo]] and Ekona,<ref name=\"May20\">[http://www.janes.com/article/80201/fighting-attacks-on-timber-and-fuel-trucks-in-anglophone-cameroon-likely-to-rise-shortly-before-october-elections Fighting, attacks on timber and fuel trucks in Anglophone Cameroon likely to rise shortly before October elections] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180523011733/http://www.janes.com/article/80201/fighting-attacks-on-timber-and-fuel-trucks-in-anglophone-cameroon-likely-to-rise-shortly-before-october-elections |date=2018-05-23 }}, Jane's 360, May 21, 2018. Accessed May 22, 2018.</ref> and abducted the mayor of the town of [[Bangem]].<ref>[http://allafrica.com/stories/201805210260.html Cameroon: Killings, Kidnappings Mars National Day Celebrations ] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180521103447/http://allafrica.com/stories/201805210260.html |date=2018-05-21 }}, allAfrica, May 21, 2018. Accessed May 21, 2018.</ref> On May 24, Cameroonian soldiers killed at least 30 people while storming a hotel in Pinyin.<ref>[https://www.voanews.com/a/dozens-of-cameroon-youth-killed-in-south/4411815.html Dozens of Cameroon Youth Killed in South] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180527194114/https://www.voanews.com/a/dozens-of-cameroon-youth-killed-in-south/4411815.html |date=2018-05-27 }}, Voanews, May 27, 2018. Accessed May 27, 2018.</ref> By the end of May, Cameroon had also retaken Belo, though fighting continued around the town, which was almost completely abandoned by its inhabitants.<ref name=thisisagenocide>[https://www.theguardian.com/global-development/2018/may/30/cameroon-killings-escalate-anglophone-crisis 'This is a genocide': villages burn as war rages in blood-soaked Cameroon] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180601174340/https://www.theguardian.com/global-development/2018/may/30/cameroon-killings-escalate-anglophone-crisis |date=2018-06-01 }}, The Guardian, May 20, 2018. Accessed Jun 1, 2018.</ref>\n\nIn mid-June, Ambazonian forces started a blockade of the [[Kumba]]-[[Buea]] highway at Ekona, a town located approximately 10 kilometers from Buea. A military assault on the separatists in Ekona failed to lift the blockade.<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/hold-kumba-buea-highway-leaves-passengers-stranded/ Hold up on Kumba-Buea highway leaves passengers stranded] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180624035717/https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/hold-kumba-buea-highway-leaves-passengers-stranded/ |date=2018-06-24 }}, Journal du Cameroun, Jun 18, 2018. Accessed Jun 23, 2018.</ref> While casualties related to the battle of Ekona remain unconfirmed, the Cameroonian government later declared that more than 40 soldiers and policemen died in the later half of June across Southern Cameroons.<ref name=100deadvoa>[https://www.voanews.com/a/cameroon-says-military-casualties-mounting/4456739.html Cameroon says Military Casualties Mounting] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180628015704/https://www.voanews.com/a/cameroon-says-military-casualties-mounting/4456739.html |date=2018-06-28 }}, Voice of America, Jun 27, 2018. Accessed Jun 27, 2018.</ref> By now, the war had fully extended to Buea, with separatists mounting road blocks and attacking government soldiers on June 29.<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/panic-grips-buea-soldiers-battle-separatists/ Panic grips Buea as soldiers battle separatists] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180629204552/https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/panic-grips-buea-soldiers-battle-separatists/ |date=2018-06-29 }}, Journal du Cameroun, Jun 29, 2018. Accessed Jun 29, 2018.</ref> Attacks in Buea intensified in July, with one invasion on July 1,<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/muea-lockdown-soldiers-battle-separatists/ Muea in lockdown as soldiers battle separatists] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180702122154/https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/muea-lockdown-soldiers-battle-separatists/ |date=2018-07-02 }}, Journal du Cameroun, Jul 1, 2018. Accessed Jul 2, 2018.</ref> another on July 9<ref>[https://www.enca.com/africa/gunfire-in-cameroons-english-restive-region Gunfire in Cameroon's English restive region] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180709201441/https://www.enca.com/africa/gunfire-in-cameroons-english-restive-region |date=2018-07-09 }}, Enca, Jul 9, 2018. Accessed Jul 9, 2018.</ref> and another on July 30.<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/four-civilians-killed-buea/ Four civilians killed in Buea] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180731105038/https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/four-civilians-killed-buea/ |date=2018-07-31 }}, Journal du Cameroun, Jul 31, 2018. Accessed Jul 31, 2018.</ref>\n\n[[File:Wreckage of vehicles at Mile 16, September 11, 2018.jpg|thumb|300px|right|Scorched vehicles left behind after clashes in Buea on September 11.]]\n\nOn August 16, separatists attacked a [[convoy]] transporting a member of parliament in [[Babungo (village)|Babungo]], [[Ngo-Ketunjia|Ngo-Ketunjia Department]], killing at least four soldiers. A civilian who got caught in the crossfire was also killed.<ref name=16.08.2018>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/four-soldiers-killed-baboungo/ Four soldiers killed in Baboungo] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180816114130/https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/four-soldiers-killed-baboungo/ |date=2018-08-16 }}, Journal du Cameroun, Aug 16, 2018. Accessed Aug 16, 2018.</ref> Eight days later, a successful guerrilla attack killed two gendarmes and wounded a brigade commander in Zhoa in [[Wum]], [[Northwest Region (Cameroon)|Northwest Region]].<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-army-kills-12-separatists-troubled-anglophone-region/ Cameroon army kills 12 separatists in troubled Anglophone region] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180827143959/https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-army-kills-12-separatists-troubled-anglophone-region/ |date=2018-08-27 }}, Journal du Cameroun, Aug 27, 2018. Accessed Aug 27, 2018.</ref> As a response, the Cameroonian Army burned down the village.<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/villagers-flee-zhoa-arson-attacks/ Villagers flee Zhoa after arson attacks] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180829215224/https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/villagers-flee-zhoa-arson-attacks/ |date=2018-08-29 }}, Journal du Cameroun, Aug 29, 2018. Accessed Aug 29, 2018.</ref>\n\nSeptember saw some setbacks for the separatists, as the government launched attacks into the rural areas they controlled.<ref name=\"crisisgroupmay22019\"/> There was heavy fighting in [[Muyuka]], where Cameroon launched an offensive.<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroonfour-separatists-killed-three-soldiers-muyuka-battle/ Cameroon:four separatists killed, three soldiers in Muyuka battle] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180904153957/https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroonfour-separatists-killed-three-soldiers-muyuka-battle/ |date=2018-09-04 }}, Journal du Cameroun, Sep 4, 2018. Accessed Sep 4, 2018.</ref> The Cameroonian Army enjoyed some success in weeding out separatist camps.  In a particularly lethal raid on September 4, Cameroonian soldiers killed 27 suspected separatists near Zhoa.<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-army-kills-27-fighters-wum/ Cameroon army kills 27 fighters in Wum] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180906225504/https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-army-kills-27-fighters-wum/ |date=2018-09-06 }}, Journal du Cameroun, Sep 6, 2018. Accessed Sep 7, 2018.</ref> Another raid on separatist camps near [[Chomba]] killed at least 15 separatists.<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-soldiers-kill-15-suspected-separatists-in-nw-region/ Cameroon soldiers kill 15 suspected separatists in NW region] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180912195645/https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-soldiers-kill-15-suspected-separatists-in-nw-region/ |date=2018-09-12 }}, Sep 12, 2018. Accessed Sep 12, 2018.</ref> The separatists also had their successes; On September 9, 50 or more separatists successfully carried out three coordinated attacks on multiple targets in Oku, burning down the police station, destroying the Assistant Division Officer's belongings, stealing a police van and abducting three police officers.<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroonthree-kidnapped-as-separatist-burn-police-station-in-oku/ Cameroon:Three kidnapped as separatist burn police station in Oku] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180912131143/https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroonthree-kidnapped-as-separatist-burn-police-station-in-oku/ |date=2018-09-12 }}, Sep 10, 2018. Accessed Sep 12, 2018.</ref> On September 11, separatists took control of two neighborhoods of Buea, blocking the main entrances to the city and killing a soldier from the [[Rapid Intervention Battalion, Cameroon|Rapid Intervention Battalion]] (BIR).<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-soldier-found-dead-in-buea/ Cameroon: soldier found dead in Buea], Journal du Cameroun, Sep 11, 2018. Accessed Jul 8, 2019.</ref> An attempt was also made to abduct the Fon of Buea.<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-kidnapped-buea-traditional-ruler-freed/ Cameroon: kidnapped Buea traditional ruler freed] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180916164330/https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-kidnapped-buea-traditional-ruler-freed/ |date=2018-09-16 }}, Sep 14, 2018. Accessed Sep 16, 2018.</ref> On September 27, separatists forced the police and gendarmes to retreat from [[Balikumbat]], [[Ngo-Ketunjia]].<ref>[http://cameroonnewsagency.com/ambazonia-fighters-hoist-flags-in-abandoned-do-police-buildings/ Ambazonia Fighters Hoist Flags In Abandoned DO, Police Buildings] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181125115455/http://cameroonnewsagency.com/ambazonia-fighters-hoist-flags-in-abandoned-do-police-buildings/ |date=2018-11-25 }}, Cameroon News Agency, Sep 28, 2018. Accessed Nov 24, 2018.</ref> Despite government offensives in September, the separatists remained in control of many rural and urban areas.<ref name=\"crisisgroupmay22019\"/>\n\nOn September 30, in anticipation of the first anniversary of Ambazonia's declaration of independence on October 1, the authorities imposed a 48-hour curfew throughout the Anglophone region. This was done to prevent a re-occurrence of the mass demonstrations that took place the year before. People were forbidden from moving across sub-division boundaries, and gatherings of four or more people in public were prohibited. Businesses were shut down and motor parks were closed as well. Meanwhile, in anticipation of the [[Cameroonian presidential election, 2018|Cameroonian presidential election]] on October 7, the separatists started enforcing a lock-down of their own, blocking major highways with trees or car wrecks. Throughout the day, security forces and separatists clashed in Buea, Bamenda and other cities.<ref>[https://qz.com/africa/1410357/cameroon-army-anglophone-separatists-have-ambazonia-region-on-lockdown/ Cameroon armed forces and separatists have the Anglophone region on lockdown ahead of elections] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181003141555/https://qz.com/africa/1410357/cameroon-army-anglophone-separatists-have-ambazonia-region-on-lockdown/ |date=2018-10-03 }}, Quartz Africa, Oct 2, 2018. Accessed Oct 3, 2018.</ref>\n\nBy October, the conflict had spread to most of Southern Cameroons. The ADF alone had clashed with the army 83 times,<ref name=\"BBCoct42018\"/> separatist militias were now active in 12 divisions, and attacks were now more lethal.<ref name=\"acleddatapickingafight\"/> According to an [[International Crisis Group]] analyst, by October the war had reached a stalemate, with the army being unable to defeat the separatists, while the separatists were not militarily strong enough to expel the army.<ref name=\"BBCoct42018\"/> Others described the separatists as severely outgunned and on the verge of defeat, mostly due to their lack of access to proper weapons.<ref name=\"viceoct2018\"/> On October 7, the day of the [[Cameroonian presidential election, 2018|Cameroonian presidential election]], there were clashes all over Southern Cameroons with both sides blaming the other; the Cameroonian government claimed that separatists moved to prevent what they considered a foreign election to take place in the Anglophone regions,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://calrev.org/2019/02/11/african-powder-keg-cameroonian-conflict-and-african-security/|title=AFRICAN POWDER KEG: CAMEROONIAN CONFLICT AND AFRICAN SECURITY|last=Genin|first=Aaron|date=2019-02-11|website=The California Review|language=en-US|access-date=2019-03-15}}</ref> while the separatists blamed the government for instigating the violence.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2016/12/15/world/cameroon-protesters-deaths/index.html|title=Rights groups call for probe into protesters' deaths in Cameroon|author=Radina Gigova|website=CNN|access-date=2019-03-17|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190227172641/https://www.cnn.com/2016/12/15/world/cameroon-protesters-deaths/index.html|archive-date=2019-02-27|url-status=dead|df=}}</ref> This resulted in a very low turnout, as \"more than 90 percent of residents\" fled violence in some localities; and in many cases no officials showed up to man the polling stations.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/10/06/world/africa/cameroon-election-biya-ambazonia.html|title=Cameroon on Brink of Civil War as English Speakers Recount \u2018Unbearable\u2019 Horrors|last=Searcey|first=Dionne|date=2018-10-06|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-03-17|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190324074220/https://www.nytimes.com/2018/10/06/world/africa/cameroon-election-biya-ambazonia.html|archive-date=2019-03-24|url-status=dead|df=}}</ref> In Bamenda, at least 20 separatist fighters moved around openly to prevent people from voting. Two separatists were killed by government troops while attacking a polling station.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/oct/07/gunfire-in-cameroons-anglophone-regions-deters-voters-on-polling-day Gunfire in Cameroon's anglophone regions deters voters on polling day] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181008162624/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/oct/07/gunfire-in-cameroons-anglophone-regions-deters-voters-on-polling-day |date=2018-10-08 }}, The Guardian, Oct 7, 2018. Accessed Oct 8, 2018.</ref> Following the election, two people from Kumba were murdered for having voted.<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroontwo-persons-killed-for-voting-in-kumba/ Cameroon:Two persons killed for voting in Kumba] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181012175439/https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroontwo-persons-killed-for-voting-in-kumba/ |date=2018-10-12 }}, Journal du Cameroun, Oct 12, 2018. Accessed Oct 12, 2018.</ref> On October 17, [[Social Democratic Front (Cameroon)|SDF]] President [[John Fru Ndi]]'s house in Bamenda was set on fire by armed men.<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroonfru-ndis-residence-goes-up-in-flames/ Cameroon:Fru Ndi\u2019s residence goes up in flames] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181020011458/https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroonfru-ndis-residence-goes-up-in-flames/ |date=2018-10-20 }}, Journal du Cameroun, Oct 18, 2018. Accessed Oct 19, 2018.</ref> On October 23, the Cameroonian Army launched simultaneous attacks on seven or more separatist camps in the Northwest Region, initiating battles that continued for more than 24 hours. At least 30 separatists were killed, as well as an unknown number of Cameroonian soldiers.<ref>[https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/africa/fighting-between-cameroon-military-separatists-kills-18/2018/10/25/a87fd7c2-d848-11e8-8384-bcc5492fef49_story.html Fighting between Cameroon military, separatists kills \u2018many\u2019] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181025144011/https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/africa/fighting-between-cameroon-military-separatists-kills-18/2018/10/25/a87fd7c2-d848-11e8-8384-bcc5492fef49_story.html |date=2018-10-25 }}, Washington Post, Oct 25, 2018. Accessed Oct 25, 2018.</ref>\n\nIn the beginning of November, 79 students and four staff members [[PSS Nkwen kidnapping|were kidnapped from a school in Nkwen]], near Bamenda.<ref>[http://www.wsfa.com/2018/11/05/armed-men-kidnap-students-cameroon-restive-northwest/ Separatists kidnap 78 pupils in Cameroon's restive northwest] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181105190926/http://www.wsfa.com/2018/11/05/armed-men-kidnap-students-cameroon-restive-northwest/ |date=2018-11-05 }}, WSFA 12 News, Nov 5, 2018. Accessed Nov 5, 2018.</ref> All 79 students were released without ransom three days later.<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-principal-of-pss-nkwen-three-others-released/ Cameroon: Principal of PSS Nkwen, three others released] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181112121607/https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-principal-of-pss-nkwen-three-others-released/ |date=2018-11-12 }}, Journal du Cameroun, Oct 12, 2018. Accessed Oct 12, 2018.</ref> The Ambazonia Self-Defence Council claimed that they not only had nothing to do with the kidnappings, but had also sent its own fighters to try to locate the children.<ref>[https://www.dw.com/en/kidnapped-children-in-cameroon-released-without-ransom/a-46199258 Kidnapped children in Cameroon released without ransom] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181108184003/https://www.dw.com/en/kidnapped-children-in-cameroon-released-without-ransom/a-46199258 |date=2018-11-08 }}, Deutsche Welle, Nov 7, 2018. Accessed Nov 8, 2018.</ref> November also saw several major confrontations. On November 11, according to the separatists, 13 Cameroonian soldiers and two separatists were killed when separatists carried out a successful ambush.<ref>[https://www.reuters.com/article/us-cameroon-separatists/at-least-15-killed-in-cameroon-in-clashes-between-army-separatists-idUSKCN1NI2VM At least 15 killed in Cameroon in clashes between army, separatists] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181114031829/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-cameroon-separatists/at-least-15-killed-in-cameroon-in-clashes-between-army-separatists-idUSKCN1NI2VM |date=2018-11-14 }}, Reuters, Nov 13, 2018. Accessed Nov 14, 2018.</ref> The next day, Cameroonian soldiers ambushed and killed at least 13 suspected separatists in [[Donga-Mantung]],<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-soldiers-kill-13-separatist-fighters-in-binka/ Cameroon soldiers kill 13 separatist fighters in Binka] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181113165855/https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-soldiers-kill-13-separatist-fighters-in-binka/ |date=2018-11-13 }}, Journal du Cameroun, Nov 13, 2018. Accessed Nov 13, 2018.</ref> and another 25  near [[Nkamb\u00e9]] the next day.<ref>[https://www.trtworld.com/africa/25-killed-in-clashes-in-english-speaking-cameroon-officials-21656 25 killed in clashes in English-speaking Cameroon \u2013 officials] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181114143737/https://www.trtworld.com/africa/25-killed-in-clashes-in-english-speaking-cameroon-officials-21656 |date=2018-11-14 }}, TRT World, Oct 14, 2018. Accessed Oct 14, 2018.</ref> On November 22, around 40 Ambazonian fighters and unarmed civilians were killed in [[Bali, Cameroon|Bali]] by government soldiers, who then set their corpses on fire. With no trace of bullet wounds on any of the bodies, unconfirmed reports alleged the use of chemicals by the soldiers.<ref>[http://cameroonnewsagency.com/soldiers-use-chemicals-to-kill-fighterscivilians-in-bali/ Soldiers Use \u2018Chemicals\u2019 to Kill Fighters,Civilians in Bali] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181228130941/http://cameroonnewsagency.com/soldiers-use-chemicals-to-kill-fighterscivilians-in-bali/ |date=2018-12-28 }}, Cameroon News Agency, Nov 25, 2018. Accessed Dec 28, 2018.</ref> On November 28, separatists blocked the Buea-Kumba Highway.<ref name=\"jdcdec3\">[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-traffic-paralysed-on-buea-kumba-road-after-heavy-gunshots/ Cameroon: Traffic paralysed on Buea-Kumba road after heavy gunshots] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181204151358/https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-traffic-paralysed-on-buea-kumba-road-after-heavy-gunshots/ |date=2018-12-04 }}, Journal du Cameroun, Dec 3, 2018. Accessed Dec 3, 2018.</ref> The month also saw the first major spillover into other parts of Cameroon; On November 29, at least 30 people were kidnapped by ten unidentified gunmen in [[Bangourain]], [[West Region (Cameroon)|West Region]], and transported with canoes across the [[Noun River (Cameroon)|Lake Bamendjing]] reservoir.<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/at-least-30-persons-kidnapped-in-cameroons-west-region/ At least 30 persons kidnapped in Cameroon\u2019s West region] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181129225551/https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/at-least-30-persons-kidnapped-in-cameroons-west-region/ |date=2018-11-29 }}, Journal du Cameroun, Nov 29, 2018. Accessed Nov 29, 2018.</ref> A month later, two suspected separatists were lynched by the villagers, and the Cameroonian Army launched an offensive nearby.<ref>[http://cameroonnewsagency.com/soldiers-vs-ambazonia-fighters-the-struggle-to-break-the-bangolan-wall/ Soldiers VS Ambazonia Fighters : The Struggle to Break The Bangolan Wall] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181228223332/http://cameroonnewsagency.com/soldiers-vs-ambazonia-fighters-the-struggle-to-break-the-bangolan-wall/ |date=2018-12-28 }}, Cameroon News Agency, Dec 28, 2018. Accessed Dec 28, 2018.</ref> Bangourain was attacked once more on December 22, prompting the separatists to accuse the government of carrying out a [[false flag]] operation to incite Cameroonian Francophones.<ref name=\"cnadec2618\">[http://cameroonnewsagency.com/the-bangourain-attack-a-long-walk-towards-peace-shaming-the-devil/ The Bangourain Attack: A Long Walk Towards Peace, Shaming The Devil] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181227043751/http://cameroonnewsagency.com/the-bangourain-attack-a-long-walk-towards-peace-shaming-the-devil/ |date=2018-12-27 }}, Cameroon News Agency, Dec 26, 2018. Accessed Dec 26, 2018.</ref> In Kembong, just south of [[Mamfe]], a military vehicle hit a road bomb; no soldiers died, but the vehicle was destroyed.<ref>[https://www.bbc.com/pidgin/tori-46367595 Anglophone crisis: Cameroon separatists 'bomb' military moto for Kembong] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181203013948/https://www.bbc.com/pidgin/tori-46367595 |date=2018-12-03 }}, BBC (Pidgin), Nov 30, 2018. Accessed Nov 30, 2018.</ref>\n\nDecember saw more burning of houses by government soldiers in Romajia,<ref name=\"cnadec72018\">[http://cameroonnewsagency.com/the-onslaught-in-kumbo-continues-analysis-of-radio-evangelum/ The Onslaught In Kumbo Continues-Analysis of Radio Evangelum] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181209165257/http://cameroonnewsagency.com/the-onslaught-in-kumbo-continues-analysis-of-radio-evangelum/ |date=2018-12-09 }}, Cameroon News Agency, Dec 7, 2018. Accessed Dec 7, 2018.</ref> Kikiakom and Ekona.<ref name=\"cnadec72018\"/> On December 15, at least five separatists were summarily executed, possibly by fellow separatists.<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-infighting-from-ambazonia-armed-groups-leaves-at-least-5-dead/ Cameroon: infighting from \u2018Ambazonia armed groups\u2019 leaves at least 5 dead] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181217062906/https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-infighting-from-ambazonia-armed-groups-leaves-at-least-5-dead/ |date=2018-12-17 }}, Journal du Cameroun, Dec 16, 2018. Accessed Dec 16, 2018.</ref> On December 21, ADF General [[Ivo Mbah]] was killed during a military raid in Kumba.<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-ambazonia-general-killed-in-kumba/ Cameroon: \u2018Ambazonia General\u2019 killed in Kumba] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181221230740/https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-ambazonia-general-killed-in-kumba/ |date=2018-12-21 }}, Journal du Cameroun, Dec 21, 2018. Accessed Dec 21, 2018.</ref>\n\nOn December 31, the presidents of Cameroon and Ambazonia addressed the ongoing conflict in their end of year speeches. President [[Paul Biya]] of Cameroon promised to \"neutralize\" all separatists who refused to disarm, while emphasizing that anyone who drops their guns can be reintegrated into society.<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/biya-says-soldiers-will-crush-ambazonia-fighters-who-fail-to-drop-their-guns/ Cameroon: Biya says soldiers will \u2018neutralize\u2019 Ambazonia fighters who fail to drop their guns] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190101014559/https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/biya-says-soldiers-will-crush-ambazonia-fighters-who-fail-to-drop-their-guns/ |date=2019-01-01 }}, Journal du Cameroun, Dec 31, 2018. Accessed Dec 31, 2018.</ref> President [[Samuel Ikome Sako]] of Ambazonia said that the separatists would switch from a defensive to an offensive strategy in the war, and announced that a Mobile Wing Police would be created to capture territory and defeat government militias. He also condemned anyone engaged in kidnappings of civilians, and promised to fight back against anyone involved in such practices.<ref>[http://cameroonnewsagency.com/no-retreat-no-surrender-from-defensive-to-offensive-strategy-the-way-forward-in-2019-dr-samuel-sako/ No Retreat, No Surrender, From Defensive To Offensive Strategy, The way Forward In 2019-Dr Samuel Sako] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190101051522/http://cameroonnewsagency.com/no-retreat-no-surrender-from-defensive-to-offensive-strategy-the-way-forward-in-2019-dr-samuel-sako/ |date=2019-01-01 }}, Cameroon News Agency, Dec 31, 2018. Accessed Dec 31, 2018.</ref> The same night, separatist fighters attacked the convoy of the Governor of the [[Northwest Region (Cameroon)|Northwest Region]], injuring at least one government soldier.<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-nw-governor-attacked-by-ambazonia-fighters-on-new-year/ Cameroon: NW Governor attacked by Ambazonia fighters on New Year] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190101192111/https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-nw-governor-attacked-by-ambazonia-fighters-on-new-year/ |date=2019-01-01 }}, Journal du Cameroun, Jan 1, 2019. Accessed Jan 1, 2019.</ref> The Cameroonian Army also announced the killing of [[Lekeaka Oliver]], Field Marshall of the [[Red Dragon (Ambazonian militia)|Red Dragon militia]], in [[Lebialem]]; the killing was denied by the Interim Government of Ambazonia,<ref name=\"Oliver\">[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-mystery-surrounds-reported-death-of-ambazonias-field-marshall/ Cameroon: Mystery surrounds \u2018reported death of Ambazonia\u2019s Field Marshall\u2019] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190102181616/https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-mystery-surrounds-reported-death-of-ambazonias-field-marshall/ |date=2019-01-02 }}, Journal du Cameroun, Jan 2, 2019. Accessed Jan 2, 2019.</ref> and was also denied by sources within the Cameroonian Army. Oliver resurfaced in a video a week later, proving that reports of his death were false.<ref name=\"jdcjan42019\">[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-three-soldiers-killed-in-mbelenka/ Cameroon: Three gendarmes killed in Mbelenka] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190104154040/https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-three-soldiers-killed-in-mbelenka/ |date=2019-01-04 }}, Journal du Cameroun, Jan 4, 2018. Accessed Jan 4, 2018.</ref>\n\n===2019===\n\n{{Main|Timeline of the Anglophone Crisis (2019)}}\n\n2019 started off with further escalation of the war. On January 6, Anglophone Cameroonians in the diaspora organized protests to mark the first anniversary of the arrest of the Ambazonian leadership. Throughout the day, armed clashes took place in [[Muyuka]], [[Bafut, Cameroon|Bafut]]. Mundum and [[Mamfe]].<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-protests-ghost-towns-marked-anniversary-celebrations-of-detained-ambazonia-leaders/ Cameroon: Protests, ghost towns mark anniversary celebrations of detained \u2018Ambazonia leaders\u2019] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190107170427/https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-protests-ghost-towns-marked-anniversary-celebrations-of-detained-ambazonia-leaders/ |date=2019-01-07 }}, Journal du Cameroun, Jan 7, 2019. Accessed Jan 7, 2019.</ref> In Mamfe, two Ambazonian generals were killed when their camps were raided by the BIR.<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-two-ambazonia-generals-killed-in-mamfe/ Cameroon: Two \u2018Ambazonia Generals\u2019 killed in Mamfe] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190107165605/https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-two-ambazonia-generals-killed-in-mamfe/ |date=2019-01-07 }}, Journal du Cameroun, Jan 7, 2019. Accessed Jan 7, 2019.</ref>  On January 24, General Andrew Ngoe of [[SOCADEF]] was killed in Matoh, [[Mbonge]].<ref name=\"AndrewNgoe\">[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-ambazonia-general-killed-in-matoh/ Cameroon: \u2018Ambazonia General\u2019 killed in Matoh] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190125020522/https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-ambazonia-general-killed-in-matoh/ |date=2019-01-25 }}, Journal du Cameroun, Jan 24, 2019. Accessed Jan 24, 2019.</ref>\n\nJanuary also saw the start of the trials of the Ambazonian leaders, including [[Sisiku Julius Ayuk Tabe]], who had spent a year in prison. The trial was complicated by all the Ambazonian leaders rejecting their Cameroonian nationality, which the court ultimately ignored. The leaders then refused to be tried by Francophone judges. On March 1, the trial took a diplomatic twist; a Nigerian court determined that the deportation of the Ambazonian leadership had been unconstitutional, and ordered their return to Nigeria. Nevertheless, the trial resumed.<ref name=\"mar12019abuja\">[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-nigerian-court-orders-return-of-ambazonia-leaders/ Cameroon: Nigerian Court orders return of Ambazonia leaders] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190301205941/https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-nigerian-court-orders-return-of-ambazonia-leaders/ |date=2019-03-01 }}, Journal du Cameroun, Mar 1, 2019. Accessed Mar 1, 2019.</ref>\n\nThe separatists got bolder with enforcing lockdowns. The same day as the start of the trial, the streets of Buea were almost completely deserted.<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-vionlence-gunshots-ghost-towns-engulf-parts-of-anglophone-towns/ Cameroon: vionlence, gunshots, ghost towns engulf parts of Anglophone towns], Journal du Cameroun, Jan 10, 2019. Accessed Jan 10, 2019.</ref> On February 4, in anticipation of [[Public holidays in Cameroon|Youth Day]] on February 11, separatists declared a 10-day lockdown, telling people all across the Anglophone regions to stay at home from February 5\u201314.<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-ambazonia-separatists-impose-ten-day-lockdown-on-anglophone-regions/ Cameroon: Ambazonia separatists impose \u2018ten-day lockdown\u2019 on Anglophone regions] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190205044109/https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-ambazonia-separatists-impose-ten-day-lockdown-on-anglophone-regions/ |date=2019-02-05 }}, Journal du Cameroun, Feb 4, 2019. Accessed Feb 4, 2019.</ref> The lockdown was a matter of controversy among the separatists, with a spokesperson of the [[Ambazonia Defence Forces]] arguing that it would be counterproductive.<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-ambazonia-activists-divided-over-ten-day-lockdown/ Cameroon: Ambazonia activists divided over \u2018ten-day lockdown\u2019] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190205030751/https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-ambazonia-activists-divided-over-ten-day-lockdown/ |date=2019-02-05 }}, Journal du Cameroun, Feb 4, 2019. Accessed Feb 4, 2019.</ref> The next day, large parts of Buea were closed down, while armed clashes took place in Muea and Muyuka. Most of Bamenda was also closed down, with smaller clashes taking place.<ref name=\"feb52019\">[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroongunshots-blackouts-open-day-one-of-ambazonia-lockdown/ Cameroon:Gunshots, blackout open day one of Ambazonia lockdown] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190206012239/https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroongunshots-blackouts-open-day-one-of-ambazonia-lockdown/ |date=2019-02-06 }}, Journal du Cameroun, Feb 5, 2019. Accessed Feb 5, 2019.</ref> In Muyuka, an Ambazonian Colonel was killed alongside two other separatist fighters.<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-ambazonia-colonel-killed-in-muyuka/ Cameroon: Ambazonia \u2018Colonel\u2019 killed in Muyuka] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190207020111/https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-ambazonia-colonel-killed-in-muyuka/ |date=2019-02-07 }}, Journal du Cameroun, Feb 6, 2019. Accessed Feb 6, 2019.</ref> In Mbengwi, two separatists died while attacking the Divisional Office there.<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-security-forces-kill-two-separatist-fighters-in-mbengwi/ Cameroon: Security forces kill two separatist fighters in Mbengwi] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190207015523/https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-security-forces-kill-two-separatist-fighters-in-mbengwi/ |date=2019-02-07 }}, Journal du Cameroun, Feb 6, 2019. Accessed Feb 6, 2019.</ref> As a result of the lockdown, Youth Day celebrations had negligible turnout in Southern Cameroons. In Bamenda, the Governor of Northwest Region, Adolph Lele l\u2019Afrique, was escorted by soldiers to attend a small celebration. The military escort came under fire while driving to the ceremony, possibly resulting in casualties. The celebrations were boycotted in most major cities in the Anglophone regions, including Buea, Kumbo, Belo, Ndop, Ndu, Wum, Muyuka, Mamfe, Tombem, Mundemba and Lebialem, while there was a comparatively significant turnout in Nkambe.<ref>[https://nationaltelegraph.net/cameroon-lockdown-gunshots-frustrate-youth-day-force-buea-university-to-postpone-exams/ Cameroon: Lockdown, Gunshots Frustrate Youth Day, Force Buea University To Postpone Exams] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190213124107/https://nationaltelegraph.net/cameroon-lockdown-gunshots-frustrate-youth-day-force-buea-university-to-postpone-exams/ |date=2019-02-13 }}, National Telegraph, Feb 11, 2019. Accessed Feb 12, 2019.</ref>\n\nEarly March saw two serious kidnapping incidents; one on the Kumba-Buea Highway, which was quickly foiled by the BIR,<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-soldiers-rescue-passengers-freed-along-buea-kumba-road/ Cameroon: Soldiers rescue passengers freed along Buea-Kumba road] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190321225853/https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-soldiers-rescue-passengers-freed-along-buea-kumba-road/ |date=2019-03-21 }}, Journal du Cameroun, Mar 20, 2019. Accessed Mar 20, 2019.</ref> and one at the University of Buea, where more than 15 students were kidnapped, beaten and released.<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-at-least-15-buea-university-students-kidnapped/ Cameroon: At least 15 Buea University students kidnapped], Journal du Cameroun, Mar 20, 2019. Accessed Jul 7, 2019.</ref> The separatists set up several road blocks, including an overnight mission where the [[Seven Karta]] militia blocked the Bafut-Bamenda Highway with concrete walls<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-ambazonia-fighters-erect-wall-in-bafut/ Cameroon: Ambazonia fighters erect wall in Bafut], Journal du Cameroun, Mar 23, 2019. Accessed Jul 7, 2019.</ref> On March 14, Cameroonian soldiers burned down several houses in Dunga Mantung and Menchum, and killed at least 12 people (several of whom were burned alive).<ref>[http://cameroonnewsagency.com/thursdays-incidents-in-wum-and-nkambe-central-casualties-you-should-know/ Thursday\u2019s Incidents In Wum And Nkambe Central; Casualties You Should Know], Cameroon News Agency, Mar 16, 2019. Accessed Mar 18, 2019.</ref> At the end of March, an ADF leader announced that they would take the war into the French-speaking parts of Cameroon. A week later, separatists \u2013 possibly the ADF \u2013 raided Penda Mboko, [[Littoral Region (Cameroon)|Littoral Region]], and injured three gendarmes.<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-three-gendarmes-injured-as-suspected-ambazonia-fighters-attack-littoral-region-again/ Cameroon:Three gendarmes injured as suspected Ambazonia fighters attack Littoral region again], Journal du Cameroun, Apr 2, 2019. Accessed Apr 2, 2019.</ref> This was done in defiance of the Interim Government.<ref>[https://www.bareta.news/interim-government-warns-cameroun-against-propagating-inter-citizen-war-between-both-cameroons/ Interim Government Warns Cameroun Against Propagating Inter-Citizen War Between Both Cameroons], Bareta News. Accessed Dec 25, 2018.</ref>\n\nOn March 31, various Ambazonian independence movements agreed to form the [[Southern Cameroons Liberation Council]] (SCLC), a united front consisting of both separatists and federalists.<ref>[http://cameroonnewsagency.com/federalists-meet-restorationists-which-group-will-perform-the-osmosis/ Federalists Meet Restorationists, Which Group Will Perform The Osmosis?], Cameroon News Agency, Mar 29, 2019. Accessed Apr 10, 2019.</ref> On April 4, separatists imposed a 10-day lockdown on Buea.<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-looming-ambazonia-lockdown-sparks-exodus-from-buea/ Cameroon: Looming Ambazonia lockdown sparks exodus from Buea], Journal du Cameroun, Apr 4, 2019. Accessed Apr 4, 2019.</ref> On April 9, the newly-established SCLC declared an early end to lockdown, citing how it mainly affected civilians. However, the [[Ambazonia Self-Defence Council]], the armed wing of the [[Interim Government of Ambazonia|Interim Government]], declared that the SCLC had no authority to call off the lockdown without consulting it first.<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-confusion-looms-as-ambazonia-faction-maintains-lockdown-in-fako/ Cameroon: Confusion looms as Ambazonia faction maintains Fako lockdown], Journal du Cameroun, Apr 10, 2019. Accessed Apr 10, 2019.</ref>\n\n[[File:Soldiers in Bamenda, May 24, 2019.png|thumb|right|Cameroonian soldiers in Bamenda in May, 2019.]]\n\nOn April 14, four Cameroonian soldiers and three separatist fighters were killed in [[Bali, Cameroon|Bali]].<ref>[http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2019-04/15/c_137978898.htm Three separatists, 4 soldiers killed in clashes in Cameroon's troubled Anglophone region], XinhuaNet, Apr 15, 2019. Accessed Apr 15, 2019.</ref> In Ekona, at least six people were killed in a government offensive.<ref>[http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2019-04/15/c_137977131.htm Six killed in anti-separatism military operation in Cameroon's restive Anglophone region], XinhuaNet, Apr 15, 2019. Accessed Apr 15, 2019.</ref> The next day, security forces carried out mass arrests in Buea as they searched for separatist bases.<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/camerooncivilians-arrested-as-security-forces-raid-buea-in-search-of-ambazonia-fighters/ Cameroon:Civilians arrested as security forces raid Buea in search of Ambazonia fighters], Journal du Cameroun, Apr 16, 2019. Accessed Apr 17, 2019.</ref> On April 24, gunmen burned down the house of the mayor of [[Fundong]].<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroonresidence-of-fundong-mayor-burnt-by-suspected-separatist-fighters/ Cameroon:Residence of Fundong Mayor burnt by suspected separatist fighters], Journal du Cameroun, Apr 25, 2019. Accessed Jul 8, 2019.</ref> On April 27, [[Social Democratic Front (Cameroon)|SDF]] leader [[John Fru Ndi]] [[Kidnapping of John Fru Ndi|was kidnapped]] in Kumbo by separatists, but was released the same day. Fru Ndi had travelled to Kumbo to attend the funeral of Joseph Banadzem, the Parliamentary group leader of the SDF. Local separatist fighters had consented to the funeral taking place, provided that no Francophone Cameroonians attended it.<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-sdf-chairman-ni-john-fru-ndi-kidnapped/ Cameroon: SDF Chairman Ni John Fru Ndi released after brief kidnap], Journal du Cameroun, Apr 27, 2019. Accessed Apr 27, 2019.</ref> On April 30, government soldiers killed one person and burned at least 10 houses in Kikaikelaiki, [[Bui (Cameroon department)|Bui]].<ref>[http://cameroonnewsagency.com/in-pictures-soldiers-burn-over-10-house-cardinal-tumis-village/ In Pictures: Soldiers Burn Over 10 House Cardinal Tumi\u2019s Village], Cameroon News Agency, Apr 30, 2019. Accessed May 1, 2019.</ref>\n\nMay saw the Anglophone Crisis get some international attention. On May 5, following appeals by the [[European Union Parliament]], it was announced that the Anglophone Crisis would be debated at the [[United Nations Security Council]].<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-un-security-council-to-discuss-anglophone-crisis/ Cameroon: UN Security Council to discuss Anglophone crisis], Journal du Cameroun, May 5, 2019. Accessed May 5, 2019.</ref> Days later, the Cameroonian government announced it was ready for an \"inclusive\" dialogue where anything except Ambazonian independence could be discussed.<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroonpaul-biya-ready-for-dialogue-to-end-anglophone-crisis-pm-says/ Cameroon:Paul Biya ready for dialogue to end Anglophone crisis, PM says], Journal du Cameroun, May 9, 2019. Accessed May 9, 2019.</ref> Meanwhile, a [[2019 Ambazonian leadership crisis|leadership crisis]] erupted within the [[Interim Government of Ambazonia]], forcing smaller separatist movements to pick their loyalties.<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-sepratist-hardliners-react-after-impechment-of-detained-ambazonia-leader/ Cameroon: Sepratist hardliners react after impechment of detained Ambazonia leader], Journal du Cameroun, Jun 12, 2019. Accessed Jun 12, 2019.</ref>\n\nIn June, the separatists announced that they had started producing their own weapons in the warzone. Shortly afterwards, a mine killed four policemen and wounded another six,<ref name=\"producingownweapons\"/> convincing many that the separatists were no longer outgunned, but indeed well-armed.<ref name=\"voajun192019\"/> The same month, it was revealed that the government of Cameroon and separatist movements would enter negotiations.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://cameroonnewsagency.com/armed-conflict-in-southern-cameroons-ambazonia-leaders-welcome-swiss-led-mediation-process/|title=Armed Conflict In Southern Cameroons: Ambazonia Leaders Welcome Swiss-Led Mediation Process \u2013 Cameroon News Agency|first=|date=|website=|language=en-US|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=dead|access-date=2019-07-04}}</ref> On June 27, John Fru Ndi was [[Kidnapping of John Fru Ndi#Second kidnapping|kidnapped for the second time]] in two months.<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-kidnapped-sdf-chairman-ni-john-fru-ndi-released/ Cameroon: Kidnapped SDF Chairman Ni John Fru Ndi released], Journal du Cameroun, Jun 29, 2019. Accessed Jun 29, 2019.</ref>\n\nHeavy fighting took place in July. On July 3, separatists ambushed a military boat carrying 13 Cameroonian soldiers on the Ekpambiri river, [[Manyu (department)|Manyu Division]]. Three soldiers managed to escape, two were rescued, one was found dead after five days, and seven remain unaccounted for. The Cameroonian Army declared that they knew which base the attackers had come from, and that an operation would be launched to destroy it.<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-corpse-of-soldier-discovered-in-manyu-river/ Cameroon: Corpse of soldier discovered in Manyu river], Journal du Cameroun, Jul 8, 2019. Accessed Jul 8, 2019.</ref> On July 8, at least two gendarmes were killed and several more were wounded in an ambush in [[Ndop]].<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-two-gendarmes-killed-in-restive-nw-region/ Cameroon: Two gendarmes killed in restive NW region], Journal du Cameroun, Jul 10, 2019. Accessed Jul 10, 2019.</ref> On July 11, at least seven separatist fighters were killed in Esu.<ref>[http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2019-07/12/c_138218983.htm 7 separatists killed in Cameroon's troubled Anglophone region], XinhuaNet, Jul 12, 2019. Accessed Jul 12, 2019.</ref> The next day, armed men kidnapped 30 bus passengers passing through [[Belo, Cameroon|Belo]], in an apparent case of infighting among local separatist militias.<ref>[http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2019-07/13/c_138224267.htm About 30 passengers kidnapped in Cameroon's restive Anglophone region], XinhuaNet, Jul 13, 2019. Accessed Jul 14, 2019.</ref> One Cameroonian soldier and three separatists were killed in Buea on July 14,<ref>[http://french.xinhuanet.com/2019-07/15/c_138229310.htm Cameroun/Crise anglophone : un soldat et trois s\u00e9paratistes arm\u00e9s tu\u00e9s dans le sud-ouest], XinhuaNet, Jul 15, 2019. Accessed Jul 15, 2019. (French)</ref> and at least one Cameroonian soldier and at least five separatists were killed in [[Mbiame]] three days later.<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-soldier-killed-in-restive-nw-region-2/ Cameroon: Soldier killed in restive NW region], Journal du Cameroun, Jul 17, 2019. Accessed Jul 17, 2019.</ref>\n\nTowards the end of July, [[July 2019 Cameroon prison riots|two major prison riots]] took place. On July 22, separatist inmates at [[Kondengui Central Prison]] took part in staging a protest against the prison conditions. The protest escalated into a riot, which was eventually quelled violently. A similar protest and crackdown took place at Buea Central Prison a few days later.<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/camerooncalm-returns-to-buea-prison-after-protest-by-prisoners/ Cameroon:Calm returns to Buea prison after protest by prisoners], Journal du Cameroun, Jul 24, 2019. Accessed Jul 24, 2019.</ref> More than 100 inmates were moved to undisclosed locations for detention,<ref name=\"jul292019\">[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-anglophone-detainees-missing-after-kondengui-protests/ Cameroon: Anglophone detainees missing after Kondengui protests], Journal du Cameroun, Jul 29, 2019. Accessed Jul 29, 2019.</ref> some of whom were subjected to torture,<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-tortured-mancho-bibixy-ambazonia-detainees-not-dead/ Cameroon: Tortured Mancho Bibixy, Ambazonia detainees not dead!], Journal du Cameroun, Jul 29, 2019. Accessed Jul 29, 2019.</ref> and there were speculations that some had been killed during the riots. The [[Interim Government of Ambazonia]] demanded that the Cameroonian government account for the missing inmates, threatening to impose a lockdown encompassing the entire Anglophone regions if it failed to do so.<ref name=\"jul262019\">[http://cameroonnewsagency.com/ambazonia-separatist-leaders-give-govt-ultimatum-to-present-detained-prisoners/ Ambazonia Separatist Leaders Give Gov\u2019t Ultimatum To Present Detained Prisoners], Cameroon News Agency, Jul 28, 2019. Accessed Jul 28, 2019.</ref> The lockdown started on July 29.<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-ambazonia-leaders-call-for-another-lockdown-in-anglophone-regions/ Cameroon: Ambazonia leaders call for another \u2018lockdown\u2019 in Anglophone regions], Journal du Cameroun, Jul 30, 2019. Accessed Jul 30, 2019.</ref> Midnight to July 31, the ten detained members of the Interim Government, including [[Sisiku Julius Ayuk Tabe]], went on a hunger strike over the missing convicts.<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-separatist-leader-launches-hunger-strike/ Cameroon separatist leader launches hunger strike], Journal du Cameroun, Aug 1, 2019. Accessed Aug 1, 2019.</ref>\n\nOn August 4, separatist fighters ambushed and killed a soldier and his civilian driver in Penda Mboko, [[Littoral Region (Cameroon)|Littoral Region]], the second attack there since March.<ref>[http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2019-08/05/c_138284639.htm One soldier killed in rare ambush in Cameroon], XinhuaNet, Aug 5, 2019. Accessed Aug 5, 2019.</ref> On August 14, in an effort to sabotage the new school year, separatist militias announced that region-wide lockdowns would be enforced on September 2\u20136 and 9\u201313, covering the first two weeks of the academic year.<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-ambazonia-fighters-declare-lockdown-to-frustrate-school-resumption-in-anglophone-regions/ Cameroon: Ambazonia fighters declare \u2018Lockdown\u2019 to frustrate school resumption in Anglophone regions], Journal du Cameroun, Aug 14, 2019. Accessed Aug 14, 2019.</ref> On August 15, at least seven soldiers from the BIR were injured when their vehicle skidded off the road in Kumba; while separatists claimed responsibility for the incident, the army claimed it was simply a road accident.<ref>[http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2019-08/16/c_138312378.htm Seven Cameroonian soldiers injured in accident in restive Anglophone region], XinhuaNet, Aug 16, 2019. Accessed Aug 16, 2019.</ref>\n\nOn August 20, the ten detained members of the [[Interim Government of Ambazonia]], including [[President of Ambazonia|President]] [[Sisiku Julius Ayuk Tabe|Ayuk Tabe]], were sentenced to [[life imprisonment]] by the Yaound\u00e9 Military Tribunal.<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-detained-ambazonia-leaders-handed-life-sentence/ Cameroon: Detained Ambazonia leaders handed life sentence], Journal du Cameroun, Aug 20, 2019. Accessed Aug 20, 2019.</ref> This was followed by a military escalation and a series of lockdowns, crushing hopes that the school year could start as normal in early September. Within a week, violence and uncertainty had triggered tens of thousands of people to flee from the Anglophone regions.<ref name=\"voaaug262019\">[https://www.voanews.com/africa/thousands-flee-violence-cameroons-english-speaking-regions Thousands Flee Violence in Cameroon\u2019s English-Speaking Regions], Voice of America, Aug 26, 2019. Accessed Aug 26, 2019.</ref> Due to the escalation, a government-led effort to reopen at least 4,500 schools by September 2 ultimately failed.<ref>[https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-49529774 Cameroon's conflict keeps schools shut], BBC, Sep 3, 2019. Accessed Sep 3, 2019.</ref>\n\nIn September, President Paul Biya announced the [[Major National Dialogue]], a political dialogue that would be held before the end of the month.<ref name=\"Cameroon 2019. p 12\">[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-paul-biya-convenes-national-dialogue-to-solve-anglophone-crisis/ Cameroon: Paul Biya convenes national dialogue to solve Anglophone crisis], Journal du Cameroun, Sep 10, 2019. Accessed Sep 12, 2019.</ref> While separatists were quick to reject the initiative, citing the recent life sentences handed to the separatist leaders,<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/biyas-dialogue-for-cameroon-crisis-runs-into-questions-rejection/ Biya\u2019s \u2018dialogue\u2019 for Cameroon crisis runs into questions, rejection], Journal du Cameroun, Sep 11, 2019. Accessed Sep 12, 2019.</ref> opposition parties in Cameroon showed interest in the initiative and started submitting proposals.<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-matomba-submits-pre-dialogue-proposals-to-pm-dion-ngute/ Cameroon: Matomba submits pre-dialogue proposals to PM Dion Ngute], Journal du Cameroun, Sep 20, 2019. Accessed Sep 23, 2019.</ref> Meanwhile, the war continued; on September 20, separatist fighters launched a failed attack on a hotel in Bamenda where several government officials were staying.<ref>[http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2019-09/21/c_138409937.htm Cameroon's security forces repel separatists' attack on gov't officials], XinhuaNet, Sep 21, 2019. Accessed Sep 21, 2019.</ref> While the Major National Dialogue was happening, a significant number of Anglophones celebrated Ambazonia's third independence day on October 1. Nine people were killed in clashes all across the Anglophone regions that day,<ref>[https://www.voanews.com/africa/cameroon-separatists-celebrate-independence-dialogue-held Cameroon Separatists Celebrate 'Independence' as Dialogue is Held], Voice of America, Oct 2, 2019. Accessed Oct 2, 2019.</ref> while \"Field Marshall\" Lekeaka Oliver of the [[Red Dragon (Ambazonian militia)|Red Dragon militia]] used the occasion to declare himself Paramout Ruler of [[Lebialem]].<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-lebialem-traditional-rulers-disown-ambazonia-warlord-field-marshal/ Cameroon: Lebialem traditional rulers disown Ambazonia warlord Field Marshal], Journal du Cameroun, Oct 15, 2019. Accessed Oct 15, 2019.</ref> October also saw the public surrender of Ambazonian general Ekeom Polycarp, who was subsequently assassinated by other separatists.<ref>[http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2019-10/17/c_138480115.htm Key separatist commander killed after dropping weapons in Cameroon's troubled Anglophone region], XinhuaNet, Oct 17, 2019. Accessed Oct 17, 2019.</ref> The separatists also started opening \"community schools\" across the Anglophone regions, providing an alternative to the government-run schools which they had boycotted for years.<ref name=\"community schools\">[https://www.voanews.com/africa/cameroon-separatists-open-community-schools Cameroon Separatists Open 'Community Schools'], Voice of America, Oct 18, 2019. Accessed Oct 18, 2019.</ref>\n\nOn December 1, separatist fighters carried out their first attack on an airplane, firing at a [[Camair-Co]] passenger plane while it was landing at [[Bamenda Airport]]. No one was wounded in the attack, although several bullets penetrated into the cabin. This incident was the first of its kind, and possibly indicated that the separatists would take on larger government targets.<ref>[https://www.theeastafrican.co.ke/news/africa/Passenger-plane-shot-at-west-Cameroon/4552902-5370230-do3bu5/index.html Passenger plane shot at as violence escalates in west Cameroon], The East African, Dec 2, 2019. Accessed Dec 5, 2019.</ref> The AGovC announced that the airline in question often transported soldiers, and that they thus considered their aircraft to be legitimate targets.<ref>[http://cameroonnewsagency.com/attack-on-camair-co-passenger-plane-shows-nothing-is-under-control/ Attack On Camair-Co Passenger Plane Shows Nothing Is Under Control], Cameroon News Agency, Dec 1, 2019. Accessed Dec 1, 2019.</ref> The separatists also started their campaign to sabotage the upcoming [[2020 Cameroonian parliamentary election]], and within a week they abducted some 40 politicians, including two mayors and at least 19 councilors.<ref>[https://www.voanews.com/africa/cameroon-separatists-kidnap-candidates-protest-election Cameroon Separatists Kidnap Candidates to Protest Election], Voice of America, Dec 16, 2019. Accessed Dec 18, 2019.</ref> A separatist attack on a civilian truck with a military escort left some three civilians dead on December 19.<ref>[http://cameroonnewsagency.com/2-die-and-15-injured-in-ekona-attack/ 2 Die And 15 Injured in Ekona Attack], Cameroon News Agency, Dec 19, 2019. Accessed Dec 19, 2019.</ref> Cameroon also launched a series of operations in Mezam, Boyo, Donga Mantung, Bui, Ngo Ketunjia and Boyo that would, over six days, force around 5,500 people to flee their homes.<ref>[https://reliefweb.int/report/cameroon/cameroon-massive-population-displacement-north-west-flash-update-20-december-2019 Cameroon: Massive population displacement, North West: Flash update (20 December 2019)], ReliefWeb, Dec 23, 2019. Accessed Dec 24, 2019.</ref> In their respective New Year speeches on December 31, President Paul Biya of Cameroon and Samuel Ikome Sako of Ambazonia both promised to intensify the war in 2020.<ref>References:\n*[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/paul-biyas-end-of-year-message-to-cameroonians-2/ Paul Biya\u2019s 2019 end of year message to Cameroonians], Journal du Cameroun, Dec 31, 2019. Accessed Jan 1, 2019.\n*[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroonambazonia-leader-delivers-end-of-year-message/ Cameroon:Ambazonia leader delivers end of year message], Journal du Cameroun, Dec 31, 2019. Accessed Jan 1, 2019.\n</ref>\n\n===2020===\n\n{{Main|Timeline of the Anglophone Crisis (2020)}}\n\nSeparatist forces started the new year by declaring a five-day lockdown for February, intended to prevent the upcoming parliamentary election from taking place in the Anglophone regions.<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-2020-twin-polls-separatists-announce-five-day-lockdown-in-anglophone-regions/ Cameroon/2020 twin polls: Separatists announce five-day lockdown in Anglophone regions], Journal du Cameroun, Jan 3, 2019. Accessed Jan 3, 2019.</ref> Clashes took place in Buea and Muyuka, where separatists burned down the office of the Divisional Officer.<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-ambazonia-boys-set-fire-on-muyukas-d-os-office/ Cameroon: Suspected Ambazonia boys set ablaze Muyuka\u2019s D.O\u2019s office], Journal du Cameroun, Jan 3, 2019. Accessed Jan 3, 2019.</ref> On January 6, after failing to listen to demands from fellow separatists not to terrorize civilians, separatist commander \"General Divine\" was assassinated by his own men.<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroonambazonia-general-killed-by-peers-in-sw-region/ Cameroon:\u2019Ambazonia General\u2019 killed by peers in SW Region], Journal du Cameroun, Jan 6, 2020. Accessed Jan 6, 2020.</ref> Following instances of popular uprisings against the separatists in Balikumbat and Babungo, the ADF ordered its fighters to take action against anyone caught terrorizing civilians.<ref name=\"voajan82020\">[https://www.voanews.com/africa/cameroon-anglophone-villagers-attack-separatist-camps-over-abuse Cameroon Anglophone Villagers Attack Separatist Camps Over Abuse], Voice of America, Jan 8, 2020. Accessed Jan 8, 2020.</ref> January also saw what was possibly the most serious instance of separatist infighting to date; the [[Southern Cameroons Restoration Forces]] (loyal to the Interim Government) abducted 40 fighters from the Ambazonia Defence Forces, six of whom were subsequently murdered.<ref name=\"voainfightingjan\">[https://www.voanews.com/africa/cameroons-anglophone-separatists-turn-infighting Cameroon\u2019s Anglophone Separatists Turn to Infighting], Voice of America, Jan 22, 2020. Accessed Jan 23, 2020.</ref> \"General Chacha\", the separatist commander responsible for the abduction, was captured and summarily executed by Cameroonian soldiers a week later.<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-dreaded-ambazonia-general-killed-in-bui/ Cameroon: Dreaded Ambazonia General killed in Bui], Journal du Cameroun, Jan 27, 2020. Accessed Jan 27, 2020.</ref>\n\nA [[2020 Cameroonian parliamentary election|parliamentary election]] was held in February, and was marked by unprecedented escalation on both sides. Hundreds of additional troops were deployed to combat separatist attempts to sabotage the election, while the separatists abducted 120 politicians within the two weeks preceding the election. Efforts by the Cameroonian government to prevent a repeat of the debacle surrounding the 2018 presidential election ultimately failed, as the turnout in the Anglophone regions was very low. The Ambazonians, who claimed that 98 percent of the population boycotted the election, hailed this as a great victory.<ref name=\"cnafeb92020\">[http://cameroonnewsagency.com/low-turnout-frustrates-election-in-north-west-south-west-regions/ Low Turnout Frustrates Election In North West, South West Regions], Feb 9, 2020. Accessed Feb 11, 2020.</ref> The results in 11 constituencies were later nullified due to separatist activities, triggering a partial re-election in March. The results were largely the same, with a marginal turnout and clashes taking place throughout the day.<ref>[https://www.theafricareport.com/25124/cameroon-anglophone-regions-hit-by-violence-during-partial-legislative-polls/ Cameroon\u2019s Anglophone regions hit by violence during partial legislative polls], The Africa Report, Mar 26, 2020. Accessed Mar 27, 2020.</ref> Less than a week after the February election, Cameroonian soldiers and armed Fulani carried out the [[Ngarbuh massacre]], killing at least 23 civilians in Ntumbo, Northwest Region and drawing international condemnation.<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-un-wants-punishment-for-perpetrators-of-ngarbuh-killings/ Cameroon: UN wants punishment for perpetrators of Ngarbuh killings], Journal du Cameroun, Feb 18, 2020. Accessed Feb 18, 2020.</ref>\n\nOn March 7, around 20 separatist fighters carried out attacks on a police station and gendarmerie in [[Galim]], [[West Region (Cameroon)|West Region]], killing two gendarmes, two police officers and four civilians. This was the third separatist attack in West Region.<ref name=\"trtmar92020\">[https://www.trtworld.com/africa/anglophone-separatists-kill-five-soldiers-four-civilians-in-west-cameroon-34394 Anglophone separatists kill five soldiers, four civilians in west Cameroon], TRT World, Mar 9, 2020. Accessed Mar 9, 2020.</ref> The next day, an [[improvised explosive device]] killed one soldier and injured four soldiers, two police officers and one civilian in Bamenda.<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-womens-day-explosion-leaves-soldier-dead-others-injured-in-bamenda/ Cameroon: Women\u2019s Day explosion leaves soldier dead, others injured in Bamenda], Journal du Cameroun, Mar 9, 2020. Accessed Mar 9, 2020.</ref> Cameroon subsequently carried out an offensive in [[Ngo-Ketunjia]], where it claimed to have destroyed 10 separatist camps and killed at least 20 fighters, including some of those who had participated in the Galim raid.<ref>[https://en.trend.az/world/other/3211672.html 20 separatists killed in military offensive in Cameroon's troubled Anglophone region], Trend News Agency, Mar 22, 2020. Accessed Mar 22, 2020.</ref>\n\nOn March 26, SOCADEF declared a two-week ceasefire to give people time to get tested for [[Coronavirus disease 2019|coronavirus]],<ref>[https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-52053738 Cameroon rebels declare coronavirus ceasefire], BBC, Mar 26, 2020. Accessed Mar 27, 2020.</ref> a move that was welcomed by the [[United Nations]].<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-un-reacts-to-ceasefire-declared-by-ambazonia-armed-group/ Cameroon: UN reacts to ceasefire declared by Ambazonia armed group], Journal du Cameroun, Mar 27, 2020. Accessed Mar 27, 2020.</ref> The Interim Government and the AGovC declared their willingness to have their armed groups follow suit, but conditioned it on international monitoring and Cameroonian troops being confined to their bases.<ref>[https://cameroonnewsagency.com/covid19-ig-agovc-will-declare-covid19-ceasefire-only-when-all-parties-agree-to-internationally-binding-terms/ COVID19: IG, AGovC Will Declare COVID19 Ceasefire Only When All Parties Agree To Internationally Binding Terms], Cameroon News Agency, Nov 27, 2020. Accessed Nov 27, 2020.</ref> The same day as SOCADEF's unilateral ceasefire went into effect and, coincidentally, the same day as the first COVID-19 case was confirmed in the Anglophone regions, President Sako declared the shutting of Ambazonia's borders and restriction of movement and public gatherings in order to limit the spreading of the virus, effective from April 1.<ref>[https://cameroonnewsagency.com/covid-19-ambazonia-interim-government-president-shuts-down-border/ COVID-19: Ambazonia \u2018Interim Government\u2019 President Shuts Down Border], Cameroon News Agency, Mar 29, 2020. Accessed Mar 30, 2020.</ref> However, the danger posed by COVID-19 did not bring about an immediate end of hostilities on the ground; just the day before Sako's declaration, separatists attacked an armored car, killing a soldier and 11 officials, including two deputy mayors.<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-at-least-12-ambushed-by-ambazonia-forces-in-oku/ Cameroon: Dozens ambushed by Ambazonia forces in Oku], Journal du Cameroun, Mar 30, 2020. Accessed Mar 30, 2020.</ref> On April 8, responding to claims by the Cameroonian government that the war was nearing an end, separatists attacked military bases and destroyed infrastructure in villages all across the Anglophone regions.<ref name=\"voaapr92020\">[https://www.voanews.com/africa/cameroons-separatists-relaunch-attacks-reject-state-reconstruction-plan Cameroon's Separatists Relaunch Attacks to Reject State Reconstruction Plan], Voice of America, Apr 9, 2020. Accessed Apr 9, 2020.</ref>\n\n==Strategy==\n\n===Military strategy===\n\nThe Cameroonian Army is fighting a [[counter-insurgency]] war, aiming to hit the separatists' support base. This includes burning houses where weapons are found and, according to locals but denied by the army, carrying out revenge attacks.<ref name=\"Dirty War\">[https://www.nation.co.ke/news/africa/-Dirty-war--ravages-Cameroon-s-anglophone-region/1066-4546558-fs0ta9z/index.html 'Dirty war' ravages Cameroon's Buea region] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180507050007/https://www.nation.co.ke/news/africa/-Dirty-war--ravages-Cameroon-s-anglophone-region/1066-4546558-fs0ta9z/index.html |date=2018-05-07 }}, Daily Nation, May 5, 2018. Accessed May 7, 2018.</ref> In August 2018, the Defence Minister of Cameroon announced that the army would be expanded with 2,600 new recruits, 2,000 of whom would go to the BIR.<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-recruit-2600-amidst-tension-anglophone-regions/ Cameroon to recruit 2600 soldiers amidst tension in Anglophone regions] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180829214638/https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-recruit-2600-amidst-tension-anglophone-regions/ |date=2018-08-29 }}, Aug 29, 2018. Accessed Aug 29, 2018.</ref> In addition to expanding the army, the government has supported local vigilante groups, which there were more than 30 of as of October 2019.<ref name=\"xinhuavigilantes\"/> The government has also set up rehab centers in Bamenda and Buea to reintegrate separatists who have surrendered into civil society.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.voanews.com/a/cameroon-yet-to-build-planned-rehab-centers-for-ex-boko-haram-fighters/4791847.html |title=Cameroon Yet to Build Planned Rehab Centers for ex-Boko Haram Fighters |author=Moki Edwin Kindzeka |work=Voice of America |date=18 February 2019 |accessdate=27 February 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190301013317/https://www.voanews.com/a/cameroon-yet-to-build-planned-rehab-centers-for-ex-boko-haram-fighters/4791847.html |archive-date=1 March 2019 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> With no military victory in sight, the Cameroonian Army has sought to at least contain the conflict to rural areas. As of late-2018, the Cameroonian Army aimed to control all urban areas as well as strategic points on the countryside, and did not seek to recapture the entire Anglophone regions.<ref name=\"crisisgroupmay22019\"/>\n\n[[File:Weapons seized from separatist fighters in Bamenda.jpg|thumb|right|Weapons of separatist fighters in Bamenda, seized by the Cameroonian military in February 2019]]\n\nThe Ambazonian separatists are fighting a [[Guerrilla warfare|guerrilla war]]. Numerically and materially disadvantaged, the separatists carry out [[Hit-and-run tactics|hit-and-run attacks]], [[ambush]]es and [[Raid (military)|raids]]. According to the ADF, as of June 2018 there were 1,500 soldiers in the ADF, spread across 20 camps throughout Southern Cameroons.<ref name=EmmanuelFreudenthal/> In May 2019, independent sources measured the total number of separatist fighters to be between 2,000 and 4,000, a figure that included numerous ex-soldiers and ex-policemen, a significant number of female combatants, and dozens of Nigerian mercenaries. The Nigerians among the rebels mostly consisted of criminals and ex-insurgents who had previously taken part in the [[conflict in the Niger Delta]].<ref name=\"crisisgroupmay22019\"/>\n\nAt the start of the war, the separatists struggled with gaining access to firearms, having to rely on [[Rifle|hunting rifles]] and in some cases single-shot pistols. As the war went on, they gradually gained limited access to some more sophisticated weapons, capturing some from the Cameroonian Army and buying some in Nigeria (where they enjoyed the support of officers in the Nigerian Army). They also benefitted from fundraising campaigns, launched by diaspora activists to purchase guns for the separatist militias. This began to yield visible results in the first half of 2019.<ref name=\"goinginternational\">[https://foreignpolicy.com/2019/05/13/cameroons-separatist-movement-is-going-international-ambazonia-military-forces-amf-anglophone-crisis/ Cameroon\u2019s Separatist Movement Is Going International], Foreign Policy, May 13, 2019. Accessed May 14, 2019.</ref> From being severely outgunned in the fall of 2018,<ref name=\"viceoct2018\">[https://news.vice.com/en_us/article/qvajj3/inside-cameroons-bloody-war-over-the-english-language Inside Cameroon's bloody war over the English language], VICE News, Oct 1, 2018. Accessed Jun 19, 2019.</ref> by the summer of 2019 the separatists had become well-armed.<ref name=\"voajun192019\">[https://www.voanews.com/africa/cameroon-war-victims-casualty-figures-high-because-fighters-are-well-armed Cameroon War Victims: Casualty Figures High Because Fighters Are Well Armed], Voice of America, Jun 19, 2019. Accessed Jun 19, 2019.</ref> They also declared that they had started producing their own weapons within Southern Cameroons, a declaration followed shortly by an explosion in Mamfe that killed four policemen.<ref name=\"producingownweapons\">[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroonexplosion-kills-four-policemen-restive-anglophone-region/ Cameroon:Explosion kills four policemen in restive Anglophone region], Journal du Cameroun, Jun 16, 2019. Accessed Jul 8, 2019.</ref>\n\nThe militias enjoy significant local support, with civilians giving them food, informing them on troop movements, or outright assisting them in carrying out attacks.<ref name=\"BBCoct42018\">[https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-45723211 Cameroon's Anglophone crisis: Red Dragons and Tigers \u2013 the rebels fighting for independence] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181004145026/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-45723211 |date=2018-10-04 }}, BBC, Oct 4, 2018. Accessed Oct 4, 2018.</ref> The Interim Government of Ambazonia has stressed that the war will take place solely within Southern Cameroons, and claims that attacks across the border have been [[false flag]] operations by the Cameroonian government.<ref>[https://www.bareta.news/interim-government-warns-cameroun-against-propagating-inter-citizen-war-between-both-cameroons/ Interim Government Warns Cameroun Against Propagating Inter-Citizen War Between Both Cameroons] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181226084435/https://www.bareta.news/interim-government-warns-cameroun-against-propagating-inter-citizen-war-between-both-cameroons/ |date=2018-12-26 }}, Bareta News. Accessed Dec 25, 2018.</ref> In March 2019, the ADF announced that it would take the war into the French-speaking parts of Cameroon, defying the Interim Government.<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-three-gendarmes-injured-as-suspected-ambazonia-fighters-attack-littoral-region-again/ Cameroon:Three gendarmes injured as suspected Ambazonia fighters attack Littoral region again] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190402151300/https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-three-gendarmes-injured-as-suspected-ambazonia-fighters-attack-littoral-region-again/ |date=2019-04-02 }}, Journal du Cameroun, Apr 2, 2019. Accessed Apr 2, 2019.</ref>\n\nUnlike most Cameroonian soldiers deployed in the region, the separatists are locals, and are thus more familiar with the terrain. Cameroonian General Melingui stated that the separatists have a leverage over the army when it comes to familiarity with the battleground; \"They know the terrain. These are youths from local villages. We try to seek them out but we can't find them. Our men aren't familiar with the forest.\" Cameroonian authorities have admitted that they have little control over the security situation outside the cities.<ref name=\"Dirty War\"/> Journalist Emmanuel Freudenthal, who spent a week with ADF rebels in 2018, stated that the separatists control much of the countryside because the infrastructure in Southern Cameroons is so poorly developed, making it hard for the Cameroonian government to access those areas.<ref name=EmmanuelFreudenthal>[http://en.rfi.fr/africa/20180614-cameroon-i-spent-week-embedded-anglophone-armed-separatists Cameroon: I spent a week embedded with Anglophone armed separatists] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180614222031/http://en.rfi.fr/africa/20180614-cameroon-i-spent-week-embedded-anglophone-armed-separatists |date=2018-06-14 }}, RFI, Jun 14, 2018. Accessed Jun 14, 2018.</ref>\n\nAGovC leader in exile [[Ayaba Cho Lucas]] summed up the ADF strategy in the following way: \"60% of the GDP of Cameroon is earned in Ambazonia. [...] We must try to raise the cost of the occupation to higher than the profits they get here.\"<ref name=thisisagenocide/>\n\nRetired American diplomat [[Herman Jay Cohen]] has argued that Cameroon's military approach to the conflict plays straight into the separatist strategy. Drawing parallels to the [[Eritrean War of Independence]], he has claimed that the growing bitterness resulting from prolonged warfare will only serve to close the window of opportunity where reconciliation and territorial integrity is still an option, thereby - ironically - increasing the likelihood of Ambazonian secession.<ref>[https://www.cfr.org/blog/lessons-past-cameroons-crisis Lessons From the Past on Cameroon\u2019s Crisis], Council on Foreign Relations, Jan 3, 2019. Accessed Jan 5, 2019.</ref>\n\n===Political, diplomatic and propaganda strategy===\n\nAccording to Millan Atam, chairperson of the Southern Cameroonians Congress of the People, the separatists are building up support for their cause through two distinct phases. The first phase was to build internal capability to resist the Cameroonian Army and raise faith in the cause. Once a significant portion of the population of Southern Cameroons clearly wanted separation, the separatists would approach the international community with their cause.<ref>[http://www.thedailyvox.co.za/black-on-black-colonialism-the-divide-between-francophone-cameroon-and-anglophone-ambazonia-nolwandle-zondi/ Black-On-Black Colonialism: The Divide Between Francophone Cameroon And Anglophone Ambazonia] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180608004454/http://www.thedailyvox.co.za/black-on-black-colonialism-the-divide-between-francophone-cameroon-and-anglophone-ambazonia-nolwandle-zondi |date=2018-06-08 }}, The Daily Vox, Jun 4, 2018. Accessed Jun 5, 2018.</ref>\n\nThe Cameroonian government has tried to limit the extent of which the conflict affects everyday life in Southern Cameroons, and portrays the war as a battle between chaos and stability in which the government represents the latter. To this end, local authorities have penalized businesses that respected \"ghost towns\" declared by the separatists.<ref>[http://www.africanews.com/2018/07/22/cameroon-warns-buea-businesses-don-t-obey-ghost-town-orders-from-separatists/ Cameroon mayor warns Buea businesses over ghost towns on Mondays] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180823141920/http://www.africanews.com/2018/07/22/cameroon-warns-buea-businesses-don-t-obey-ghost-town-orders-from-separatists/ |date=2018-08-23 }}, Africa News, Jul 22, 2018. Accessed Aug 23, 2018.</ref> The government has fired and replaced local administrators who fled from the region, despite their fears of kidnappings.<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/biya-appoints-new-batibo-do-sacks-runaway-administrators-in-anglophone-regions/ Biya appoints new Batibo DO, sacks runaway administrators in Anglophone regions] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180920234424/https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/biya-appoints-new-batibo-do-sacks-runaway-administrators-in-anglophone-regions/ |date=2018-09-20 }}, Journal du Cameroun, Sep 20, 2018. Accessed Sep 20, 2018.</ref> In September 2018, the army physically prevented people from fleeing their homes.<ref>[https://africa.cgtn.com/2018/09/16/cameroon-intercepts-families-from-fleeing-war-torn-anglophone-region/ Cameroon intercepts families from fleeing war-torn Anglophone region] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180916171051/https://africa.cgtn.com/2018/09/16/cameroon-intercepts-families-from-fleeing-war-torn-anglophone-region/ |date=2018-09-16 }}, CGTN Africa, Sep 16, 2018. Accessed Sep 16, 2018.</ref>\n\nIn August 2018, [[Ministry of Territorial Administration (Cameroon)|Minister of Territorial Administration]] Atanga Nji offered amnesty to separatists who surrender their weapons, saying they would \"be received as prodigal sons\". The minister also announced a plan to rebuild infrastructure that had been destroyed due to the conflict.<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/future-not-bushes-minister-atanga-nji/ Your future is not in the bushes- Minister Atanga Nji] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180823005857/https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/future-not-bushes-minister-atanga-nji/ |date=2018-08-23 }}, Journal du Cameroun, Aug 22, 2018. Accessed Aug 22, 2018.</ref>\n\nBoth sides have used [[WhatsApp]] to spread propaganda.<ref name=\"Dirty War\"/> Cameroonian authorities have arrested journalists on the accusation of propagating false information, the punishment for which is six months to two years in prison.<ref>[https://www.voanews.com/a/cameroon-journalist-jailed-in-anglophone-unrest/4650515.html Cameroon Journalist Jailed in Anglophone Unrest] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181109234807/https://www.voanews.com/a/cameroon-journalist-jailed-in-anglophone-unrest/4650515.html |date=2018-11-09 }}, Voice of America, Nov 8, 2018. Accessed Nov 9, 2018.</ref>\n\n== War crimes ==\n\n===By Cameroon===\n\nThere is photographic evidence that shows a consistent strategy of burning down villages. The army has claimed that the soldiers who were filmed were separatists wearing stolen Cameroonian Army uniforms, a claim that has been denied by local residents. Satellite images show extensive damage to villages. Journalists have been denied entry to the conflict zones, and soldiers have been forbidden from carrying mobile phones.<ref name=burning>[https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-44561929 Burning Cameroon: Images you're not meant to see] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180919204526/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-44561929 |date=2018-09-19 }}, BBC, Jun 25, 2018. Accessed Jun 25, 2018.</ref> In August 2018, the [[Centre for Human Rights and Democracy in Africa]] published a list of 106 villages that had been raided by government forces since October 2017. Citing eyewitness accounts, videos and photos as evidence, the Centre claimed that 71 of these villages had been completely destroyed and depopulated, while the remaining 34 had been partially deserted.<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/chrda-publishes-shocking-list-military-atrocities-cameroons-nw-sw-regions/ CHRDA publishes shocking list of military atrocities in Cameroon\u2019s NW, SW regions] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180822132046/https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/chrda-publishes-shocking-list-military-atrocities-cameroons-nw-sw-regions/ |date=2018-08-22 }}, Journal du Cameroun, Aug 22, 2018. Accessed Aug 22, 2018.</ref>\n\n===By Ambazonia===\n[[File:Government Bilingual High School in Fontem, South West Cameroon.jpg|thumb|right|A destroyed bilingual high school in [[Fontem]].]]\n\nAt the end of 2017, the separatists declared a school boycott, and have attacked and burnt down schools that refused to shut down. Between February 2017 and May 2018, at least 42 schools were targeted.<ref name=burning/> Some separatists consider schools to be legitimate targets because the French language is taught as a mandatory subject.<ref name=EmmanuelFreudenthal/> As of July 2019, close to 6,000 schools had shut down across the Anglophone regions, affecting more than 600,000 children.<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/6000-schools-shut-down-in-restive-anglophone-cameroon/ 6000 schools shut down in restive Anglophone Cameroon], Journal du Cameroun, Jul 30, 2019. Accessed Jul 30, 2019.</ref> In October 2019, separatists began opening their own schools.<ref name=\"community schools\"/>\n\nIn their effort to make the Anglophone regions ungovernable, separatist elements have maimed employees at state-owned corporations.<ref name=\"Cameroon 2019\">[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-armed-men-chop-off-fingers-of-cdc-workers/ Cameroon: Armed men chop off fingers of CDC workers], Journal du Cameroun, Jan 3, 2019. Accessed Jan 3, 2019.</ref> Kidnapping for ransom has also occurred frequently,<ref>[https://reliefweb.int/report/cameroon/schools-fail-open-cameroons-restive-english-speaking-regions Schools Fail to Open in Cameroon's Restive English-speaking Regions] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180904230919/https://reliefweb.int/report/cameroon/schools-fail-open-cameroons-restive-english-speaking-regions |date=2018-09-04 }}, Reliefweb, Sep 4, 2018. Accessed Sep 4, 2018.</ref> as well as blackmailing of civilians into transferring money to fund the struggle.<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-anglophones-forced-to-fund-secessionist-conflict/ Cameroon anglophones \u2018forced to fund\u2019 secessionist conflict], Journal du Cameroun, Jul 17, 2019. Accessed Jul 17, 2019.</ref> Owing to the obscure nature of many of the separatist militias (see [[List of Ambazonian militant groups|list]]), some attacks attributed to separatists may as well be the acts of local criminals. Notwithstanding, it is beyond doubt that separatist elements have carried out numerous such acts,<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-human-rights-watch-accuses-ambazonia-separatists-of-kidnappings/ Cameroon: Human Rights Watch accuses Ambazonia separatists of kidnappings], Journal du Cameroun, Jul 13, 2019. Accessed Jul 13, 2019.</ref> sometimes drawing condemnation from the Interim Government of Ambazonia.<ref name=\"Cameroon 2019\"/>\n\nThroughout 2017, there were no reports of ADF using violence against civilians. As of October 2018, five such incidents had been reported, though these attacks were for the most part not lethal; one civilian death was attributed to an ADF attack. Other separatist groups had attacked civilians 25 times within the same time frame, and were responsible for 13 civilian deaths.<ref name=\"acleddatapickingafight\"/> Separatists have also been accused of using schools and churches as military barracks;<ref>[https://www.christianpost.com/news/churches-turned-into-military-barracks-people-killed-cameroon-christians-cry-out.html Churches turned into military barracks, people killed: Cameroon Christians cry out] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181206162200/https://www.christianpost.com/news/churches-turned-into-military-barracks-people-killed-cameroon-christians-cry-out.html |date=2018-12-06 }}, The Christian Post, Dec 6, 2018. Accessed Dec 6, 2018.</ref> in July 2019, Cameroon accused the separatists of occupying more than 50 schools.<ref>[https://www.voanews.com/africa/cameroon-separatist-fighters-occupy-50-schools Cameroon: Separatist Fighters Occupy 50 Schools], Voice of America, Jul 22, 2019. Accessed Jul 23, 2019.</ref>\n\n==Casualties==\n\nBetween September 2017 and February 2018, Cameroon claimed to have lost 22 soldiers and policemen in the conflict.<ref>[https://ewn.co.za/2018/02/09/we-are-in-a-war-cameroon-unrest-confronted-by-army-offensive 'We are in a war': Cameroon unrest confronted by army offensive], Eyewitness News, Feb 8, 2018. Accessed Jul 23, 2019.</ref> By May, at least 44 soldiers and policemen had been killed.<ref name=\"unfoldingcatastrophe\"/> In June 2018, the official figure rose to 84 dead.<ref>[https://www.reuters.com/article/us-cameroon-separatists/separatists-have-killed-84-troops-since-sept-2017-cameroon-idUSKBN1JG360 Separatists have killed 84 troops since Sept. 2017: Cameroon], Reuters, Jun 20, 2018. Accessed Jul 23, 2019.</ref> Within two weeks in the later half of June, the official figure went up to more than 120 dead.<ref name=100deadvoa/> By October 2018, the military and police had lost at least 175 servicemen. Separatist losses were estimated to be in the hundreds.<ref name=\"reliefweboct10\">[https://reliefweb.int/report/afghanistan/atrocity-alert-no-126-10-october-2018-afghanistan-cameroon-and-democratic Atrocity Alert No. 126 (10 October 2018): Afghanistan, Cameroon and Democratic Republic of the Congo], Relief Web, Oct 10, 2018. Accessed Nov 7, 2018.</ref>\n\nThe war intensified in early 2019. By June, Cameroonian military and police casualties were estimated to be around 500 dead. The separatists had lost around 1,000 fighters.<ref name=\"unfoldingcatastrophe\">[https://www.raoulwallenbergcentre.org/newsfeed/2019/6/4/release-of-landmark-report-on-unfolding-catastrophe-in-cameroon Cameroon-unfolding catastrophe\u2019 evidence of human rights violations and crimes against humanity], Centre for Human Rights and Democracy in Africa (CHRDA), Jun 3, 2019.</ref> While civilian casualties are hard to determine, in May 2019 they were estimated by independent sources to be around 650 killed.<ref name=\"crisisgroupmay22019\">[https://www.crisisgroup.org/africa/central-africa/cameroon/272-crise-anglophone-au-cameroun-comment-arriver-aux-pourparlers Cameroon\u2019s Anglophone Crisis: How to Get to Talks?], Crisis Group, May 2, 2019. Accessed May 2, 2019.</ref> In January the same year, the [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Kumbo|Diocese of Kumbo]] had been able to document 385 civilian deaths in Kumbo alone within the past seven months.<ref>[http://cameroonnewsagency.com/kumbo-diocese-documents-385-deaths-in-7-months/ Kumbo Diocese Documents 385 Deaths In 7 Months], Cameroon News Agency, Mar 29, 2019. Accessed Oct 29, 2019.</ref> In September 2019, independent sources stated that the conflict had claimed the lives of around 3,000 people, counting both combatants and civilians.<ref name=\"3000killed\">[https://www.crisisgroup.org/africa/central-africa/cameroon/cameroons-anglophone-dialogue-work-progress Cameroon\u2019s Anglophone Dialogue: A Work in Progress], CrisisGroup, Sep 26, 2019. Accessed Oct 28, 2019.</ref> By February 2020, between 800 and 1,000 Cameroonian soldiers had been killed.<ref name=\"newhumanitarianfeb62020\"/>\n\nAnglophone groups have disputed these figures. While federalist movements claimed that the conflict had taken 3,000\u20135,000 lives as of the summer of 2019, separatists claimed that between 5,000 and 10,000 people had been killed.<ref name=\"unfoldingcatastrophe\"/>\n\n==Humanitarian consequences==\nBy January 2018, 15,000 people had fled from Southern Cameroons to Nigeria.<ref name=Africa/> This number increased to at least 40,000 people by February.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.africanews.com/2018/02/14/cameroon-separatists-claim-to-have-abducted-missing-soldier/|title=Cameroon separatists claim to have abducted missing soldier|website=Africa News|date=14 February 2018|accessdate=23 April 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180421162750/http://www.africanews.com/2018/02/14/cameroon-separatists-claim-to-have-abducted-missing-soldier/|archive-date=21 April 2018|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> By August 2018, more than 180,000 people had been displaced due to the war.<ref name=atrisk230818>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroons-anglophone-population-risk/ Cameroon\u2019s Anglophone population at risk] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180823122945/https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroons-anglophone-population-risk/ |date=2018-08-23 }}, Journal du Cameroun, Aug 23, 2018. Accessed Aug 23, 2018.</ref> As of May 2019, 530,000 people had been internally displaced, and 35,000 had fled to Nigeria.<ref name=\"crisisgroupmay22019\"/> In June 2019, [[UNICEF]] said that 1.3 million people in the Anglophone regions needed humanitarian aid.<ref>[https://www.unicef.org/press-releases/geneva-palais-briefing-note-situation-children-north-west-and-south-west-regions Geneva Palais briefing note on the situation for children in the North-West and South-West regions of Cameroon], UNICEF, Jun 21, 2019. Accessed Jul 8, 2019.</ref>\n\n== Other consequences ==\nThe conflict has severely harmed the local economy. In June 2018, Cameroon Development Corporation, a state-owned company with 22,000 employees, declared the conflict could lead to the loss of 5,000 jobs on the short term.<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-anglophone-crisis-could-cost-5000-jobs/ Cameroon: Anglophone crisis could cost 5,000 jobs] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180619012714/https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-anglophone-crisis-could-cost-5000-jobs/ |date=2018-06-19 }}, Journal du Cameroon, Jun 18, 2018. Accessed Jun 18, 2018.</ref> In July 2018, Cameroonian NGO ''Human Is Right'' reported that the war had caused a 70 percent increase in unemployment in the agricultural sector. The palm oil and cocoa sectors in Southwest Region had taken a severe blow, with state-owned company Pamol abandoning plantations in some areas. The private company Telcar Cocoa reported that the cocoa production had fallen 80 percent. The NGO suggested that companies make deals with the separatists in order to safeguard their facilities.<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroons-palm-oil-cocoa-sectors-worst-hit-crisis/ Cameroon\u2019s palm oil, cocoa sectors worst hit by crisis] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180719123106/https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroons-palm-oil-cocoa-sectors-worst-hit-crisis/ |date=2018-07-19 }}, Journal du Cameroun, Jul 19, 2018. Accessed Jul 18, 2018.</ref> The separatists aim to prevent the Cameroonian state from getting any income from the Anglophone regions, in order to make cost of controlling the region surpass the benefits.<ref name=thisisagenocide/>\n\nThe conflict has triggered an exodus of the Nigerian business community from Southern Cameroons, as well as Nigerian traders who used to run key markets.<ref>[https://qz.com/1322709/cameroons-anglophone-crisis-sees-nigerian-business-community-flee-as-ambazonia-forces-strike/ Cameroon\u2019s Nigerian business community is fleeing as the Anglophone crisis deepens] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180709153727/https://qz.com/1322709/cameroons-anglophone-crisis-sees-nigerian-business-community-flee-as-ambazonia-forces-strike/ |date=2018-07-09 }}, Quartz, Jul 7, 2018. Accessed Jul 9, 2018.</ref>\n\nThousands of displaced people have fled to protected natural areas, endangering the wildlife there.<ref>[http://africanarguments.org/2018/07/12/cameroon-crisis-threatens-wildlife-people-flee-protected-areas/ Cameroon crisis threatens wildlife as thousands flee to protected areas], African Arguments, Jul 12, 2018. Accessed Jul 12, 2018.</ref>\n\n==Reactions==\n[[File:Southern Cameroonians We Did.JPG|thumb|right|Southern Cameroonian expats marching in support of the Ambazonian cause]]\n\n===Within Cameroon===\n\nThe Anglophone Crisis has become a divisive question in Cameroonian politics. The [[Cameroon People's Democratic Movement]] (CPDM), the ruling party, regards the separatists as terrorists and supports a military solution to the conflict.<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-defence-minister-says-terrorirsts-will-not-be-freed/ Cameroon\u2019s Defence minister says \u201cterrorists\u201d will not be freed] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190327195906/https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-defence-minister-says-terrorirsts-will-not-be-freed/ |date=2019-03-27 }}, Journal du Cameroun, Dec 14, 2018. Accessed Mar 27, 2019.</ref> The CPDM supported both the carrying out and conclusion of the [[Major National Dialogue]], which was organized by the Cameroonian government.<ref name=\"Cameroon 2019. p 12\"/>\n\nMeanwhile, the opposition has been vocal in its criticism of the government's handling of the conflict. In January 2019, the [[Social Democratic Front (Cameroon)|Social Democratic Front]] announced it would oppose any future elections in the country while the war is still ongoing. The party supports a negotiated solution to the conflict, and has demanded a ceasefire, the opening of a dialogue, amnesty for everyone jailed because of the crisis, the establishment of a [[truth and reconciliation commission]], and decentralization of the country.<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/no-elections-in-cameroon-if-anglophone-crisis-persists-sdf-warns-biya/ No elections in Cameroon if Anglophone crisis persists, SDF warns Biya] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190128191136/https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/no-elections-in-cameroon-if-anglophone-crisis-persists-sdf-warns-biya/ |date=2019-01-28 }}, Journal du Cameroun, Jan 22, 2019. Accessed Jan 28, 2019.</ref> In March 2019, the SDF accused members of the Cameroonian government of supporting certain armed elements in the Anglophone regions.<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-sdf-suspects-biya-regime-of-sponsoring-ambazonia-fighters/ Cameroon: SDF suspects Biya regime of sponsoring Ambazonia fighters] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190327194549/https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-sdf-suspects-biya-regime-of-sponsoring-ambazonia-fighters/ |date=2019-03-27 }}, Journal du Cameroun, Mar 27, 2019. Accessed Mar 27, 2019.</ref> In May 2019, the SDF announced it would boycott [[National Day (Cameroon)|National Day]] celebrations in sympathy with people in Southern Cameroons living in a state of civil war.<ref name=\"nationalday2019\">[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-sdf-to-boycott-may-20-celebrations/ Cameroon: SDF to boycott May 20 celebrations], Journal du Cameroun, May 8, 2019. Accessed May 8, 2019.</ref>\n\nSmaller opposition parties, such as the [[Cameroon Renaissance Movement]] (MRC), also blame the government for failing to solve the Anglophone Crisis.<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-maurice-kamto-announces-nationwide-protests-on-january-26/ Cameroon: Maurice Kamto announces nationwide protests on January 26] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190128191123/https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-maurice-kamto-announces-nationwide-protests-on-january-26/ |date=2019-01-28 }}, Journal du Cameroun, Jan 16, 2019. Accessed Jan 28, 2019.</ref> On January 26, 2019, supporters of the MRC invaded the Cameroonian embassy in Paris, citing \u2013 among other reasons \u2013 the Anglophone Crisis.<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/protesters-invade-cameroon-embassies-abroad/ Protesters invade Cameroon embassies abroad] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190128135442/https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/protesters-invade-cameroon-embassies-abroad/ |date=2019-01-28 }}, Journal du Cameroun, Jan 27, 2019. Accessed Jan 28, 2019.</ref> In May 2019, the MRC joined the SDF in boycotting National Day celebrations.<ref name=\"nationalday2019\"/> The Cameroon People's Party has taken a nuanced approach, condemning both the government and the separatists. Party leader [[Kah Walla]] has said that the crisis can be solved by turning Cameroon into a federation.<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-kah-walla-rubbishes-separatist-threats-insists-only-federation-can-solve-anglophone-crisis/ Cameroon: Kah Walla rubbishes separatist threats, insists Federation can solve Anglophone crisis] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190422024152/https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-kah-walla-rubbishes-separatist-threats-insists-only-federation-can-solve-anglophone-crisis/ |date=2019-04-22 }}, Journal du Cameroun, Apr 22, 2019. Accessed Apr 22, 2019.</ref>\n\n===Countries and international organizations===\n{{Main|International reactions to the Anglophone Crisis}}\n\nThe Anglophone Crisis has become a diplomatic challenge to Cameroon, and has damaged the country's relations with some of its allies. While member states of the [[African Union]]<ref name=\"AU\">[https://taarifa.rw/2018/07/12/african-union-intervenes-in-cameroon-crisis/ African Union Intervenes In Cameroon Crisis], Taarifa, Jul 12, 2018. Accessed Jul 12, 2018.</ref> and [[France]]<ref name=\"Arria\">[http://webtv.un.org/live-now/watch/arria-formula-meeting-of-the-un-security-council/6036271424001/?term= Arria-Formula Meeting of the UN Security Council], United Nations, May 13, 2019. Accessed Jul 8, 2019.</ref> have taken either a neutral stance or sided with the Cameroonian government, several European countries and the [[United States]] have criticized Cameroon.<ref name=\"FalloutsUN\">[https://www.hrw.org/news/2019/06/28/africa-should-not-fail-cameroon Africa Should Not Fail Cameroon], Human Rights Watch, Jun 28, 2019. Accessed Jul 8, 2019.</ref> The United States have been particularly vocal in its criticism; In July 2019, following a fact-finding mission by some of its members to the country, the [[United States House of Representatives|House of Representatives]] called for a reintroduction of a federal system in Cameroon.<ref>References:\n*[https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/116/hres358/text H.Res. 358: Calling on the Government of Cameroon and armed groups to respect the human rights of all Cameroonian citizens, to end all violence, and to pursue a broad-based dialogue without preconditions to resolve the conflict in the Northwest and Southwest regions.], [[GovTrack]], Jul 23, 2019. Accessed Jul 25, 2019.\n*{{cite web| url = https://reliefweb.int/report/cameroon/cameroon-north-west-and-south-west-crisis-situation-report-no-9-31-july-2019| title = Cameroon: North-West and South-West Crisis Situation Report No. 9 - As of 31 July 2019| date = September 3, 2019| website = [[ReliefWeb]]| access-date = September 26, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2019, Switzerland announced that both the Cameroonian government and the separatists had asked it to act as a mediator, and that negotiations would take place. This would be the first known case of talks between the two warring sides, and has been met with international endorsement.<ref>[https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-ambazonia-leaders-agree-to-participate-in-swiss-led-dialogue/ Cameroon: Ambazonia leaders endorse Swiss-led dialogue to solve Anglophone crisis], ''Journal du Cameroun'', Jun 28, 2019. Accessed Jun 28, 2019.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Ongoing military conflicts}}\n{{Post-Cold War African conflicts}}\n\n[[Category:2010s conflicts]]\n[[Category:2020s conflicts]]\n[[Category:Conflicts in 2016]]\n[[Category:Conflicts in 2017]]\n[[Category:Conflicts in 2018]]\n[[Category:Conflicts in 2019]]\n[[Category:Conflicts in 2020]]\n[[Category:2010s in Cameroon]]\n[[Category:Wars of independence]]\n[[Category:Wars involving Cameroon]]\n[[Category:History of Cameroon]]\n[[Category:History of Ambazonia]]\n[[Category:Anglophone Crisis| ]]\n", "name_user": "Mikrob\u00f8lgeovn", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anglophone_Crisis"}
